<html>
<head><title>Summary - Flat Tax</title></head>
<body>
<center>
<font size=5><b>FREEDOM &amp; FAIRNESS RESTORATION ACT<br> 
OF 1995 (Flat Tax) - Summary <br> </font>
<font size=4>H.R. 2060, S. 1050<br></b></font>
<hr>   
(This analysis  is an excerpt from &quotA Side By Side Analysis   
of Alternative Tax System Proposals&quot; 
published  August 1, 1995 by <a href="/savers/legislation/blc.html">The Business 
Leadership Council</a>.)   
   <br>
<hr>
</center>
<b>Sponsors:</b> Mr. Armey and Mr. Shelby<br>   
   <p>
<b>Basic Principles:</b>  The plan is based on the principles set   
forth in &quot;The Flat Tax&quot; by Robert E. Hall and   
Alvin Rabushka (2nd Ed., 1995).  The plan has an individual   
wage tax and a business tax imposed on all   
forms of business which allows the deduction of &quot;business   
inputs&quot; but not taxes, fringe benefits, interest and dividends.   
   <p>
Unlike a value added tax, wages are deductible to the firm   
and the employee is taxed on his wages (after a   
generous standard deduction and dependent exemption).  The   
proposal would have a comprehensive   
consumption tax base.   
   <p>
<b>Rate Structure, Individuals:</b>  20 percent flat tax rate for   
1996, 17 percent thereafter on wages.   
   <p>
<b>Tax Base, Generally:</b>  Individual taxable income is defined   
as wages, retirement distributions and   
unemployment compensation less the standard deduction and   
the dependent exemptions.   
   <p>
<b>Interest, Dividends and Other Investment Income and Expense: 
</b>
Investment income is neither taxable   
to the recipient nor deductible to the payor.   
   <p>
<b>Municipal Bond Interest:</b> Municipal bond interest would not   
be taxable.   
   <p>
<b>Standard Deduction Family Living Allowance: </b> The standard   
deduction would be:   
   <p>
$21,400 for a joint return or surviving spouse;   <br>
$14,000 for a head of household;   <br>
$10,700 for a single person or married couple filing   
separately.   <br>
   <p>
<b>Personal Exemption:</b> None.   
   <p>
<b>Dependent Exemption:</b> $5,000 per dependent.   
   <p>
<b>Capital Gains:</b>  Not taxed on financial instruments.  Gross   
proceeds from real and personal property are   
included in income.  Basis existing prior to enactment of   
the flat tax is not deductible against gross   
revenue from the sale of property.   
   <p>
<b>Home Ownership:</b>  The home mortgage interest deduction is   
repealed.  Capital gains from the sale of a   
home would not be taxed.   
   <p>
<b>State and Local Taxes:</b>  State and local taxes are not   
deductible.   
   <p>
<b>Estate and Gift Taxes:</b>  The unified estate and gift tax is   
repealed.   
   <p>
<b>Pensions, IRAs, and Other Qualified Plans:</b>  Receipts from   
qualified plans by individuals would generally be taxable.   
   <p>
<b>Compensation (Wages & Salaries): </b> Wages would be taxable to   
the employee and deductible to the business.   
   <p>
<b>Charitable Contributions:</b>  Charitable contributions would   
not be deductible.   
   <p>
<b>Educational Expenses:</b>  Educational expenses would not be   
deductible.   
   <p>
<b>Savings, Generally:</b>  The return to savings would not be   
taxed.   
   <p>
<b>Inflation Indexing: </b> The dependent exemption and standard   
deduction are indexed for inflation.   
   <p>
<b>Social Security Benefits:</b>  Social Security benefits are   
exempt.
<p>
<hr>
