<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Member Biographies -- TRC
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Grace-Marie Arnett">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Grace-Marie Arnett">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center>
<h2>Abbreviated Biographies of the TRC Members</h2>
</center> 
<P><br>
<hr>
<P>
<blockquote>
<a name="Kemp"></a>
<B><b>Jack Kemp</b>, Commission Chairman,</B> is Co-Director of <a href="/empower/">Empower
America</a>, a Washington, D.C. public policy and advocacy organization
he co-founded in 1993 with William Bennett, Jeanne Kirkpatrick
and Vin Weber.  Prior to founding Empower America, Kemp served
for four years as Secretary of <a href="http://www.hud.gov/">Housing and Urban Development</a>.
 Before his appointment to the Cabinet, Kemp was a Republican
candidate for President of the United States, and he represented
the Buffalo, New York, area for nine terms in the <a href="http://www.house.gov">U.S. House of
Representatives</a>.  He came to Congress after 13 years as a professional
football quarterback, playing for the <a href="http://nflhome.com/teams/chargers/chargers.html">San Diego Chargers</a> and <a href="http://nflhome.com/teams/bills/bills.html">
Buffalo Bills</a>.
<P>
<a name="Feulner"></a>
<B>Edwin J. Feulner, Jr., Commission Vice Chairman,</B> is president
of the <a href="/heritage/">Heritage Foundation</a>, a leading conservative public policy
group based in Washington, D.C.  He also serves as Chairman of
the Institute for European Defense and Strategic Studies, in London.
 Feulner, who has a Ph.D. from the <a href="http://www.ed.ac.uk/">University of Edinburgh</a>, has
extensive experience in public service and policy, having served
as Consultant for Domestic Policy to <a href="http://gopher.nara.gov:70/1/inform/library/reagan">President Reagan</a>, and as
an advisor to other government departments and agencies.
<P>
<a name="Adams"></a>
<B>Loretta H. Adams, Commissioner,</B> is President of Market
Development, Inc., a full-service consumer, marketing and opinion
research firm based in San Diego.  The company, founded by Adams
in 1978, has more than 100 employees and is devoted exclusively
to conducting research among Latin American/Latin American-origin
consumers in the United States and Latin America.  
<P>
<a name="Blackwell"></a>
<B>J. Kenneth Blackwell, Commissioner,</B> is the Treasurer of
the <a href="http://www.odn.ohio.gov/ohio/index.htmlx">State of Ohio</a>.  A former ambassador to the <a href="http://www.un.org">United Nations</a>
Commission on Human Rights and Deputy Under Secretary of the U.S.
<a href="http://www.hud.gov">Department of Housing and Urban Development</a>, Blackwell first served
in public office on the Cincinnati City Council, then as Mayor
of Cincinnati.  He is a member of the Council on Foreign relations
in New York, and a former independent public policy consultant
and writer.
<P>
<a name="Cain"></a>
<B>Herman Cain, Commissioner,</B> is Chairman and CEO of Godfather's
Pizza, Inc.  He assumed the presidency of Godfather's Pizza in
1986, after being selected for the position by the pizza chain's
parent, The Pillsbury Company.  In 1988, he successfully led a
group of Godfather's Pizza senior management in purchasing the
chain from Pillsbury.  Prior to his tenure at Godfather's, Cain
worked with the <a href="http://www.navy.mil">U.S. Navy</a>, <a href="http://www.cocacola.com">Coca-Cola</a>, and Burger King.
<P>
<a name="Campbell"></a>
<B>Carroll Campbell, Commissioner,</B> is President and CEO of
the American Council of Life Insurance.  He is the former Governor
of <a href="http://www.state.sc.us/">South Carolina</a>, serving two four-year terms.  Campbell launched
is political career in 1970, when he was elected to the South
Carolina House.  He later served in the State Senate, until he
was elected to the first of four terms in the <a href="http://www.house.gov">U.S. House of Representatives</a>.
 While in Congress he served on both the Appropriations and Ways
and Means Committees.
<P>
<a name="du Pont"></a>
<B>Pete du Pont, Commissioner,</B> is Policy Chairman of the <a href="http://www.shoponline.com/ncpa/">National
Center for Policy Analysis</a>, and Director in the Wilmington, Delaware,
law firm of Richards, Layton &amp; Finger.  He has served as a
state legislator, U.S. Congressman, Governor and in 1988 was a
Republican candidate for President of the United States.  du Pont
writes a weekly column, distributed by <a href="http://www.scripps.com">Scripps Howard News Service</a>
and is a featured columnist in <I>CEO</I> Magazine.
<P>
<a name="Faris"></a>
<B>Jack Faris, Commissioner,</B> is President and CEO of the National
Federation of Independent Business (NFIB), the nation's largest
small business advocacy organization with more than 600,000 members.
 Reared in a small business family in Florida, Faris has served
in a variety of banking positions and also owned his own marketing
and management consulting firm for 12 years, working primarily
with small and independent businesses.
<P>
<a name="Fong"></a>
<B>Matt Fong, Commissioner,</B> is <a href="http://www.treasurer.ca.gov/">Treasurer</a> of the State of California.
 He is the highest-ranking elected official in the continental
United States of Asian ancestry.  Prior to becoming State Treasurer,
Fong was Vice Chairman of the State Board of Equalization.  A
graduate of the <a href="http://www.usafa.af.mil">U.S. Air Force Academy</a> who served five years in
the military, his background includes starting a small business
and serving as an attorney.
<P>
<a name="Forstmann"></a>
<B>Theodore J. Forstmann,</B> <B>Commissioner,</B> is a founding
partner of the private investment firm, Forstmann Little &amp;
Co.  The firm has acquired 20 companies since founded in 1978.
Forstmann Little's limited partners in these investments are primarily
a small group of blue-chip corporate pension funds and individual
investors that provide both equity and subordinated debt financing.
 Forstmann is Chairman of Gulfstream Aerospace corp., owned by
Forstmann Little &amp; Co.
<P>
<a name="Kleckner"></a>
<B>Dean Kleckner, Commissioner,</B> is President of the <a href="http://www.fb.com">American
Farm Bureau Federation</a> (AFBF), a post he has held since 1986.
 Prior to becoming AFBF president, he was president of the Iowa
Farm Bureau for 10 years.  Kleckner operates a 350-acre corn,
soybean and hog farm near Rudd, Iowa.  He serves on a top-level
U.S. Trade Advisory Committee, first appointed by President Reagan
and reappointed by President Bush, and since then reappointed
by President Clinton.
<P>
<a name="Peterson"></a>
<B>Shirley D. Peterson, Commissioner,</B> is President of <a href="http://www.hood.edu">Hood
College</a> in Frederick, Maryland.  Prior to assuming the college
presidency, she was Commissioner of the <a href="http://www.irs.ustreas.gov">Internal Revenue Service</a>
and Assistant Attorney General (Tax Division) at the United States
<a href="http://www.usdoj.gov">Department of Justice</a>.   She has served as a private tax attorney
and is a principal of the Council on Excellence in Government
in Washington, D.C.
<P>
<a name="Snow"></a>
<B>John W. Snow, Commissioner,</B> is Chairman, President and
CEO of CSX Corporation of Richmond, Virginia. He has been with
the company since 1977, and prior to working for CSX Corporation
was the Deputy Undersecretary of the <a href="http://www.dot.gov">U.S. Department of Transportation</a>,
a private attorney and college professor.
<P>
<a name="Weiland"></a>
<B>John Wieland, Commissioner,</B> is President of John Wieland
Homes, Inc., of Atlanta, Georgia.  His company has more than 600
full-time employees and hundreds of subcontractors.  In the past
four years, the company has expanded its business to three other
southern states.  Also involved in providing housing for the working
poor, Wieland is a former member of the International Board of <a href="http://www.students.uiuc.edu/~jwyckoff/HfH.html">
Habitat for Humanity</a>.
<P>
<h3>Staff of the Commission</h3>
<P>
<B>Grace-Marie Arnett</B>, president of Arnett &amp; Co., is executive
director of the Tax Reform Commission. Ms. Arnett has operated
her own consulting firm for eleven years, specializing in policy
analysis.  She also serves as a senior associate with the Domestic
Policy Issues Program at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies.  
<P>
<B>Alan Reynolds</B>, senior fellow and director of economic research
at the Hudson Institute</a>, is the research director for the Tax
Reform Commission. Mr. Reynolds was formerly chief economist with
Polyeconomics, vice president of the First National Bank of Chicago,
senior economist with Argus Research, and economics editor of
<I>National Review</I>.    
<P>
<B>Rich Myers, </B>a public relations consultant, is public affairs
director for the Tax Reform Commission.  He has extensive media
experience, particularly in the area of tax policy.  Mr. Myers
served as a public affairs spokesman at the U.S. Department of
Treasury and as communications director for the National Taxpayers
Union.    
<P>
Staff support is provided by <B>Elizabeth Kern</B>, <B>Scott Sundstrom</B>,
<B>Gilbert Pringle</B>, <B>Melinda Schriver</B>, and <B>Brian
Pleva.</B>
<P><P>
