seems to me that you could take your show on the road around this 
country.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER WIELAND</b>:  We're going to.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  There are any number of ways that 
you can attempt to get your message across that will bolster what 
we're trying to do here.<p> 
 
		In the end, I can see Jack on <b>Meet the Press</b> and on 
<b>This Week with Brinkley</b> and on <b>Face the Nation</b>  when you reach 
your conclusions.  There are any number of ways that we're going 
to be able to get this message across.  But it <p> 
 
is --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  I'm too shy to do those shows.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  What?<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  I'm too shy to do those shows.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Yeah -- oh.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		But -- and I didn't mean to select those to --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  -- to eliminate others -- 
<b>McNeil/Lehrer</b> and all the others.  <p> 
 
		But we do have build consensus.  And the first thing we 
have to do is build a consensus within our majority in the 
Congress.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		Well, what we're trying to do is inventory the problems 
which you have addressed yourself to quite eloquently, Bill -- 
inventory the solutions.  And we hope you'll come back --<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  I will.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  -- in perhaps the early fall and talk 
about the Archer bill.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  I will.  I will.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Senators Nunn and Domenici are both on 
their way, I've just been informed.  <p> 
 
		But let me take a question and prerogative of the 
Chair.<p> 
 
		You did mention, in passing, that four members of our 
Commission could not be here, all of whom were appointed by the 
Speaker and the Majority Leader of the Senate, Bob Dole.<p> 
 
		Loretta Adams is an entrepreneur -- an impresario, an 
Hispanic businesswoman from <p> 
 
San Diego.<p> 
 
		Governor du Pont, an old buddy of yours, is Carroll's 
counterpart.<p> 
 
		And Teddy Forstmann, of Forstmann, Little, one of our 
Nation's outstanding entrepreneurs and financiers.<p> 
 
		And John Snow, chairman of CSX. <p> 
 
		In my opening comment, I quoted President Kennedy, who 
said, in '62, that the paradox of tax reform is that many times 
high rates cause less revenue.  <p> 
 
		And setting the rates at a level of equilibrium at 
which people are willing to maximize their output and still pay 
tax in a peacetime economy is really going to take a Solomon-like 
decision.  Albeit in a democracy, there will be give and take.<p> 
 
		One of the questions I have for you, Mr. Chairman, is, 
if a principle --<p> 
 
		(End tape 1, side 1)<p> 
 
		-- for a government's legitimate purposes, a corollary 
to that, or secondary to that principle, is upon whom should the 
burden of that tax be placed?<p> 
 
		I don't think there's any -- I watched you and Charlie 
Rangel go toe to toe.  And he's a friend of yours and a good 
friend of mine.  		And he kept bringing up the issue -- I'm 
not speaking for him, but it's an issue that all of us have to 
address in this debate, "fairness."<p> 
 
		We wouldn't tax a teenager who's starting out in life.  
We wouldn't tax an apprentice starting his or her first rung of 
the ladder that we euphemistically call <i>the American Dream</i>, but 
you reminded us today is a "universal" dream.  <p> 
 
		How do we adjust the Code -- i.e., the rate -- so that 
the burden falls on those most able to pay, but in such a way as 
it does not reduce their ability to save, invest, and work, and 
take that risk that is so important to the creation of wealth?<p> 
 
		As a principle, what is in your mind about making sure 
that the weakest elements of our society -- the woman coming off 
of welfare, taking her first job -- how do you make sure that a 
sales tax, if it is a consumption tax, is not placed in such a 
way as those with the least amount of disposable income in our 
society are paying too heavy a burden?<p> 
 
		I don't say that to argue.  I say that to raise issues 
--<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  No, I understand.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  -- that I know are going to be raised 
by our colleagues in this great democratic -- small "d" -- 
debate.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Well -- and we must be prepared to 
come to grips with that issue.  That is a very, very big issue.  
And it's one that we struggle with here, in the Congress, over 
and over and over again.  <p> 
 
		It, in a sense, is one of the big conundrums as to how 
we tax; because on the one hand. we say those who are able to pay 
the most should pay the most.  And I don't think people will 
argue with that.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  But what is "the most"?  <p> 
 
		And what is the relative incline in taking assets away 
from those who are in a position to create jobs?<p> 
 
		It takes, today, $280,000 per job of invested capital 
in the United States.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  How much?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  $280,000.<p> 
 
		Now, Jack, your members probably would not spend that 
much in small businesses, but that's the average across the 
board.<p> 
 
		Now, $280,000, in the minds of those who want to tax 
wealth, is a large amount of money.  <p> 
 
		So, if you adopt the concept that we have got to take a 
big chunk away from someone who has $280,000 to invest, you're in 
effect destroying jobs.<p> 
 
		So the conundrum is:  How do you continue the savings 
and invested capital to create the better-paying job, to increase 
real family income in the paychecks, and at the same time say, 
"Well, we're really going to hit those people"?  <p> 
 
		And we have never found a valid answer to that over the 
years, I don't think, in this country.  <p> 
 
		But the one thing that we do know is no matter how we 
manipulated the Code by those who would socially engineer it, we 
have not changed the basic percentage of ownership of wealth in 
this country.  We have not succeeded in redistributing wealth.  <p> 
 
		It may sound good from a rhetorical standpoint on a 
political stump, but the reality is that it has not worked.<p> 
 
		But one interesting thing, which you know better than 
anybody else, is when the rates were reduced in 1986 -- and that 
was the benefit of the '86 Act, in spite of all of the bad parts 
of it -- the people in the very highest income effectively paid 
more, with a lower rate, of the percentage of the money that came 
in to fund the federal government. <p> 
 
		Now, that doesn't fit within the political rhetoric of 
those who always want to sic the poor against the rich and the 
rich against the poor, in creating economic class struggles in 
this country.<p> 
 
		But so long as we have a democracy with a free 
enterprise, capitalistic society, we're going to need people who 
have wealth to create jobs.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Of course, that top <p> 
 
10 percent changes every 20 years.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  And that's true, too.  I mean, 
that's also true of these distribution tables on which all of our 
proposals are judged, that what does this do for this income 
class, acts as if people stay in that income class all of their 
lives, and they don't.  <p> 
 
		We know the studies show that Americans are moving up 
and down the ladder every year, and that's the secret in this 
country.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Do you have a minute or two to take a 
couple more questions?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Yes, if you've got a minute or two 
to listen to long answers.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Well, Nunn and Domenici are on their 
way. <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Okay.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  They were on the floor of the Senate 
when I got word that they were walking over.  So. I'll let them. <p> 
 
		Raise your hands if you have -- <p> 
 
		Governor Campbell -- Carroll.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		Mr. Chairman, the issue of equity and fairness often is 
in the way it's explained.  <p> 
 
		If you had a 20 percent flat tax and you told somebody 
that "Somebody who made $200,000 is going to pay a $40,000 tax; 
and if you make $20,000, you're going to pay a $4,000.  Is that 
fair?" -- they'd probably all say, "Yeah, that's fair."<p> 
 
		Oftentimes it's not explained in, you know, exactly 
those terms.  And so when you look at the tax from a flat tax 
standpoint, then I think you could explain the equity of it.<p> 
 
		The other thing that I was very interested in -- and 
you kept going back to --was the creation of the capital base in 
the country, which we have to have, which has got to come from 
people's savings, long-term savings.  <p> 
 
		And I guess that comment let's me have a segue into 
what we're doing today to keep the government from growing back.  <p> 
 
		And I speak of the headlines in papers about baby 
boomers not preparing for the future, not ready for the future, 
and things like that <p> 
 
-- and as to whether we should address that as an incentive need.  
<p> 
 
		All of these things deal with the equity.  And the 
reason that one deals with equity is if they don't prepare, 
you're going to have to tax somebody else more to take care of 
them in the future.  <p> 
 
		And I think that's all part of what we're doing.  I 
don't mean to overstate that.  <p> 
 
		I guess the one thing that I wanted to ask you, from 
the consumption tax standpoint, you made the comment about states 
and the conflict, and that was raised.  There actually is, in the 
system today, another layer of that taxation.<p> 
 
		And one is simple.  You have a state sales tax.  Then, 
in many instances, you have a county sales tax.  And in many 
instances, you have a city sales tax or a tax on things.  <p> 
 
		So that tiered system is there at different levels of 
government.  I'm not so sure it would be as difficult as some 
have raised the specter of.  <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Well, I do think that the fairness 
and the regressivity concern is an important one.  And it has 
been raised by a couple of you, and I share that concern.  <p> 
 
		And I think when you do get into the very lower-income 
people -- first, let me say that if you put a tax on good and 
services, the Social Security recipient, the retired person who 
is living off their Social Security benefits, would immediately 
be made whole by <p> 
 
the COLA.  So, there would be no disadvantage to a retired person 
on Social Security.  <p> 
 
		If you are at the very bottom and you're on welfare, 
you would be made whole by an increase in your welfare benefits 
that would keep pace with the CPI.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Mm-hmm.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Now, the question though, then, is 
when you get above the threshold of being on welfare and you're 
in a lower income category as a worker, I think we do have to be 
concerned about some credit rebate or waiver system that would 
not punish those people.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Bill, you've really done us a great 
service.<p> 
 
<center>*  *  *</center> 
<p> 
<a href="#CONTENTS">CONTENTS</a>
<center><b><a name="Senator Sam Nunn">Senator Sam Nunn</a></b></center> 
<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  I congratulate you on taking this job, 
because I don't know of any job that's more challenging, but also 
has more potential for really accomplishing something for 
American people and the future income and economic growth of our 
country.<p> 
 
		Mr. Chairman, you're right.  You and I started in the 
tax business together about the same time.  You were out in front 
of me, I think, you and Bill Roth.  And then I came trailing in 
about 1978.  But I've been involved a long time.  		<p> 
 
		And I never will forget when we passed a resolution in 
the Senate urging the Finance Committee and the Ways and Means 
Committee to basically -- well, actually, we passed the bill in 
the Senate called the "Nunn-Chiles bill" and you passed a 
resolution.  <p> 
 
		You came back on a flight and passed a resolution in 
the House to urge the House conferees to accept it, which had 
already passed the Senate two-thirds.  Your vote passed by <p> 
 
two-thirds.  Lo and behold, the Conference kicked the whole thing 
out and put in some language. <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  That was about 1978.  And I always 
contended to President Carter -- at that time President Carter -- 
that had the administration supported it at that time, the 1980 
election might have been different, because that was a 
fundamental point in our history.  But I wanted to --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>: I will resist a comment on that.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  I don't think he agreed either.   <p> 
 
		But, Mr. Chairman, Senator Domenici is coming in just a 
few minutes.  And I thought I'd lead off just with a few informal 
remarks.  I would like to have had a statement prepared, but I've 
been caught between the Defense markup -- in fact, we're meeting 
now.  So, I'm going to make my remarks brief.  <p> 
 
		And then Senator Domenici will probably come in, in the 
middle.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Okay.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  We just had a vote on a securities 
matter.<p> 
 
		The fundamental point of economic policy, we believe -- 
Senator Domenici and I, and I think we see this alike -- is to 
promote the long-term growth and a higher standing of living in 
the American people.<p> 
 
		Now, the growth and higher standard of living of our 
country depend on productivity, depend on our people being more 
productive.  And that increased productivity depends on increased 
investment.  <p> 
 
		And increased investment depends on fundamental 
savings.  And that is the heart of what we're talking about.  And 
we believe that's the heart of what's wrong with our Tax Code 
today.  <p> 
 
		Because without savings, you don't get investment.  
Without investment, you don't get productivity.  And without 
productivity, you do not get the kind of increases in our 
standard of living and economic growth that we all, I think, 
desire.<p> 
 
		The bottom line is that savings relates directly to 
jobs, and higher-paying jobs, because it all goes together.  <p> 
 
		So, what we set out to do was to address that 
fundamental problem that affects our economic growth and also the 
pay of the American worker.<p> 
 
		The U.S. national savings rate is very low, as we all 
know.  That trend started in the 1970s, but continues to this 
day.  <p> 
 
		We've had about 20 years of much lower savings.  And it 
is demonstrated very vividly in all the charts on investment and 
certainly those charts where we're compared to Japan, but not 
just Japan.  Almost any country in the world, or any industrial 
country is out-saving us and out-investing us.<p> 
 
		And, of course, the economists tell us that national 
investment equals national savings, plus, of course, imported 
capital.  And we've gotten our investment primarily because we 
have imported capital over the last two decades.<p> 
 
		Now, the question is:  Why do we have such low savings?  
<p> 
 
		I don't sit here before this tax panel and try to 
contend that it's all related to the Tax Code.  I think that's a 
fundamental part of it, but it's also cultural, and it also 
relates to the overall budget deficit.  <p> 
 
		We're trying to address that budget deficit, but it 
fundamentally cuts into our savings, our net savings as a Nation.<p> 
 
		The Tax Code today, Mr. Chairman -- and you ask, in the 
letter:  What's wrong with our current Code?  <p> 
 
		And, of course, if the American people come to the 
conclusion that we do need to change the Tax Code, it will be 
because they believe there are fundamental problems with it. <p> 
 
		So, what's wrong with our Tax Code today?<p> 
 
		Senator Domenici and I believe that the fundamental 
problem with our Tax Code is that it taxes savers twice and it 
taxes investors twice.  It taxes consumers once.<p> 
 
		So, naturally the laws of economics and incentives mean 
that if you are taxed twice if you save, but once if you consume, 
there is more incentive to consume than to save. <p> 
 
		We're trying to level the playing field.  We're trying 
to say that savers are basically not penalized, that there's no 
bias against savings in the Tax Code.  That was our fundamental 
goal.<p> 
 
		The corporate level also demonstrates that, in effect, 
corporate earnings are taxed twice.  They're taxed once at the 
company level; and when they're distributed as dividends, they're 
taxed again.<p> 
 
		And, of course, if the corporate rate is higher than 
the individual rate, people in lower brackets who are investors 
are taxed at a higher rate at the corporate level than they would 
be taxed if the money was distributed directly to them to begin 
with.<p> 
 
		So, both the business side and the individual side we 
believe are biased against people who save.<p> 
 
		We have a number of goals.  But when we get down to the 
question of what is the effect of savings, I think it has been 
said many times in many different reports.<p> 
 
		The most recent one I've read -- <p> 
 
Martin Feldstein had an editorial in the <b>Economist</b> magazine last 
week that said "Save and Prosper."   <p> 
 
		In fact, high-savings countries have high rates of 
investment, whereas low-savings countries have low rates of 
investment.<p> 
 
		Lots of people have said pretty much the same thing.  
And I think the evidence is pretty overwhelming.  <p> 
 
		So, our goals were several.  <p> 
 
		The first -- the first goal was that we believe that 
any tax system should be designed, as far as possible, to finance 
the real needs of government with the least damage to economic 
growth.  <p> 
 
		I suppose it's hard to find any tax that promotes 
economic growth.  Some are worse than others.  And what we think 
we ought to try to do is design a tax system that does the least 
harm to economic growth.<p> 
 
		A second goal was to remove the bias against savers -- 
I've already alluded to that <p> 
 
-- allowing savings and investment to move to the place where 
they make the most sense, as dictated by the market and by free 
decisions of free people.                                  <p> 
 
		The third goal is to reduce the complexity of the Tax 
Code.  And that means to have understandable principles.  This 
reducing complexity has been the goal of almost every tax reform 
movement that I know anything about.  It never seems to happen.  <p> 
 
		But at the very least, we ought to make the principles 
of the Tax Code understandable, and we ought to strive for 
simplicity.	<p> 
 
		I don't think we ought to strive so much for simplicity 
that we ignore economic effect and that we ignore the basic 
fairness element.  But I do think simplicity ought to be a 
fundamental part of the goal.<p> 
 
		The fourth goal that we had in our proposal was to try 
modernize the American tax system based on the competitive 
reality of the world.  We don't have a level playing field now.  		We actually have a tax system that 
puts us at a 
disadvantage vis-a-vis the Europeans and Japanese and other 
competitors.  In effect, they have a value-added tax to finance a 
great portion of their government.  So, goods in their country 
that are exported, they get a rebate.  They are not taxed, 
basically.<p> 
 
		Our goods carry with them abroad the tax system of our 
country and the tax rates of our country.  <p> 
 
		On the other hand, when we ship good to Europe or 
Japan, those goods are taxed with their value added.  Now, when 
they ship goods here, they don't have a similar tax.<p> 
 
		So, we're trying to level the playing field 
competitively.  That's another very important goal.  <p> 
 
		The way we address that -- and there may be other ways 
-- but we found this one to be the most satisfying, at least from 
our perspective -- is that our tax is territorial.  It applies to 
all sales on U.S. soil, no matter where the business is 
headquartered.  <p> 
 
		If you're headquartered in New York or you're 
headquartered in California or you're headquartered in Georgia, 
your goods that are sold in the American market under our 
proposal would be taxed at the same rate as goods that are made 
in England or Germany or France or Mexico or South Korea that are 
imported into this country.<p> 
 
		So, we have a territorial tax.  It is border 
adjustable.  And that would put us on the same level playing 
field with Japan and Europe and others.  <p> 
 
		That is to say if an American company is located in 
Europe and sells outside the United States, they would not be 
taxed.  We'd get rid of a huge amount of complexity if the sales 
are outside the United States or a subsidiary.  <p> 
 
		On the other hand, if they are located in another 
country, Mexico or anywhere else, and they are producing there 
and shipping back into this country, their goods are taxed 
exactly as if they were made in the United States, and we would 
indeed have a level playing field.<p> 
 
		Some of our trading partners may raise a complaint 
about this.  We believe it's <p> 
 
GATT-compliant.  We've structured it to be <p> 
 
GATT- compliant.  We think that's important.<p> 
 
		But nevertheless, we think that a level playing field, 
in this day of competition and international competition, is 
essential for the American businesses.<p> 
 
		The final goal that I will mention this morning is that 
it be perceived as fair.  <p> 
 
		I think a tax system can be defined as working if it 
promotes economic growth and raises a standard of living to the 
American people.  But if it's going to endure, it's going to have 
to be fair.  <p> 
 
		You can pass a bill, might even get it signed into law, 
but it will not last if the American people come to the 
conclusion that it is not fair.  <p> 
 
		That's the hard part.  It's hard to blend fairness and 
simplicity.  Those two sometimes work apart.<p> 
 
		The way we tried to approach the fairness issue, we 
kept progress rates.  I know there'll be disagreement on that.  <p> 
 
		You could take our system and you could make flat rates 
of it if you wanted.  We believe that progress rates, though, in 
this system, where savings are fundamentally deducted, where you 
deduct your savings, you deduct your investment before you pay 
your tax, the marginal rate takes on a totally different nature 
than the marginal rate now, where you have not been able to 
deduct savings.<p> 
 
		So, we kept progressive rates, but we fundamentally, we 
think, changed the equation on the effect of those progressive 
rates on investment and on savings.<p> 
 
		We also have a family living allowance which does not 
exist under the current Tax Code.  We kept the standard 
deduction, so you get an extra standard -- you get an extra 
family living allowance, recognizing that low-income people are 
not going to be able as much as <p> 
 
higher-income people.  That's just a fact of life.<p> 
 
		We strengthened the earned-income tax credit.  We 
increased that so that we make it more enticing and give more 
incentive for people to work, rather than the other way around.  <p> 
 
		There would be a larger earned income tax credit.  We 
know there are some problems in administering that, and we don't 
ignore those, but we think that, still, that principle is 
absolutely essential.<p> 
 
		And then, finally -- and I'll close with this, Mr. 
Chairman -- we believe the most regressive part of our current 
Tax Code is the FICA tax, the employee and employer Social 
Security and Medicare tax.  <p> 
 
		In effect, it's regressive because it cuts off -- most 
of it cuts off at $60,000.  Low-income people pay a higher 
proportion of their income for FICA taxes than higher-income 
people.  It also is a tax on jobs.  <p> 
 
		We know if you want to get rid of anything, you tax it 
enough.  Well, we've got a big tax on jobs in this country.  And 
I think that is one of the biggest impediments that <p> 
 
low-income and low-skilled American people face is that FICA tax 
that every employer looks at before they hire someone.  They're 
talking about another 14 percent.<p> 
 
		So, what we do is we calibrate our rates so that the 
employee gets a full credit back against their income tax -- not 
a deduction, but a credit back against their income tax, dollar 
for dollar, for the FICA taxes paid.  The same thing for the 
employer.  <p> 
 
		We believe that feature should be incorporated in any 
tax code that you come up with.<p> 
 
		I know you want to have some dialogue.  I don't know 
whether my colleague, <p> 
 
Senator Domenici, is here or not.  But I will just close with 
those very scattered remarks and invite your comments and 
questions.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Well, Senator, thank you very much for 
that eloquent testimony. <p> 
 
		I'd like to take the prerogative of the Chair and turn 
it over, for the first question, to your constituent, John 
Wieland of Atlanta Georgia, one of our Nation's most productive 
homebuilders.  <p> 
 
		And, John, take it away.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER WIELAND</b>:  It has been suggested that a 
fundamental change in the income tax might not last for long, 
that the income tax after that change is going to continue to 
grow back to perhaps what we know it today.<p> 
 
		How can you -- how can we be sure that we made a tax 
and kept an income tax, that that wouldn't happen?<p> 
 
		<b>PARTICIPANT</b>:  That it would not simply be repealed, is 
that what you --<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER WIELAND;</b>  Yes.  And it wouldn't grow back, 
you know, in an effort raise taxes, whatever the White House 
thinks is appropriate.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Well, I believe that's one of the 
problems and challenges with a flat tax, because if you get rid 
of all the deductions with a flat tax and then get the rate down 
in exchange for that -- we have only to look at the Act of '86.  <p> 
 
		What happens is the rates start going back up, but you 
still don't get your deductions back.  I think that's a real a 
problem.<p> 
 
		We kept what we considered to be the essential 
deductions that we believe the American people want and will 
demand over a period of time.  <p> 
 
		We kept the deduction for home mortgages, and we kept 
the deduction for charities in our proposal.  <p> 
 
		We do eliminate a number of other deductions.  You can 
eliminate any number of deductions -- current deductions you'd 
like in a Code and you can lower the rate to do that.  <p> 
 
		But if you do that one time and you get rid of all of 
them and then people come back and raise the rate, then you have 
a real disincentive. <p> 
 
		We believe that once you put in law that savings and 
investment are deducted at the individual level, that that 
deduction will remain.  We believe that will be so clearly 
understood and will be such a driving force in the economy, that 
that one will not be subject to change.<p> 
 
		A future Congress might decide they want a higher rate.  
But if you keep the basic premise that a person that takes $100 
and puts it in a bank account or $1,000, they get to deduct that 
before they pay their taxes, I believe there would be strong 
support for that one that it would not change, because it would 
be perceived to allow people to be building for their future.<p> 
 
		The other thing that I think is so important here -- as 
we reform the entitlement programs, we all know, as we sit here, 
there is no way in the world we're going to be able to keep the 
Social Security system the way it is today for people who are now 
20, 30, 40 years old.  <p> 
 
		We can protect those who are already retired, and we 
should, or those who are about to retire.  But the people in 
their 20s and 30s and 40s are going to have to retire at a higher 
age.  I don't think there's any doubt about that.<p> 
 
		We believe that tax reform goes with entitlement 
reform, because people are going to have to be -- and younger 
people particularly are going to have to be given an ability to 
save money over a period of time so they can augment the 
retirement programs that will hopefully still exist when they get 
there.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Dean Kleckner, on the far left.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER KLECKNER</b>:  Senator, it seems to me that 
the debate, as we go on through the year, will center on tax 
change or tax reforms that focus on social policy, on fear of the 
government -- fear of the tax collection process itself, IRS, and 
economics -- with economics probably ending up third in that 
triumvirate, where it should be first.<p> 
 
		What -- and I like -- I agree with many things you said 
here.  I like the thrust that you and Senator Domenici are 
talking about.  <p> 
 
		But what can we do?  What advice do you have for us -- 
because we're going to be talking not only back to you, but to 
the American people -- to bring economics more to the forefront 
and get away from the social agenda, which you can't ever 
eliminate, and the fear of the government, fear of the IRS, which 
I think is rising -- the fear of the government is rising amongst 
the American people.  <p> 
 
		What do we do, what do we focus on to bring it to the 
economic agenda? <p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  That's a tough question. and I wouldn't 
presume to be able to give you a complete answer on that.  <p> 
 
		I would say that I believe we have a Tax Code that is 
so complex today that the people who are administering it in the 
IRS don't understand it themselves.  <p> 
 
		And if they don't understand it, the average person out 
there on the firing line in the IRS -- or at least if there are 
fundamental features they don't understand, then the way they 
administer it is going to be perceived by the people that they're 
dealing with, the public, as being both ill-informed and unfair.  
And I think there's a growing sense of that.<p> 
 
		So, I believe the Congress of the United States and 
this Commission will be making recommendations to the Congress of 
the <p> 
 
United States and to the President -- next President.  <p> 
 
		I believe that you have a real opportunity here to try 
to come up with some clarity; because if the IRS can't understand 
it, no one else can.  <p> 
 
		And I think that it's really almost unfair to the 
Internal Revenue Service agents out there.  Far be it from me to 
defend them.  I know that's not politically correct to defend the 
IRS, and I'm not going to do it here today.  		But I 
would say that they, themselves. will tell you, when you talk to 
them privately, there's lots of this Code that they can't 
understand themselves, or that it's so complex they're not 
capable of explaining it to people.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Jack Faris, an old friend of yours, of 
NFIB.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FARIS</b>:  Senator, we thank you for your 
leadership.  You've been working on this for a while, as you 
mentioned earlier, and we thank you for that.<p> 
 
		Yet, one of the things that concerns the small business 
owners around the country is: "I'm spending my life building into 
a business and building a company and building a reputation, 
taking less out and putting more in, to build something for my 
family."  The whole area of inheritance and the state taxes.<p> 
 
		We hope we'll save the family farm, ranch, and 
business, and the jobs located in those businesses.  <p> 
 
		Does your proposal include the elimination of those 
inheritance taxes or exempts the smaller, privately owned company 
to be able to be passed down to the family and employees?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Our proposal does not touch anything but 
the income tax.  We don't pretend to have addressed the estate 
tax.  <p> 
 
		I personally, individually -- and I'm not speaking for 
the group that came up with this proposal or for Senator 
Domenici, but I believe he shares this.  <p> 
 
		I think if we keep our current Internal Revenue Code 
that we have now, we have to increase the estate tax exemption 
for small businesses.  I think it has to be updated.  So, I don't 
favor the present estate tax with the present Code.<p> 
 
		We have to be careful in this proposal, though, because 
in this proposal, if you take -- if you make $100,000 and you 
save 20 of that, that money is deferred.  Eventually you're going 
to pay taxes on it.  <p> 
 
		But if you keep that invested, you will never pay taxes 
on it.  And then you pass away, you die, and at that stage there 
has to be some incidence of taxation.  So, we would not abolish 
the estate tax.  <p> 
 
		I don't think abolishing the estate tax plus this 
deferred tax on savings and investment would go together.  I 
think that would be a conflict, because then you would have not 
just a deferral of tax, you would have tax that would never -- I 
mean, you'd have income that would never be taxed. <p> 
 
		So, under the current Code, I favor reforming the 
estate tax.  I hope we can make a fundamental reform, which would 
mean the estate tax could then be modernized based on the new 
system.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Matt Fong.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSION FONG</b>:  Senator Nunn, in the different 
consumption proposals, yours seems to -- your use of the tax 
initiative seems to have a degree of preference for the tax-exempt market that the others do not.  Can you 
explain your --<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  For the -- for the what?<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FONG</b>:  Tax-exempt market.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Like municipals and --<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FONG</b>:  Municipals, yes.	<p> 
 
		Can you explain your rationale for giving a preference 
for this, that the others have not done so?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  I haven't studied the other tax 
proposals on that feature.  But financing local government and 
state government is a key part of our overall responsibilities.  
We don't want to do something at the federal level that wrecks 
the local and state government ability to finance.<p> 
 
		Now, what we do, by letting you put money in a savings 
account, the earnings on -- and that's deductible -- we level the 
playing field somewhat with municipal and state bonds.  <p> 
 
		But we still give a preference to municipal and state 
bonds by saying that the income off of those -- let's say you get 
$5,000 a year off of your municipal bonds, that income, even if 
you consume it, would not be taxed. <p> 
 
		We believe under the Constitution and under our system 
of state government, local government, and federalism, that we 
should not do something at the federal level that's going to 
cripple the ability of state and local governments to raise 
money.<p> 
 
		And we think that preference would still be enticing to 
people for investment purposes.  In effect, people who invest in 
those bonds are paying taxes.  They're paying taxes by a lower 
rate.  They are, in effect, subsidizing state and local 
government by taking a rate that would be lower than they would 
otherwise receive.<p> 
 
		That's a hard concept to explain, but I think it's 
true.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER</b>:  Senator Nunn -- <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Excuse me, waiting to testify and with 
a short time is our friend Dick Armey, the Majority leader of the 
House.<p> 
 
		So, if Pete Domenici cannot make it, Sam, when you 
finish, we will then have Dick Armey.  And I would ask that the 
questions be as brief as possible so we can get to Dick.<p> 
 
		Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER</b>:  Thank you very much for being here, 
Senator Nunn.	<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Thank you.	<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER</b>:  You explained your approach and how it 
leveled the global playing field.  <p> 
 
		One of my concerns is, with a major change, using 
either one of the approaches that's on the table, how do we 
adjust for the fact that a large percentage of the population 
will not be at the same starting point?<p> 
 
		You know, you've got some that are much further behind 
in this whole equation, and you start talking about incenting 
(sic) savings when you've got a group of people who are not even 
at the same starting point.  How does your approach address the 
inequity there?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Well, as I mentioned, the FICA Tax 
rebate would make a huge difference for low-income people.  <p> 
 
		It would also make a big difference for small 
businesses that really need to expand but can't afford to add 
another 14 percent to the minimum wage, plus whatever they're 
paying.  <p> 
 
		So, those two features I think are important.<p> 
 
		We also keep the rates progressive, so that if someone 
for very -- we're not trying to tax wealth as long as wealth as 
long as wealth is working for jobs -- for all of us.<p> 
 
		But if I'm a borrower, and I don't save any money, but 
someone else is saving money, that person saving money helps me, 
because I'm going to be able to borrow at less interest rate than 
I otherwise would.  <p> 
 
		So, I think that concept is important.  		I 
would also say that we would help grow the economy.  I believe 
the economic pie is going to grow when savings increase and 
investments increase.  And therefore I think the job growth is 
going to be here.<p> 
 
		We also have another feature that I did not emphasize 
today that addresses the human capital need.  And that is the 
$2,000 deduction per person for higher education or for skilled 
training.  <p> 
 
		We think all of those features are important.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Carroll or Shirley.    		 
<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  One quick question.  And --		<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Let me add one other thing on that 
point.  <p> 
 
		But right now a person in, let's say, a modest-income 
bracket -- middle-income -- middle-, low-income -- they have a 
very hard time saving money.  <p> 
 
		We think our proposal would allow them to save money 
and get that capital that they need to begin small businesses, or 
for education or health purposes, or whatever they need.  <p> 
 
		Right now they have a very difficult time saving 
because they're paying taxes before they are able to put away 
savings.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Carroll Campbell.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  Senator, very briefly, you 
mentioned that younger people must be given encouragement and 
ability to save.  Do you treat long-term savings any different in 
yours than short-term savings?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  No.  If you pull it out of savings, and 
it goes into your consumption stream --<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  Right back.  That's what I --<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  -- and you pay taxes on it.  It's a 
year-end calculation.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL:</b>  Okay.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Shirley Peterson.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN:</b>  So to the extent that you saved it over 
the year, then you would get a deduction.  <p> 
 
		If you just saved it for two months, and you didn't 
have that savings accumulated at the year-end, you would not get 
a deduction.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  The earnings on that savings as 
it's invested builds up tax-free, though, I believe I heard you 
say.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  As long as you reinvest it.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  As long as it stays in?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN:  Right</b>. <p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  Yes.	<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Right.  If you go out and you get your 
earnings off that investment and you get a portrait painted of 
yourself, then you get taxed.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL:</b>  But as long as it stays there 
and keeps earning?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  If you put it in a savings account where 
I can borrow it, and Jack can borrow it, and others can borrow 
it, then you get earning.<p> 
 
		The other feature that I would think is very attractive 
about this is capital gains.  This proposal would end the debate 
on capital gains; because if you took your capital gain and 
reinvested it, then it's deducted.  It's deferred.  <p> 
 
		But if you take your capital gains and consume it and 
spend it, then it's not.  <p> 
 
		For the first time, we can honestly say to the taxi 
driver, or the bank teller, or the person working as a school 
teacher, or anyone else, "Your income is no different from the 
investor's income that has a capital gain.<p> 
 
		"If you make $45,000 a year and you save $5,000, you're 
going to defer taxes on that.  <p> 
 
		"If a millionaire makes $5,000 capital gain, they're 
going to defer taxes if they reinvest it.  But if they consume 
it, they're going to pay taxes, just as you."<p> 
 
		It gets rid of this class debate on capital gains.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Senator Nunn has been joined by the 
distinguished Budget Chairman, Pete Domenici -- Senator Domenici.	<p> 
 
		Thank you, Pete, for coming over.  I know your schedule 
is brief.  <p> 
 
		The Chair has never been in this position before, 
caught in the ultimate conundrum of two distinguished U.S. 
Senators on both sides of the aisle and their important 
contribution to this debate, with Dick Armey sitting on the 
sidelines.<p> 
 
		Pete, do you have a -- Sam has been for a half-hour, 
talking with the Commission.  This is just a dialogue.  <p> 
 
		Do you want to share with us your perspective on the 
problems that you saw in the Code that led to your Domenici-Nunn 
bill.  		And thank you so much, Pete, for being here.
<p>
<p>
<center><a href="#CONTENTS">CONTENTS</a></center>
<p>
<p>
<center>REMARKS OF<a name="Pete V. Domenici"> SENATOR PETE V. DOMENICI</a></center> 
<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  Thank you, <p> 
 
Mr. Chairman.		<p> 
 
		And I look around and I know most of you, some of your 
very well.  <p> 
 
		And I, first of all, what to congratulate you on 
accepting the responsibility of being on this advisory group.  I 
think it's absolutely critical that we do the right thing with 
tax reform and do it soon.<p> 
 
		My own thinking is very simple.  The Tax Code and the 
fiscal policy of this Nation have more to do with the future of 
our people than any other policies we talk about.  All others are 
dwarfed.  <p> 
 
		If we don't have the right fiscal policy and we don't 
have the right tax policy, we don't have "Opportunity America."  <p> 
 
		This Tax Code that we've got is backward.  It penalizes 
savings, penalizes investments.  And everything about it is kind 
of wrong-headed.<p> 
 
		I think it's so far off the mark.  And as to 
corporations, it is so cumbersome and so difficult that we ought 
to just throw the whole thing out.  <p> 
 
		So, we didn't start with the premise of tinkering with 
it.  We said, Let's have a whole new approach.<p> 
 
		I assume my friend and colleague, who has worked 
diligently on this and knows it very, very well -- frankly, we 
both worked hard enough, Chairman Kemp, that I think we can move 
over to the Finance Committee and help them a little.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		He's an armed service expert.  I'm supposedly a budget 
expert.  But I think we understand the Code now -- not in detail 
like some of you on this Commission.  <p> 
 
		But let me just say, I believe if you look at the 
corporate reform that's in this, you can't help but think it's 
something America ought to have.<p> 
 
		Simple as could be for those who understand corporate 
America, when the terrible things and these awful amortization-depreciation schedules that are audited ad 
nauseam that all kind 
of lawyers play around with and accountants spend millions on 
essentially put American business, not corporations, on a cash 
basis, that means they deduct what they purchase by way of 
equipment and the like.  <p> 
 
		At a point in time when this is passed, you'll get off 
all the things that bring accountants now from the Internal 
Revenue Service into our corporate headquarters, and they camp in 
some of them all year long -- some of you know that -- as to be 
compared with Japan, where they don't have such things.<p> 
 
		And we also make it border-adjustable.  We have to go 
through a process to do that, but I think it's very, very 
important that if you're going to reform the Tax Code, you tell 
the American people that American corporations will no longer be 
penalized as they sell in the world market vis-a-vis our foreign 
corporations that sell to us, or even American corporations.  <p> 
 
		So, we essentially have a flat, easy tax for 
corporations, and they're taxed as if they were in Atlanta, 
Georgia; or Albuquerque --even if they're overseas.  <p> 
 
		We don't think that's going to be onerous, but we think 
it's very fair.  It permits us to get down to that flat tax of 
about 10.5 percent.<p> 
 
		On the individual side, we can go through a lot of 
details, but we had some very simple but positive goals, and they 
were to increase American savings and increase investment by 
American people in productive things.  <p> 
 
		And we ended up considering the American savings pool 
to be sufficiently significant for America's future, to where we 
will give our citizens a tax break of significant proportions if 
they put their money in the savings pool.  And we won't tax them 
on it so long as they give it to that pool, which helps America.  <p> 
 
		So, right off the bat, this approach says anything you 
want to save, in any quantities you want to save, for anything 
you want to save.  Kind of a universal IRA.  You can do that.  <p> 
 
		But it also says we don't need a capital gains argument 
in America.  If you invest your money, you leave it there to be 
turned and churned and reinvested.  You don't pay tax, because we 
think the investment pool owned by individuals and investment 
entities is good for America.  <p> 
 
		So, we're saying to Americans, if you do that with your 
money, you don't pay income tax on it.  <p> 
 
		The upshot of it is we tax in a progressive way, and we 
thought progressivity was important.  It may not be, as you look 
at it.  But I would assume it may be hard to pass something that 
is not progressive.  We think it's good for America that it be 
progressive.  <p> 
 
		So, we have three brackets, but you can have whatever 
you would like.  And you only pay on what you spend, because 
essentially you deduct from what you earn -- all kinds of 
earnings, dividend earnings, any kind.  <p> 
 
		You deduct right off the top what you invest and what 
you save. <p> 
 
		And we think it has got a great opportunity, and it got 
a lot of opportunity built into it.  <p> 
 
		We cannot sit here, Mr. Chairman and Members, and say 
it's as simple as the notion of a flat tax.  But we would also 
suggest this is not a notion or an idea.  We've given you a 
total, full Tax Code.  <p> 
 
		We are very cautious fellows.  We asked so many 
questions they finally said, "Well, let's just write the whole 
damn thing so you can answer every question."  <p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		Now, that has made it such that we are picked on, 
because now people say, "Oh, this is not so good, because we know 
this about it."  		But, you see, we don't know this and 
that and the other about the other proposals.  They may all be 
wonderful, and you'll look at them all.  And I hope you come up 
with the best.<p> 
 
		Thank you very much.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Ed Feulner has a comment he wanted he 
wanted to make.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FEULNER</b>:  Mr. Chairman, I just want to 
thank both Senators Domenici and Nunn for the leadership they've 
shown going back several years, when tax reform was not a very 
popular subject.  <p> 
 
		I sat in on some of those early meetings with our good 
friends at the Center for Strategic and International Studies as 
they assembled the group.  And you two really fought through some 
very, very serious battles.<p> 
 
		I don't have any questions, <p> 
 
Mr. Chairman, but I just applaud their leadership for many years 
in this area.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Shirley Peterson.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER PETERSON</b>:  I also applaud your efforts.  <p> 
 
		I have studied your proposal with great interest, and I 
think it's fantastic that you got out there early thinking about 
this.<p> 
 
		I have one quick question.  One of our principles is to 
simplify the law.  One of the difficulties that we have in our 
current system is that we have not been able to define "income" 
easily.  	<p> 
 
		I'm a little concerned that we might face the same 
difficulty in defining "savings."  What is your response to that?<p> 
 
		SENATOR DOMENICI:  Our general response is we would 
define "savings" now pretty much like you do an IRA.  It would be 
financial savings, but it would also include investment.  	 
	So, we would have a rather broad definition.  It would not 
include things that are not financial in nature, and it would not 
include -- unless they were used directly in a business, like 
land, if it was used in a business for an apartment building or 
something of that nature.  	<p> 
 
		It would not include works of art, it would not include 
gold bullion.  But it would include gold stocks.  It would have 
to be a financial investment.<p> 
 
		So, we try to track the current Code as much as 
possible.<p> 
 
		I'd like to just throw out one other thing.  You talk 
about simplicity.  I know Chairman Archer has talked about a 
sales tax.  <p> 
 
		One of the things that makes ours -- and some people 
critique it on that ground -- a little more complex than it would 
otherwise be is the fact we came to a conclusion, after about a 
year of looking at this, that you had to do something about old 
savings if you do something about -- if you go to a consumption-based tax.  Whether it's done at the retail 
level, whether it's a 
value-added, or whether it is like ours, at the income level.  <p> 
 
		If you don't do that, what you are basically doing -- 
let's say you levied a <p> 
 
20 cent sales tax and replaced the Income Tax Code, if somebody 
saved all their lives and got $100,000 in the bank, and they're 
now -- they've already paid taxes on that and they're about to 
start consuming it, you have just taken #20,000 from them.  <p> 
 
		You've taken 20 percent of their life earnings.  We had 
to struggle with this old savings, because ours -- now, most 
people save less than $50,000, and we think we've got that part 
of it taken care of very simply, because we let them deduct and 
amortize that $50,000 as new savings, in effect writing it off 
over three years.  <p> 
 
		Above that, it gets a little more complicated.  And I 
won't go into it today.  But I would call your attention to the 
fact when you go to a consumption-based tax, whatever form, 
you've got to do something about old savings, otherwise you are 
penalizing people who've already been taxed and who have saved, 
in the name of encouraging it for others.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  You have done us a great honor.  And, 
Pete and Sam, thank you so very much on behalf of the Commission.  
<p> 
 
		And we hope to call -- we hope to do this again 
sometime in September, October.   <p> 
 
		And I say to both of you, as we begin the inventory the 
solutions, that helping focus on the problem, that is very 
helpful.  Thank you.  We appreciate your taking the time.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		Mr. Chairman, might I just say --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Yes, of course.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  I think you and your staff and all 
Members know that we did not put this together by ourselves.  So, 
there are experts in both the accounting field and from the 
business side --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.	<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  -- and auditors that help put it 
together, that modeled it.  It has been modeled because we gave 
them certain instructions. <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Good.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  Your staff ought to know what those 
instructions were, because if you'd like different instructions, 
that will change the nature of it --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  -- not the premises,  but the nature 
-- some of the specifics.  <p> 
 
		And that might make it more palatable to some of you or 
eliminate some of your questions.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR DOMENICI</b>:  Thank you very much.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  And thank all of you for taking your 
time.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Thanks, Sam.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR NUNN</b>:  Thank you. <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  The Honorable Richard Armey -- author, 
television star. <p> 
 
		Dick, thank you so very much.  I made a last-minute 
call to you as an old friend and asked you to appear.  <p> 
 
		We have been fascinated by the Armey flat tax.  We know 
the hard work you've put into it personally, your staff, the men 
and women behind it.  <p> 
 
		We've been listening to consumption and sales tax this 
morning.  We'd like to talk with you, as opposed to at you, and 
hear your view of the problems of the Tax Code and what led to 
the Armey flat tax that has gotten so much publicity around the 
country.  And thank you for being --<p> 
 
		(End tape 1, side 3)<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  After my --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  I hope you can appreciate we're 
applying for a 501(c)(3) <p> 
 
status --  	<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Oh.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  -- and we want to keep this 
nonpartisan.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Oh, okay.  I understand that.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  You know how nonpartisan I am.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I realize that.<p> 
<a href="#CONTENTS">CONTENTS</a>
<center><b>REMARKS OF CONGRESSMAN <a name="Richard K. Armey">RICHARD K. ARMEY</a> </b></center> 
<p> 
 
<center><b>MAJORITY LEADER US HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES</b></center> 
<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Let me say, first of all, I 
appreciate all of you giving of your time and time and effort to 
deal with this issue.  It's going to be, I think, a very complex 
but very much a central part of the public policy debate for the 
next few years.<p> 
 
		You've already heard from people who advocate the Nunn-Domenici proposal, the sales 
tax.  And now you hear from me.  <p> 
 
		But I think one thing that you will see we have a 
universal agreement on is the current Tax Code as we know it is 
no longer acceptable to the American people.  <p> 
 
		And I thought I would talk this morning very briefly on 
two points:<p> 
 
		Why is it the American people are so discontent -- 
even, I would say, angry -- about the current Tax Code and the 
manner in which it is enforced?  <p> 
 
		And you don't have to travel very far in this country 
before you encounter the frustration, the anger, the anxiety that 
forebodes the average American taxpayer.  <p> 
 
		Clearly, the first complaint that you hear from the 
taxpayer is that it is too complex.  That complexity is felt 
individually by the individual as something ominous.  <p> 
 
		I file my own taxes.  I have always done my own taxes.  
I have a Ph.D. in economics.  I have a considerable number of -- 
graduate  training in accounting.  <p> 
 
		And I still find myself -- struggle as I may over every 
bit of detail in each one of these complex manuals and giving it 
my best shot, filing my taxes in full confidence that I have done 
my utmost to comply with the law -- living, then, for several 
months in some dread fear that I will have a knock on the door or 
an ominous letter in my mailbox explaining to me how it is that 
somehow I missed something, and am therefore presumed to have 
been guilty of cheating on my taxes.<p> 
 
		And I have to tell you, I may not be very bright, Mr. 
Chairman, but I am not crazy.  If I'm going to pick somebody to 
have a fight with on purpose, it will not be the IRS.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		So, I assure you I am as meticulous as I can be, and 
yet I can't be confident that I didn't make a mistake.<p> 
 
		And I think that kind of dread fear is something every 
American citizen lives with today.<p> 
 
		Now, the complexity has another dimension to it that is 
not perhaps so personal.  We spend $5.4 billion manhours in 
America every year complying with the Tax Code.  That's more 
time, more manhours than is spent in the production of every car, 
truck, and van produced in this country each year.<p> 
 
		That is $232 billion worth of compliance cost.  And 
insofar as that is more than is necessary, it is sheer deadweight 
loss and waste in the economy.  <p> 
 
		Each one of these manhours, each dollar of this $232 
billion could be put to some productive use, rather than to the 
deadweight loss use of simply complying with federally -- 
government-mandated red tape.  <p> 
 
		Waste is always counterproductive.  Waste always goes 
against growth, against efficiency, against standard of living, 
and it is never something that can be accepted or tolerated in 
any economy that works to allocate scarce and precious resources 
to their best alternative use.  And this I think is something 
that we need to understand.  <p> 
 
		And I think at some level the American people 
understand.  It is a waste.  <p> 
 
		People kid me about the flat tax.  "Will it be enacted 
into law?  If it is, what will -- how will we know?"  <p> 
 
		And I say, "Well, you will know because the sales of 
Rolaids will go down between January 1 and April 15th.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		And that is the sort of intuitive, <p> 
 
in-our-stomach understanding that "There's waste afoot here, and 
it's coming back to roost in my backyard."<p> 
 
		I should not spend two weekends and several evenings 
between January 1 and April 15th being short-tempered and 
insensitive and intolerant with my wife because she might have 
lost a receipt someplace --<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		-- when, in fact, it was probably me in the first 
place.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		Or too busy to spend time with the children, because I 
got hung up -- the receipts.<p> 
 
		That's waste in a very personal way.<p> 
 
		Double-taxation is a very big part of the current Tax 
Code.  It is always incredible to me that somebody can look at 
this Tax Code and look at the rate structure and say it's fair, 
when in this Tax Code, we have billions of -- hundreds of 
billions of dollars that escape the tax base altogether, and then 
at the same time turn around and impose double-taxations on 
hundreds of billions of other dollars.  What can be more unfair 
than that?<p> 
 
		But that is particularly important when the double-taxation almost always and almost 
universally falls on savings 
and investment, which are the two engines of economic growth.<p> 
 
		Finally, people are aware of the fact that the high tax 
rates slow economic growth. 		And here is the shocking 
statistical revelation.  You'll find it on page 1 of my formal 
remarks, which I would ask you to put in the record.  	Despite 
all that we have done -- certainly the leadership shown by Jack 
Kemp in the early '80s to get rid of and lower high marginal 
rates -- by comparison with 1965, when fewer than 3 percent of 
American families filing joint reports had a marginal rate at or 
above <p> 
 
28 percent, today -- or in 1999 -- '91 -- in 1991, 36 percent of 
American families filing joint returns filed at a marginal rate 
at or above 28 percent.<p> 
 
		If there is anything, any single statistic that says to 
me Milton Friedman was right when he said "bracket creep" --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY:</b>  -- this is the statistic.  <p> 
 
		The fact of the matter is we are more beleaguered by 
the oppressive impact of high marginal rates on incentive to 
economic growth and individual initiative now than we were even 
before the high drama of the '80s and the tax reforms we 
attempted in the '80s.  <p> 
 
		And that translates into lost economic opportunity, 
lost growth.<p> 
 
		Finally, the American people think of the current Tax 
Code as unfair.  And that comes largely out of the complexity.  <p> 
 
		There is an abiding belief by almost every American 
taxpayer that "There's a break in the Code for everybody but me," 
or more breaks for others.<p> 
 
		(Sound of bell)<p> 
 
		That, ladies and gentlemen, is a bell that indicates I 
have a vote.  I would like to spend the next five minutes and 
complete my statement and then, if you will, I'll go vote.  And 
if you would like, I would then come back.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Oh, good.	<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  But I must make the vote.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Dick Gephardt has just walked in.  We 
want to hear him as well.<p> 
 
		Since -- did you say you were going to go right now?  <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Well, I would like to finish my 
statement first.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Okay.  Please do.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  So that -- and I would say it is 
this heartfelt belief that this complex system that "has a break 
for everybody but me" us unfair.  <p> 
 
		And therefore you will see people who will say, 
"Therefore, I'll give myself a break."  		And that, in my 
estimation, is the fundamental cause of what we know as the 
underground economy -- not the criminal economy, but the 
underground economy, which is technically criminal, but criminal 
behavior but normally law-abiding men.  <p> 
 
		The plumber who says, "I'll do your job on Saturday if 
you pay me in cash, because I've got no break that this guy down 
the road has gotten.  I know he's got it.  Even though I can't 
find it, I know he's got it."<p> 
 
		And then secondly, because it's so complex and has 
seemed to be so unfair, that person who is tempted to the 
underground economy says, "And I can do that and get away with 
it. Because of all the hundreds of billions of data points that 
the IRS must keep track of, they'd never find this little 
Saturday morning data point anyway."<p> 
 
		So, if you feel self-justified in cutting a corner in 
such a way that you won't get caught, you will have a low 
resistance to the temptations of the underground economy.<p> 
 
		Now, as I examined these circumstances in the current 
Tax Code and said, "How do we fix this," I was brought to the 
flat tax.  And this is what I would suggest to you the flat tax 
has to offer if you will look at it.  <p> 
 
		First, it's simplicity.  That, of course, is 
exemplified by the single <p> 
 
postcard-size form.  <p> 
 
		You know, it is a very simple matter, and incidentally, 
I would say, honest and direct matter of just simply taking that 
income that you earned, deduct from that a generous family 
allowance, and apply a single rate to that which is in excess of 
that allowance.  <p> 
 
		You don't have to hunt up all those receipts for all 
that complex and mysterious itemized deductions.  <p> 
 
		You don't have to worry about what is the definition. <p> 
 
		You know, I have a very small annuity program from my 
old years as a college professor.  I get $144 a month for my 
retirement, which, of course, reminds me that tenure meets not 
having enough money forever.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		And every time I file my taxes, I've got to try to 
figure out if this is, in this line, at A or B, because I have to 
understand the definition -- legal definitions of that. <p> 
 
		It's fair.  You know, everybody gets treated the same.  
	<p> 
 
		And let me suggest to you that as you watch the 
political debate of the next two years in America on this issue 
of taxation and on other issues, you're going to see a great 
national debate on what is fair.<p> 
 
		And I will believe, from what I've seen just in the 
testimonies I've got regarding the flat tax, that America today, 
more than at any time in our history, is coming to the belief 
that what is fair is that this government treat everybody exactly 
the same as everybody else.  		And when people believe that 
they are being treated fairly, they have lost the temptation to 
give themselves the break that they didn't get relative to the 
other person.<p> 
 
		But more than any other thing I hear, it is fair.  It's 
simple, it's obvious, it's honest, it's fair.  And I like that.  
That's the typical American response.<p> 
 
		The flat tax promotes economic growth, I think, to as 
much a degree as you can with the Tax Code, and in a very few 
specific rates, which I'll be happy to discuss after I go vote.  		The low rates are real, especially the 
low marginal 
rate is real and indisputable and obvious.  <p> 
 
		Double-taxation is ended in the flat tax, so we no 
longer have a tax bias against savings and investment.  It is 
neutral.  <p> 
 
		Under the flat tax, people will make decisions to save, 
invest, or consume based upon their personal family financial or 
business economic circumstances and conditions and not cajoled by 
some bias in the Tax Code.<p> 
 
		And then, of course, the specific treatment of capital 
is very important.  We expense capital for economic growth in 
America in the end of this century and the beginning of the next 
century that will be so much centered in the high tech, 
communications, electronics, computerized sectors of the economy, 
where new technology we know brought on line today is likely to 
be obsolete in two years from now.  		You have an 
incentive to make that investment when you can expense it and 
recapture its cost, knowing that two years from now you can even 
get more in tune with the new modern future that you didn't even 
imagine two years ago.  <p> 
 
		So, this, I think, is an extremely important growth 
component for a critical sector of our future economy.<p> 
 
		Finally, let me say, before I leave and surrender the 
podium -- and I will come back if you like --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  -- the flat tax, in my estimation, 
is an important innovation, because public policy, in order to 
prevail in America, must be accepted by America.  <p> 
 
		And the American people have demonstrated that they 
love the simplicity, the honesty, the directness, the fairness of 
the flat tax.  <p> 
 
		And there is no public policy that can be more easily 
and more inexpensively and less intrusively administered than 
that which is accepted by the American people.  <p> 
 
		So, the deadweight loss I think will go away, along 
with the incentive for underground economy.<p> 
 
		And again, I'm --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Dick, thanks. <p> 
 
		You go vote, come back.<p> 
 
		We'll hear from Senator Mack, Chairman of the Joint 
Economic Committee.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Thank you, Dick.	<p> 
 
		(Pause)<p> 
 
		It is a personal honor and a great privilege to 
introduce the Chairman of the Joint Economic Committee, my friend 
Connie Mack, the Senator from Florida.<p> 
 
		I won't introduce you to all the Commissioners, Connie, 
but I know you know all of the men and women in one forum or 
another who are on the Commission.  <p> 
 
		We are inventorying the problems of the Code and the 
nexus between taxes and growth and the budget.  <p> 
 
		And with your interest in those three issues, we 
thought it would be particularly appropriate to have your 
leadership on this issue, and we'd like you to make some comments 
and then have a dialogue with the Commission.  It's not a 
hearing, per se.  <p> 
 
		It's a public -- our first public hearing, so to speak, 
on the problems of the Code as we begin to look forward to the 
solutions down the road.<p> 
 
		So, please take what time you would like, and allow us 
to have some questions.   And then Dick Armey and, I think, Dick 
Gephardt both said they'd come back and maybe sit on a panel.<p> 
 
		Thank you.
<p> 
