<p>
<p>
<center><b>REMARKS OF <a name="Connie Mack">SENATOR CONNIE MACK</a></b> </center> 
<p> 
 
<center><b>CHAIRMAN, JOINT ECONOMIC COMMITTEE</b></center> 
<p> 
 
		<b>SENIOR MACK</b>:  Well, first of all, I want to thank you, 
Jack, for the opportunity to participate this morning.<p> 
 
		And I want to express my deep appreciation for the 
members of the panel in taking the time that I know that I know 
that is requiring of you to engage yourself and involve yourself 
in what I think is one of the most significant issues that faces 
our Nation.<p> 
 
		As you hear from people today, you're probably going to 
hear more in the specifics with respect to the various aspects of 
tax reform than you're going to hear from me, because, frankly, I 
want to address the issue from a broader perspective.<p> 
 
		I believe that the primary objective -- the thing that 
ought to be on your mind as you work your way through a series of 
decisions about the future Tax Code, the number one priority, as 
far as I'm concerned, is what does it do to growth, what does it 
do to jobs creation, what does it do with respect to business 
formation, what does it do with respect to technology, how does 
it affect the flow of capital from old technologies to new 
technologies?<p> 
 
		So, the first and primary objective I think you ought 
to keep in your mind as you work through the issue of reform is 
what is this going to do to our ability as a Nation to grow and 
provide opportunities to all Americans.<p> 
 
		Allow me to, again, take a somewhat broader perspective 
on this issue.  	<p> 
 
		Again, in speaking about the issue of growth -- and I 
would tie it into this next seven years, the commitment that has 
been made and will be made in these next few days by the Congress 
to work our way towards a balanced budget in the year 2002.  <p> 
 
		Almost always you hear from people there are really 
only two ways to address the budget deficit issue.  They either 
say you've got to raise taxes, or you've got to cut spending in 
order to get there.  	<p> 
 
		Many of us have been trying to make the case that there 
is a third and -- I was going to say "equally important."  I 
would make the case "more important" method to address the issue 
of deficit reduction.  And that's growth in the economy.  	 
		<p> 
 
		So, I think what you're involved in is vital to the 
future of the Nation from the perspective of over the next seven 
years, if we're going to meet this target -- and I'm convinced 
that we will -- that the conclusions that you draw with respect 
to the decisions you make and the recommendations that you make 
to those of us who will be out making a campaign statement to the 
American people in 1996 -- again, I think it's going to be vital, 
what you develop, as to our ability both to meet that target of a 
balanced budget by 2002 and to provide hope and opportunity to 
all Americans.<p> 
 
		Let me add another perspective here.  Several years ago 
I read a book by Jacques Attile (phonetic) that enraged me, 
frankly.  And it was -- the book was called <i>Millennium</i>.<p> 
 
		And in the book, basically Jacques Attile lays out that 
America's time in the sun has past, that the American century is 
over, it's behind us, that the future belongs either to the 
Europeans, the French, and the Germans, or to the Asians, and 
that America's time has passed.<p> 
 
		Now, I must say I'm a fairly competitive person.  So, 
as I was reading through this book, I could find myself really 
getting angry about what I was -- what I was reading.  <p> 
 
		But I think at some point you have to stop and ask 
yourself, well, is there any possibility that the premise could 
be true.  	<p> 
 
		And if there is some possibility to ask ourselves the 
question, "Well, what do we need to do to remain the center of 
influence in the 21st century?" -- and the first thing you might 
say or first thing you might hear from others, is, "Well, what 
difference does it make?"<p> 
 
		Well, I think it makes a tremendous amount of 
difference.  The first, of course, is obvious, it's -- it will 
have a direct effect on our children and our grandchildren.  <p> 
 
		If we're the center of influence into the 21st century, 
it's fairly easy to draw the conclusion that we will be able to 
enhance the standard of living for our children and 
grandchildren.<p> 
 
		But I would make the case that it goes a lot deeper 
than that.  A great nation has to set itself on a course to 
achieve something greater than itself.  And I would claim that 
that the greatness that we want to try to accomplish in the 21st 
century and the reason that we want to remain the center of 
influence is because I am convinced our Nation is the only nation 
on the globe that has the right kinds of policies, the belief in 
freedom and justice and democracy and human rights and 
capitalism.	<p> 
 
		And we are the only nation in the world, I believe, 
that is committed to exporting those ideas and those principles 
around the globe.<p> 
 
		So, again, I say to you, what you're engaged in I think 
is vital to the future.  It will, in fact, enable America to be 
the center of influence.  We will be able to export those ideas 
of freedom and justice and capitalism.<p> 
 
		And some people will respond and say, "Wait a minute, 
you know, I don't buy, you know, that kind of moral argument that 
you're making.  I'm more interested in "What can I do for the 
folks back home in my district?"	<p> 
 
		I would make the argument out of this that if, in fact, 
we are able to export those principles, that have made this 
Nation great, think of the huge markets that will have been 
created around the world in which our sons and daughters will 
have an opportunity to produce and sell in.<p> 
 
		So, I think there is a tremendous motivation behind 
what you're involved in.  And again, I commend you for the effort 
that you're making and your willingness to spend the time to be 
involved in this, what I think is a great cause.<p> 
 
		Now, let me go on to another point of this.  In 
essence, what do we have to do then?  I mean, how do we approach 
this issue of how we remain the center of influence?  <p> 
 
		Well, it's obvious the first thing that comes to my 
mind is that we have to be in a situation where we protect our 
basic civil liberties, and we enhance the capitalism that has 
made us great.<p> 
 
		And how do we do that?  Well, I think we need to listen 
to some of those who have been talking about the future.  <p> 
 
		Several weeks ago, I held a hearing of the Joint 
Economic Committee on "Economic Policy in the 21st Century."  <p> 
 
		And one of the individuals that I had at the hearing 
was Alvin Toffler.  Toffler -- everybody kind of hears Toffler 
talk about the <p> 
 
-- how we have moved from a hunting and gathering society through 
agriculture, through industrial -- into the information 
communications age.  <p> 
 
		But if you focus on that, I think you've missed the 
message.  What Alvin Toffler really says, from an economic 
perspective, is that you've got to look beyond the old factors of 
production of land, labor, and capital, because there, in fact, 
is another element today.  That element totally changes the 
future.  And that element is knowledge.  <p> 
 
		I mean, production in the future and our ability to 
produce and grow and remain the center of influence is going to 
come from adding to those basic factors that we term "knowledge."<p> 
 
		I think that when you accept that additional factor, it 
explodes the myth of scarcity, which leads me to another 
individual that I would say that my dear friend Jack Kemp focused 
me on, probably now six years ago, when George Guilder came out 
with his book called <i>Microcosm</i>.  It is a history of the 
microchip, the history of the computer.  	<p> 
 
		And he makes many of the same points.  I'd like to take 
just a moment though and -- Guilder says, "The central event of 
the 20th century is the overthrow of matter.  The powers of mind 
are everywhere ascending over the brute force of things."<p> 
 
		And, in essence, what he is arguing is that economics 
is going to move away from a study of scarcity to the allocation 
of abundance.  <p> 
 
		Now, the problem that I think that we're dealing with 
is that we find ourselves kind of boxed in to an old way of 
thinking.  I mean, this is a new world, it is a new age.  And 
there are new opportunities, and we have to develop new ways of 
looking at those opportunities.<p> 
 
		I was struck this weekend as I read through David 
Broder's article in the <i>Washington Post</i> that was entitled "The 
Democrat Divide."  And it quotes a Michael Rothschild, a 
San Francisco futurist.  He sets forth the proposition that the 
microchip revolution is ushering in a new era of abundance, 
vanquishing scarcity to the dustbin of history.<p> 
 
		And so, again, I think it is important for us to 
understand that we are, in fact, moving into a new age.  And 
we've got to get out of the thinking of economic policy that 
basically was developed with mass production, mass communication, 
mass everything.<p> 
 
		Well, today we know that there are niche markets.  We 
know that computers are used to both design and define what those 
markets are.  	<p> 
 
		And so we have to come up with economic policies that 
reflect this new age.<p> 
 
		Now, we're going to have quite a debate, and you're 
going to be involved in a whole series of choices that you're 
going to have to go through about how to put together a Tax Code 
for the 21st century.  <p> 
 
		I took this opportunity to develop a list of 10 
principles for the tax system for the 21st century, and I'll 
leave this -- I'm not going to go through it at this point, with 
the exception of maybe picking out just two.<p> 
 
		I think again, thinking from the perspective that 
growth is what we want to try to accomplish with a Tax Code, you 
have to ask yourself the question "What single thing can you do 
that will affect growth more than anything else?"  <p> 
 
		I think it's the lowest possible marginal tax rate that 
you can come up with, because I believe that if you lower the 
marginal tax rate, that you, in fact, will provide the incentive 
-- you will give people encouragement.  		You will say to 
them that "There is a reward for your work, for your savings, for 
your investing."  It is clearly the way to release and encourage 
the American spirit of innovation.<p> 
 
		So, the lowest possible marginal tax rate I think has 
got to be on the top of the list.<p> 
 
		The second point that I would make is I think whatever 
plan or program that you come up with, it should be neutral.  <p> 
 
		I hear a lot of my colleagues saying -- and it began 
back when we had the debates in 1986 about tax reform.  You know, 
there was a lot of talk about we need to punish consumption.  		Well, you know, I am not an 
economist, but I have -- I 
have listened to a number of economists over the years.  I don't 
recall seeing an economic equation that said that you can enhance 
growth by punishing consumption.<p> 
 
		Now, I want to encourage savings and investing, but 
what I'm saying to you is I think that you can encourage savings 
and investing without punishing consumption.  Because if I 
remember correctly, consumption plus investment equals what, 
income? <p> 
 
		So, what I'm saying is that, again, I think you need to 
try to work towards a Tax Code that, in fact, both encourages 
savings and investing and does so without punishing consumption.  
And I think that that can be done.<p> 
 
		Lastly, let me just make several other points.  And 
then I'll stop and try to respond to whatever questions you all 
have.<p> 
 
		One of the issues we're going deal with -- and we hear 
it day after day after day, by my colleagues on the other side of 
the aisle, is this pitting Americans against each other, trying 
to pit one group of Americans against another group, one class 
versus another class, or creating the concept that there, in 
fact, is a class in our society.<p> 
 
		And I would say, if you look at some of the data that 
the Joint Economic Committee over the years has produced with 
respect to income distribution, really the way we ought to be 
talking about it is "income mobility," because there is true 
income mobility in our society, probably unlike any other society 
in the world.<p> 
 
		Just a couple of quick statistics:  From 1979 to 1988, 
86 percent of the wage earners in the lowest percentile, 20 
percentile of the country, 86 percent moved up into a higher 
percentile, 86 percent.<p> 
 
		You had a greater probability that you would go to the 
top 20 percentile than remaining in the 20 percentile.  Now, I 
think that's rather significant.  <p> 
 
		And we need to drive that message home, because if we 
get caught into this trap that there is some kind of a static 
model that we have to live with, then you're just in a situation 
you're trying to pit one group of winners and losers against the 
other, and I think that would be a tragedy.<p> 
 
		And the other point that I would make is that -- again, 
from the statistical data that was developed -- is that 52 
percent -- almost <p> 
 
53 percent of the people were in the top 20 -- or, excuse me, the 
top 1 percent in 1979 -- 52 percent of them fell into lower 
categories during those periods.  <p> 
 
		So, it's not just -- the point in all of this is that 
there is constant motion, that, in fact, if you provide people 
with incentive, they're going to move.  <p> 
 
		And that's where I come back again to:  The lowest 
marginal tax rate provides the greatest incentive.	    <p> 
 
		I guess I could go on and on, <p> 
 
Mr. Chairman, but I think the last point that I would make would 
be with respect to capital gains.  And I know capital gains has 
been talked about by economists in many different ways.  <p> 
 
		And frankly, this is a thought that I picked up in 
discussions with my friend Congressman Armey.<p> 
 
		If you think about capital gains as being a voluntary 
tax, which it, in essence, is -- if you think the tax rate is too 
high, you just voluntarily say, "I'm going to keep my money,  I'm 
not going to give it to the government, and you don't sell."<p> 
 
		But as a result of that, capital gains has become, if 
you will, a barrier or a wall that has been built around the 
investments that have taken place in the past, in the old 
technologies of the past.<p> 
 
		And what we want to do is we want to rip down those 
walls, and we want to let that capital flow into the new 
technologies.  That's where America's future is.<p> 
 
		So, again, I close with my comments, but again 
commending both Chairman Kemp and for -- and to all of you for 
your involvement in this.  I think it is a great endeavor, and I 
look for forward to seeing the product of what you produce.<p> 
 
		Thank you very much, Mr. Chairman.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Well, Senator, we've been sitting here 
since 10 o'clock this morning, and we've heard some eloquent 
testimony.  <p> 
 
		But that -- I know I speak for all the Commissioners 
when I say that came from not only the head but the heart.  <p> 
 
		And I've heard you speak many times -- this is an 
editorial comment, and I know I speak for Carroll, with whom we 
all served together -- I have never heard you in finer form with 
regard to your vision of America in the 21st century.  	 
	And I know that's what Bob Dole and Newt Gingrich wanted us 
to do, is to put together, on a tabula rasa, a clean slate, a <p> 
 
Tax Code for the 21st century.  <p> 
 
		And you have helped set the predicate for that, 
reminded us that the ultimate wealth is not what's in the ground, 
it's what is in the heart and mind of the American people.  <p> 
 
		And I just really can't pass up the opportunity to say 
to you just thanks for the keynote address of this Commission.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Shirley Peterson, former Commissioner 
of the IRS and an old friend of yours, I know.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER PETERSON</b>:  Senator Mack, thank you very 
much.  <p> 
 
		I find your statement very provocative and eloquent.  <p> 
 
		And I must say that one point that you made has really 
captured my imagination, and that is the issue -- the point of 
thinking about knowledge as part of the capital of this country 
and trying to design some way to encourage its growth, shall we 
say.  <p> 
 
		Because in addition to accomplishing all of the goals 
and principles that you set out, certainly it would increase the 
income mobility, it would create all the incentive, all the 
opportunity, all the hope that America stands for.  <p> 
 
		So, I am just excited by that suggestion.  And we will 
try to design some way to build that into our new system.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Thank you.	<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN</b>:  (Inaudible)<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Herman Cain has a --		 
<b>COMMISSIONER PETERSON</b>:  (Inaudible) here.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  I'm sorry, Herman Cain has a question.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN</b>:  Thank you for coming, Senator Mack.  
It's good to see you.  <p> 
 
		And because I have the advantage of knowing your 
previous life, before you became a distinguished Senator here in 
Washington, and when you talked about your reaction in reading 
the <i>Millennium</i>, it triggered a disturbing statement that an early 
century economist by the name of Joseph Shumpter (phonetic) made.  
He said the greatest threat to capitalism is not its failure, but 
its success.  		<p> 
 
		And that has disturbed me, much as your observation 
with respect to the <i>Millennium</i>.  And when you think about that -- 
and that may be where we are -- we are at that crest of success, 
and that's what we are dealing with, and the fact that when you 
talk about capitalism and the use of capitalism, you are talking 
about businesses and business people using that to create the 
productivity that you've talked about.<p> 
 
		My question would be:  What are your thoughts about 
business leaders and businesspeople and the business community, 
since you have a relatively recent involvement directly as a 
business person; and now having been in Washington for a number 
of years, what are your thoughts in terms of how will businesses 
embrace radical change, revolutionary change, in terms of how we 
collect revenue from businesses, not necessarily the individual 
income tax side?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  That's a difficult question, frankly, to 
respond to, because there are so many facets of business, so many 
-- we're going to have businesses who are, in essence, moving 
into the 21st century.  There are going to be businesses that 
initially will feel threatened as a result of change.<p> 
 
		I would say to them that they should encourage this 
change, because frankly it will open up to them the same 
opportunities that I see for individuals.  <p> 
 
		And what I'm referring to there is that I can remember 
-- again historically -- and I think we've all recognized this.  <p> 
 
		As we have moved move from an agricultural-based 
society to an industrial-based society, the agriculture community 
was worried about, well, if the Congress and the country is going 
to be facing on this new industrial age, what's going to happen 
to us?  <p> 
 
		Well, the reality is that what the farmers of America 
did is they finally embraced the new age, the industrial age, and 
they used those technologies to enhance their production, their 
capability.<p> 
 
		So, what I'm saying to you is that while we're going to 
hear, I think, some concerns from what some would refer to as <p> 
 
second-wave industries, whether that be the automobile industry 
in Detroit, which I just recently visited -- and it's really 
amazing to see what the automobile industry is doing with the 
development of the new -- use of new technologies. <p> 
 
		So, I think, again, what we ought to try to focus on, 
in addition to the lower marginal rates that I talked about, is 
what can we do to encourage the flow of capital that will allow 
these new technologies to move into the old industries, to 
enhance their ability to compete internationally.  <p> 
 
		And I guess that would be another point that's obvious 
to everybody.  We are so much, today, engaged in -- in 
international competition that what we have to do is enhance our 
businesses' abilities to compete.  <p> 
 
		And I think -- if I can make one, maybe one last point 
in this, last year a fellow by the name of George Hatsophilos 
(phonetic) came and testified or spoke with a group of Senators 
that Senator Packwood and Senator Domenici had put together.  <p> 
 
		And he had indicated that as a young man from Greece, 
he had looked all throughout the world to find what land provided 
the greatest opportunity for entrepreneurism.  And he chose 
America.<p> 
 
		And what we want to do with our Tax Code is to make 
sure that the next generation of George Hatsophiloses who look 
for entrepreneur capital of the world still believe that America 
is that capital.  <p> 
 
		And I think we can do that again with the kinds of 
reforms that you all are going to be looking at with respect to 
the Tax Code.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  All growth in an economy is the result 
of risk-taking men and women who are willing to take the fruits 
of their labor and put it at risk on a new idea and go through 
the vicissitudes and vagaries in competition of the marketplace.  <p> 
 
		And you have reminded us today that consumption is the 
reward for production and savings is consumption deferred.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Absolutely.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  And your testimony is just absolutely 
laser-like in reminding this Commission that -- all of us, as 
Americans, the stake we have in setting the marginal tax rate in 
peacetime at the level of equilibrium at which people are willing 
to maximize their output and still pay that fundamental tax.<p> 
 
		I don't know where it is, but from Biblical times to 
today, there is empirical evidence -- I know I'm not supposed to 
come the any conclusions, because I've got a hat on now as a 
chairman -- but I have said many, many times, in my study of 
history, that the level of equilibrium is in the 20s, not the 40s 
and 50s, where we are today, you know..<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Ed Feulner.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FEULNER</b>:  I, too, want to thank you, Mr. 
Chairman.  	<p> 
 
		Two prefatory comments, if I may. <p> 
 
		First, I commend you for what you're doing with the 
Joint Economic Committee, in terms of the educational efforts.  <p> 
 
		I caught, on C-SPAN, your discussion with June O'Neill, 
the Director of the Congressional Budget Office, trying to make 
sense out of some very arcane number debates.  And it was very 
enlightening for me, who thought I knew a lot about some of these 
related subjects, because I learned a lot.<p> 
 
		Secondly, I know I speak for everybody on the 
Commission when I say we look forward to seeing your whole list 
of 10 principles, because I sure agree with the first three I 
heard.<p> 
 
		You were in the House, I think, at the time of the '86 
tax reform.  Chairman Archer, when he was here this morning, 
made, I think, a very telling point.  And that is that was 
supposed to be a simplifying, flattening, fairing kind of 
approach to tax reform.  It didn't work.	<p> 
 
		Subsequent to that, we have had two major tax 
increases, each of them, in effect, the largest tax increases 
we've had in our history, both as a result of the '91 budget deal 
and the tax increase of 1993.  <p> 
 
		What went wrong and how do we avoid that again, if, in 
fact, we are able to come in with some proposals that the 
Congress then accepts in terms of moving toward a fairer, flatter 
tax system?<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>;  Yes, that's a question, frankly, that 
has gone through my mind several times.  <p> 
 
		And those of us who have gone through this process, 
probably at the end of it -- I know one of the conclusions that I 
came to was why should we be surprised at what came out of 1986?  
I mean, that's -- the process was the same.  The interests were 
basically the same.  		"Why should we expect anything 
different?" is really the question that you're asking.<p> 
 
		The conclusion that I have come to is because we're 
different.  The Congress is different.  <p> 
 
		There was an incredible message that was sent by the 
people of this country in 1994.  I mean, it's amazing to listen 
to the people here in Washington, D.C., the things that they're 
saying to us -- like, you know, we should have been doing this a 
long time ago.  <p> 
 
		So, what I'm saying to you is I think the people who 
make up the Congress today are totally different.  We have a 
different way of looking at the process.  Lots of us want to 
change the process.  <p> 
 
		So, I guess what I'm saying to you is I think, Ed, that 
this is occurring just at the right time.<p> 
 
		And then the point -- the last point that I would make 
is:  There are some -- and Senator Packwood may have indicated 
this -- was he here earlier?<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  No, Senator Packwood, incidentally, to 
my colleagues, had to cancel because of the governors who are 
meeting over in the Senate.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Okay.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  So, he will not be here.  So --<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  If Senator Packwood were here, he 
probably would say to you what he has said to me.  He thinks that 
the momentum in the country has built to the point where there's 
a chance that we could pass tax reform next year.  		Well, 
I must say to you, I don't think we're quite to that point.  But 
here is the thing -- and this is how I would like to see all of 
this play out -- is that you do your work and develop a proposal, 
hopefully, that would be embraced by the Republican -- at least 
the Republican members of the Congress.  <p> 
 
		I would love to see the Republican standard-bearer in 
1996 take it as the cause, as the contract, if you will.  Boy, 
what a change in America's attitude.  <p> 
 
		There was a contract offered in 1994.  The American 
people said, "We support that.  We want you to go back to 
Washington.  We came back, and we're doing it."<p> 
 
		And I think if we go to the American people in 1996 
with a new contract about tax reform, with low marginal tax 
rates, offering hope and opportunity, you elect us, we'll go back 
to Washington in 1997, and we'll pass true tax reform.  I think 
we, in fact, can do it.  It's a different Congress.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Ken Blackwell.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER BLACKWELL</b>:  Senator Mack, I would like to 
join the chorus of thanks for your clarity and for your vision.  <p> 
 
		If the objective of good tax policy is to minimize -- 
excuse me, maximize economic growth and the rising real incomes 
and real tax receipts that go along with that economic growth, 
then the most efficient tax rate on capital gains is zero.<p> 
 
		Have things changed so radically in Washington and in 
Congress that we can expect that folks will rise above the 
political hurdle and deal with that, that reality?     	 
	<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  My reaction is yes.  		Assuming 
that the premise that I gave earlier with respect to income 
mobility is correct -- and I've heard the Chairman many times 
refer to presidential candidate McGovern, who offered a tax 
proposal to the country which was just flat rejected.  And the 
reason it was rejected, people said, "Look, I hope to be rich 
some day."<p> 
 
		I mean, there is a belief in this nation, and it is 
built on fact.  It's built on the stories that all of us hear 
from people all across this Nation, of all ages, all colors, who 
basically say, "Give me the opportunity and I'll succeed, and 
I'll move up."  <p> 
 
		So, if the premise is right and people understand that 
capital formation is key to our competitive advantage and to 
providing us with the tools to compete, then they're going to 
support it, because they know in the long run it is in their best 
interests to do so.  <p> 
 
		But, again, we can't be faint-hearted about making the 
-- providing the message.  I mean, I -- every time I talk about 
capital gains -- and I've done it now since 13 years that I've 
been involved in the Congress -- every time I do it, you know, 
somebody wants to make a charge that, "You know, Mack is just 
interested in the wealthy."<p> 
 
		Well, if we're going to let that charge deny us from 
making the claim about what the future is all about and what 
eliminating the tax on capital gains would do and the 
opportunities it would provide, if we're going to -- we might as 
well get out of the arena.    <p> 
 
		But I think we have a case to make.  In fact -- <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Your explanation that the capital gains 
tax is, in essence, a transaction tax, it's a voluntary tax.  If 
you don't transact or sell anything, you don't pay it.  The only 
people who have to pay it are middle-income working men and women 
who want to save to send their children to college.  <p> 
 
		And so it ends up that the capital gains tax is not a 
tax on the rich, it's a tax <p> 
 
-- they're already rich.  They're going to get rich under any 
system.  It's a tax on the poor, who really want to get rich.  
And that's the essence of this dynamics fluidity that you have 
alluded to.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  There are some statistical --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  I think -- Matt -- John -- Dean -- 
Carroll -- Carroll had a question, Carroll Campbell.<p> 
 
		We've got Dick Armey waiting in the wings again, so we 
want to -- <p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAMPBELL</b>:  Senator, I think your point is 
right -- right, absolutely, on target when you talk about capital 
gains.  		There's no question that you discourage the 
investment with the tax; no question that people lock up their 
investment and sit on it.  There's no question that it hurts the 
flow of capital, and it has to be corrected.  	<p> 
 
		And I speak to this strictly from experience.  We, in 
the state of South Carolina, reformed the entire Tax Code, and we 
cut the capital gains tax, and we cut a lot of other rates.  And 
everybody said, "Well, we will go broke."<p> 
 
		It was just the opposite.  I just talked to my 
successor this last weekend.  And he said, "You're not going to 
believe it."  He said, "We had a $600 million surplus this year."  
And he cut the rates again.  <p> 
 
		That was an interesting -- it's an interesting thing.  
I don't think that people understand it.  	<p> 
 
		The point I'm getting to is we've got to get across to 
the American people that a capital gains tax cut is not for the 
wealthy, it's not for the rich.  It creates jobs, it unlocks 
capital, and it creates wealth in this country.  <p> 
 
		And we have suffered for years every time we raise the 
term "capital gains reduction" or "eliminate the tax," that all 
this is something for the rich.<p> 
 
		The best example that was ever given to me was a lady 
that started a small beauty shop, worked in it for years and 
years, and wanted to sell it.  And she found out that she was 
going to have to pay the tax on it, and the appreciation of that 
little piece of property.  The compounding up really had caused 
her to sit down and put pencil to paper.  And she found out that 
she really wasn't going to make anything out of it if she sold 
it.<p> 
 
		And she explained that to me in very simple terms.  And 
I think that's what has got to be explained to the American 
people.  <p> 
 
		But that's what's happening to us in our economy.  And 
I really appreciate what you've had to say to us.  I think you're 
very eloquent, and I hope a lot of people listen.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Good.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Thank you.  Thank you, sir. <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Connie, unless there are any last-minute questions, we'll get Dick 
Armey back up here.<p> 
 
		Thanks again for a great session with us.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Well, thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  We wish you well.	<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  Thank you very much.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  We're glad you're chairman of the Joint 
Economic Committee.<p> 
 
		<b>SENATOR MACK</b>:  So am I, Mr. Chairman.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 

		(End tape 2, side 1)<p> 
 
	<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  The Commission cannot afford to buy 
your book, Dick.  So, we're looking forward to getting 
autographed copies.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Well, thank you, gentlemen.  Since 
my royalties from the book are dedicated to charity, I can't 
afford to buy my book either.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  This is the highest form of charity.  <p> 
 
<center><b><a name="Richard K. Armey">FURTHER REMARKS OF CONGRESSMAN RICHARD K. ARMEY</a></b></center> 
<p> 
 
<center><b>MAJORITY LEADER, U.S. HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES</b></center> 
<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I want to thank you, first of all, 
for letting me come back.  		And if I may, before Senator 
Mack leaves, just mention, as usual, having the privilege of 
having some time to sit and listen to Connie Mack, I've learned 
something.  And I'm sure that I'll be borrowing some of his lines 
in the next couple of days.<p> 
 
		And, Mr. Chairman --	<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Oh, I'm sorry.	<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  -- I'm like the plumber on 
Saturday, I am at your disposal.			<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Jack Faris wants to start off -- of 
NFIB.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Jack.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FARIS</b>:  Mr. Leader, thank you for being 
here, and for going back and forth and making the votes.	<p> 
 
		Business owners, especially small business owners, feel 
like that they're -- they've become more tax collectors for the 
government than they have entrepreneurs.  Many of them would 
never start if they knew the threats that they would have to 
being in business. 	<p> 
 
		We've heard from everyone today saying that "We want to 
sponsor growth and new job creation."  <p> 
 
		We know that basically happens on Main Street today.<p> 
 
		What is in your plan and proposal that takes -- that 
gives some relief to the small business owner who is chief cook, 
bottle-washer, accountant, everything, within the company, the 
business that they have, but wants to make life easier and more 
simple for them as the government's number one tax collector?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Well, Jack, I welcome that 
question.  And incidentally, I might mention I have an article 
that is coming out in <i>Policy Review</i> in the July issue that 
addresses the whole question of a national sales tax, because 
here I think is where the small business owner, particularly the 
retail merchant in America, really falls into harm's way with 
respect to this obligation of being tax collector for the state 
and making a life very complex and threatened.<p> 
 
		It is my contention that under a national sales tax the 
IRS will have a more complex job than it has today.  It will 
become a bigger agency, and it will become a more aggressive 
agency as they walk into every retail store in America, ask to 
check your inventories, check your sales receipts, check your 
purchase orders, and "Let me see if you're doing my job good 
enough to suit me."  And I think that's going to be a terrible 
experience.<p> 
 
		The flat tax says, to the small business owner, "You 
can take your inventory expenses at the time of purchase.  You 
can take your investment expenses at the time of purchase."  <p> 
 
		You have, then, in terms of the complexities of your 
Tax Code, two items of relief in terms of how you handle 
inventory and how you handle capital investment.<p> 
 
		We will allow you to deduct any normal necessary 
business expense.  And after you deduct that expense and reduce 
yourself to your net earnings, you pay a simple flat rate, which 
is the same rate that we apply to anything.  <p> 
 
		And the important thing about the flat tax, as I 
envision it, is that you capture every dollar of income earned in 
the Nation and tax it one time with a single flat rate, whether 
it be earned through business enterprise or through individual 
enterprise.  <p> 
 
		And, of course, that can only apply to net earnings.  <p> 
 
		I believe the complexity of the Code, as faced by the 
small business, will be less than it is today.  Unfortunately, we 
can find no way to give any business enterprise a code that will 
be as simple as that for the individual.  <p> 
 
		The business owner may, as we work out -- and I might 
say, by the way, we do have a team of people that are working on 
transition rules, and I think the transition rules must be 
premeditated.  They can't be worked out at the <p> 
 
11th hour.  <p> 
 
		They've got to be thought out, because if you read <i>The 
Showdown in Gucci Gulch</i>, you'll find out the transition rules is 
where all the mystery was done in '86.<p> 
 
		But as we examine that, one of the things we have to 
focus our attention on is the peculiarities of transitioning for 
-- especially the small business.<p> 
 
		(Pause)<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Dean Kleckner was the next, and then --	<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER KLECKNER</b>:  Mr. Armey, I'm a farmer from 
Iowa, president of the Farm Bureau.  I also on the National 
Economic Commission with Senator Domenici back in -- seven years 
ago, in '87, '88.  <p> 
 
		We were established at that time to be a cover for a 
tax increase, which we didn't recommend, kind of shocked some 
people.  But I think most commissions -- although we're not an 
official government commission like the NEC was -- are put in as 
a cover to do something.<p> 
 
		Have things changed?  That's my first question.  Have 
things changed today in the country that commissions and groups, 
study groups, that you're really interested in what we say?  Or 
is it predetermined and that we're in general a cover for 
something?<p> 
 
		The second one -- more direct, a follow-up with Jack 
Faris' question, and Ken Blackwell's earlier -- I guess where you 
came back on capital gains tax.  Farmers are -- have tremendous 
value in the increases in value, largely inflation increases.		<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER KLECKNER</b>:  How will -- and farmers aren't 
be sold today as a result of that, so the government -- 28 
percent of nothing is less than 14 percent of something would be.  
		But how will the capital gains increase when tremendous 
values of farmland are sold, and triple probably or quadruple 
values are then accumulated from when they were bought 30 years 
ago?  <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Let me first talk about cover.  We 
have at least three -- well, four -- at least four very good tax 
proposals that are being talked about in the Nation today, the 
Nunn-Domenici proposal, Bill Archer's emphasis on the national 
sales tax, my own iteration of the flat tax, and then we have 
Senator Specter with a different iteration of the flat tax.  
These are complex and difficult issues.<p> 
 
		In my judgment, nobody that advances these issues feels 
any qualms about the standing of their personal political 
popularity with America.  I can tell you I don't need any cover.  
I'm afraid that somebody in America may not notice that I should 
credit for the flat tax.<p> 
 
		So, I mean, certainly there's nobody seeking cover in 
this venture.  But I do think the Majority Leader of the Senate 
and Speaker of the House said these are complex ideas, they're 
all good ideas.  How do we sort through these ideas?  <p> 
 
		And we need to find people that have a proven, 
demonstrated expertise, background, and understanding that will 
have the time and the ability to sort through these ideas and 
make us a recommendation.  <p> 
 
		I don't consider that the search for cover as much as I 
see that as the search for a rational decision-making process.  
The fact of the matter is the Speaker is a very busy person.  The 
Majority Leader of the Senate is a very busy person.  <p> 
 
		The complexity, as you will learn, is so varied and 
diversified, they need your advice.<p> 
 
		Capital gains -- if I -- and let me just say, if I were 
-- this is going to be a fun statement.  I'll only get to say 
this once in my life.  If I were a farmer in Iowa, I would love 
Dick Armey.  And why do I say that?<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Are you running for something?	<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  No. I'm just saying that -- I think 
there are one or two farmers in Iowa that don't love Dick Armey.  
(Laughter)<p> 
 
		But still -- but in terms of tax reform and the flat 
tax, capital gains gets treated properly.  It's zero capital 
gains.<p> 
 
		We have a nomenclature with respect to capital gains 
today that I find personally difficult.  <p> 
 
		We talk about reducing the capital gains tax rate.  And 
inevitably somebody will talk about a preferential capital gains 
tax rate, and that just burns me up, because what, in fact, we're 
talking about is a less prejudicial capital gains tax rate.  <p> 
 
		Without basis adjustment for inflation, we have people 
paying capital gains taxes on capital losses.  <p> 
 
		And -- I think Carrol Campbell just related a story -- 
the fact of the matter is we zero capital gains, and that 
provides an enormous confidence that I can make an investment, 
take the risk.  And if it proves out and I have success, I can 
realize the benefits of that success.<p> 
 
		The other thing that I think is and should be of 
particular interest to the American farmer is the inheritance 
tax.  We do away with it.  My own view is that the federal 
government of the United States should not be the world's largest 
grave robber. <p> 
 
		But if you think of a farm family, you struggle in that 
farm, you work and you work and you build maybe some value, and 
maybe it accumulates over the years, and you manage to eke out a 
living on the farm and you've taken your son and your daughter, 
and you've sent them to school, and every year of your life you 
just got by, by putting another maintenance job on the old car, 
and so on down the line.  <p> 
 
		And then all of a sudden on one day you die, and those 
children of yours get assaulted by the government because they're 
king for a day.  <p> 
 
		On one day, the day of my death, my kids get to be 
rich, and the government comes and takes half of it away from 
them.  That's very little incentive.  <p> 
 
		And I have to tell you, if I'm given the choice between 
working for the financial well-being of the federal government 
and that of my children, I'll work a lot harder for the financial 
well-being of my children, and I'll build more and I'll build 
bigger, and I'll build more successful because of my children.<p> 
 
		Capital gains is another case where you're king for a 
day.  You just barely made a living off the farm for 30 years and 
then you sell the farm, and all of a sudden, you find yourself in 
the upper 1 percent of the income strata and somebody to be 
disdained, right?   And then we take it away.  <p> 
 
		And then, whatever you've got left after the government 
has taken their capital gains hit on you is what you've got to 
live off for the rest of your life when you go back to being a 
poor boy, you know.<p> 
 
		And these treatments I think are abusive and, quite 
frankly, not only -- it's a typical case of adding insult to 
injury.   <p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  They've heard about you in California, 
too.  Matt Fong has a question -- State Treasurer of California.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER FONG</b>:  Earlier, before you made your 
presentation, we heard from Chairman Archer and Senator Nunn.  
Both focused on one element, saying that it's very important for 
this new tax policy to have notice to address the issue of the 
global economy.<p> 
 
		What I found interesting, <p> 
 
Chairman Archer professed that he was originally, some time ago, 
before, in favor of the flat tax, but now stated that he did not 
think that the flat tax properly addressed the global economy.<p> 
 
		And Senator Nunn talked us through a very quick example 
of how the value-added tax gave a European -- and he used the 
example, a European manufacturer -- a competitive advantage over, 
say, an American manufacturer who has to incorporate his income 
tax into his price overseas.  <p> 
 
		So, can you address that issue?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Yes.  And this is a serious issue, 
and I've tried to give it serious thought, the question of border 
adjustability.  <p> 
 
		I take a generalized lesson about economics and public 
policy in this, that if you want to correct something, you don't 
do it by distorting the price system.  <p> 
 
		I think you can apply that principle to rent subsidies, 
or you can apply to agriculture policy.  You can apply it in any 
number of different ways.<p> 
 
		But what you're doing with these various forms of 
border adjustment is essentially you're dumping in the 
international tax market through the Tax Code by saying to 
foreign purchasers, "You can by American-made products at a lower 
price than what American purchasers buy."  <p> 
 
		I, frankly, don't think that's particularly fair to the 
American consumer.  <p> 
 
		And I am admonished by Adam Smith to remember that the 
ultimate end of economic activity is consumption, and to the 
effect that the government intervene in the affairs of the 
economy, it should do so on behalf of the consumer, not the 
producer.<p> 
 
		So, my own standard, it doesn't meet the public policy 
test of what is the national interest.<p> 
 
		So, I have these reservations about it. But I think -- 
more importantly, I don't think it will work.  I don't think 
you're going to correct an imbalance of trade.  <p> 
 
		As long as a nation remains dependent upon 
international capital sources to finance their investment, you're 
going to have to have a deficit in the current account in order 
to have a surplus in the capital account.<p> 
 
		Now, what does capital gains do -- or, I'm sorry, what 
does the flat tax do?  T<p> 
 
		The flat tax liberates American saving and investment 
for American investment, makes us less dependent upon foreign 
investment, and allows, then, the natural increased productivity 
and efficiency of a growing American economy to set straight this 
balance of trade.  <p> 
 
		But that becomes, then, another dilemma, because 
economies that grow faster will always have trade deficits with 
economies that grow slower.  And so you're blessing becomes your 
curse.<p> 
 
		Now, the thing that I think we ought to finally end up 
with, looking at this, while we bother ourself -- first of all, I 
believe governments have an inherent ability to bother themselves 
with things that are none of their own business.  <p> 
 
		Their lack of restraint is that they are fundamentally 
an institution that exists for the purpose of tending to other 
people's business, and they don't have any sense of discipline 
about it.  <p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		But international trade transactions are not 
transactions between governments.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  That's right.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  They're transactions between 
people.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Absolutely.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  So, why should the federal 
government --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Right on.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  -- tip the terms of trade against 
the American citizens?<p> 
 
		So, it strikes me that it is a misguided policy and one 
that is not likely to work out very well in the first place.<p> 
 
		And I frankly, because of this, have very little 
obsessive concern about border adjustability except insofar as I 
have some fear that somebody will actually bite on it and enact 
it.	<p> 
 
		I probably have said more than a prudent man should.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  No.  This is so important, and all of 
us are sitting up here nodding our heads when you said that trade 
is not between governments, it's between people.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Mm-hmm.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  And it's the freedom of an individual 
man or woman to purchase anything they want in a marketplace that 
you are defending.  And that is what the classical liberal 
tradition is.  I didn't mean to comment on it, but I was just 
saying the irony.<p> 
 
		We're sitting here, and the President of the United 
States is going to slap on -- who knows if they're going to make 
a last-minute agreement, but he's going to slap on a hundred 
percent tariffs on a certain product that will deny the American 
people the opportunity to purchase. 	<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Right.	<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  They said, "Well, they shipped it to us 
last year."  		<p> 
 
		Well, they didn't ship it to us without somebody making 
a choice in a marketplace freely without any cohesion to buy that 
product over someone else's product.  And that's called freedom.  
And that's why you're here.  	<p> 
 
		Ken Blackwell wants to ask you something.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER BLACKWELL:</b>  If I just might make --	<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  That's what your book is all about.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I believe that it is possible today 
for you to find a good book that will help you to understand that 
border adjustability.<p> 
 
		It swims against the tide of the freedom revolution.  
And we have to work on that a little bit --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  What -- who's the publisher, Dick?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Rennery (phonetic).<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Henry Rennery.		<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I'm probably out of line for even --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Where can we get it?<p> 
 
		<b>PARTICIPANT</b>:  Any bookstore.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Oh, I'm sure at any bookstore.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Any bookstore.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I'm sorry, I -- 	<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  You and Newt -- you and Newt Gingrich.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I indulge myself at your expense, 
and you're very tolerant of me.	<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  You and Gingrich are so shy about 
hawking your book.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  (Laughter)  I'm not.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Ken Blackwell.		<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER BLACKWELL</b>:  Representative Armey, as I 
understand your proposal, it does more than just simplify rates.  
It positions all income as either income to capital or income to 
labor.  <p> 
 
		Now, there are critics who would say that under your 
proposal dividend income is exempt.  <p> 
 
		How do you respond to a proposal that we allow for a 
personal consumption allowance on labor income and then just deal 
with all income, whether to labor or to capital, exactly the 
same?<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I appreciate that question.  <p> 
 
		Now, this is so -- we have so many fictions in what I 
call "the mythology of fairness in America."  And one of these 
fictions is the distinction between earned and unearned income.  <p> 
 
		First of all, no production takes place without some 
component combination of capital and labor.  We have, then, land 
in with capital.<p> 
 
		In fact, we have a very famous Democrat -- Senator -- 
named Senator Douglas that invented something called the "Cobb-Douglas Function," that showed you 
must have these combined so 
that you can provide a resource to the production process in the 
form of your labor or your capital.  And nobody will provide 
either unless they get some return on that provision.  	 
	I am not working for no pay, ladies and gentlemen.  I'm 
sorry, I'm not going to do it.  Nor am I going to make my capital 
available to you for no pay.  That's not selfish; that's just 
good sense.  I've got responsibilities to my family.<p> 
 
		So, what happens is the owners or the providers of 
capital generally become the owners of the business.  And in a 
large complex system of equity ownership as we have, they become 
stockholders.  Stockholders' share of earnings is dividends.  	<p> 
 
		What the flat tax does in its effort to capture every 
dollar's worth of earnings and tax at one time says, "We will tax 
those earnings generated by the capital component at the source, 
one time."<p> 
 
		So, when the business distributes dividends, it 
distributes after-tax earnings to the owners of the corporation.  
And so it seems to me that the fiction that somebody escapes 
taxation is without foundation.  <p> 
 
		Now, they'll boil this down to:  "Well, what happens if 
somebody inherited all his wealth?"  I always love this when 
Senator Rockefeller raises a point with me.  "That's not fair."<p> 
 
		You know, what can I say about that?  Some -- I mean, I 
didn't chose my parents so wisely from an economic point of view.  
They didn't have -- they weren't rich.  I mean, I thought I made 
a good choice in terms of their common sense and their good 
stewardship as parents, and I was lucky.  But some people are 
just lucky, they're born rich.<p> 
 
		I don't know what you're going to do about that.  I 
guess we can hate them forever.  But you don't do any economic 
good in the Nation by saying, "All right, therefore we must then 
punish you for your good fortune."<p> 
 
		What are you going to do with a basketball player?  
Gets a contract for <p> 
 
$5 million.  Now, I can't dribble a basketball.  I can dribble a 
football.  <p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		Nobody is going to pay me for playing basketball, but 
shall we --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Footballs are not supposed to be 
dribbled.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  I know that, but I can do it.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Wrong.<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  But in any event --see, this, to 
me, falls clearly under the category of jealousy, envy, and 
frankly, I think, greed.  And it is not the better part of our 
American disposition to get fascinated by that.	<p> 
 
		Now, about the flat tax and going back to our failure 
in '86, I have to tell you, you must, then, accept this 
proposition.  It is fair to capture every dollar earned in the 
tax base and treat it all the same, with a single rate for all.<p> 
 
		And my motto is:  Stay flat or die.  When you start 
making exemptions, exceptions, you know, whether it be for the 
honorable motive of giving advantage to something you think is an 
honorable activity or for the what I consider dishonorable motive 
of punishing somebody because they happen to have some good 
fortune -- most often born out of your hard work, by the way -- 
then I think what you're going to do is destroy the simplicity 
and the honesty of the Code.  	<p> 
 
		And then, I could say, "Well, you take anybody that has 
over $500,000 a year annual income, irrespective of whether they 
earned their education it or inherited it, and punish them."  
Now, why?<p> 
 
		So, I know we have these detractors, but I think it is 
detractors that come from people that don't understand the 
purpose of a Tax Code.  <p> 
 
		The purpose of a Tax Code is to raise money to finance 
the government at the minimal imposition on the American people.  
It is not to create an equality of outcome or to somehow or 
another exercise that frankly can only in its bottom line be 
described as a bold-faced prejudice.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  We're going to close up at 1 o'clock.  
So, let's get some questions.<p> 
 
		John Wieland.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER WIELAND</b>:  Mr. Leader, thank you for being 
here, and thank you for spending so much time with us.<p> 
 
		I am a homebuilder and realtor, and I am also the 
chairman of the Heard (phonetic) Museum of Art in Atlanta, so 
exemptions are very dear to my heart.<p> 
 
		How are we going to be able to protect all the 
Americans who have invested in homes and made a 30-year decision, 
you know, based on the existing Tax Code?  How are we going to be 
able to encourage home ownership, which we all believe is the 
bedrock of, you know, much of our culture?  <p> 
 
		And I hate to think that Americans aren't generous, but 
I think that there is some correlation between the deductibility 
of charitable contributions and the willingness to give.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  There's a lot of anxiety about 
this.  And one of the things I would ask, too, one must always 
look at if, in fact, you find yourself living in a world where 
you have a special break or opportunity or advantage, such as a 
mortgage interest deduction, and it's precious to you, as it is 
to our homeowners today, you're going to have an obvious anxiety 
about living in a world where that special opportunity doesn't 
exist, but yet that's what I ask you to do.  <p> 
 
		Don't think about being in this world, of this Tax 
Code, without the home mortgage, because I, too, would fight 
that.  Think in terms of a whole new world, called the "Flat Tax 
World," where there's a growth, a growing opportunity.  <p> 
 
		Recognize, if you will, to my shock, less than 25 
percent of American homeowners take the home interest mortgage.  	<p> 
 
		I would argue that the -- incidentally, what I consider 
to be the second most important American Dream, to own your own 
home -- the first being to get your kids out of it --<p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		-- the American Dream, to own your own home, is 
prompted by impulses that are so far greater in your life than 
the Tax Code.  People aren't going to quit buying homes if we 
have a new tax world without that exemption.<p> 
 
		And I would suggest that when you look at what happens 
with interest rates -- and everybody agrees, even DRI, that did 
the study for the realtors, agrees the interest rates will go 
down, you get a compensation to the homeowner in terms of their 
affordability of a home.  <p> 
 
		When they have a more certain understanding that they 
will more certainly have a better job with a greater opportunity 
for a promotion and advancement in a growing economy, and they 
make that life decision on what home to buy or when and where to 
trade up.<p> 
 
		I have to tell you, if I were a realtor today, if I 
made my living out of home real estate transactions, I would pray 
for the "Flat Tax World," where I had  a growing economy, where 
more people had better jobs, with a more certain understanding 
I'd get my promotion and my pay raise and lower interest rates, 
and I know I'd sell more, better, bigger homes.<p> 
 
		But one must first, it seems, extricate oneself from 
one's own worst fears.  And that is a tough thing, because the 
flat tax is not a revision of the existing Tax Code.  The flat 
tax is a new tax code in a new world.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Herman Cain.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN</b>:  Congressman, thank you for being 
here.<p> 
 
		One of several of our presenters in the course of our 
meetings have brought up the issue relative to the flat tax 
proposal, the issue of investing in human capital.  <p> 
 
		As I understand it, under the flat tax proposal, it's 
basically revenue, amount of expenses, mostly in terms of 
financial capital, et cetera, human capital being how do we 
invest in the development of the human capital side of the 
equation long term with respect to growth.  How would you respond 
to that?  	<p> 
 
		And if I'm not mistaken, the flat tax approach, with no 
deductions, does not directly invest in human capital, or does 
it? <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  The first thing you need to 
understand is a flat tax says that if there's going to be a 
public program in support of education, job training, that should 
be done on the expenditure side.<p> 
 
		But the Tax Code is about raising money.  And so I 
would say that the human capital question is not a question for 
the Tax Code, and it is a function.	<p> 
 
		But if I may, governments, I think, do particularly 
poor jobs of investing in human capital.  Government-sponsored 
training programs and so forth generally don't work out too well.<p> 
 
		I have a great deal of affection for the machinists in 
America.  They work together, and they are pushing an encouraging 
-- and getting very little support from any government entity -- 
a whole system of apprenticement.<p> 
 
		A young person going on a job, learning that job from a 
person who has been on that job, who knows they're going to work 
with and rely on that person beside them on the job, is going to 
learn the job and learn it right.<p> 
 
		Mike Berg, who didn't have an eighth grade education, 
taught me my job as an apprentice lineman when I was going to 
college.  And he was concerned, because if he's sitting on a pole 
and he hollers for a come-along, and I send him a coffin hoist, 
I've made his day worse off.  It was very important to him that I 
learn his job right.<p> 
 
		Government programs for human capital, in my 
estimation, become slush buckets for providers of human capital 
training.  So, I have a wariness about those programs.<p> 
 
		But what do we do with the Tax Code -- with the flat 
tax?  <p> 
 
		We say to the American family <p> 
 
wage-earner, "We will make it maximum possible for you to 
maintain for your own family's use, with a generous family 
allowance to begin with and then a low marginal rate, the maximum 
amount of your earnings."<p> 
 
		"And then, Mom and Dad, you decide what's the best 
school for your children, where is the best college for your 
children, what is the best training program."  <p> 
 
		And I dare say that in your pizza shop you probably, 
without any assistance from the federal government, have done a 
much better job of teaching youngsters the disciplines of 
workmanship, what Thorstein Veblen calls "the spirit of 
workmanship."  These things truly are learned by young people as 
they grow up.  <p> 
 
		And I hate to use the word "boondoggle" -- but I dare 
say that if I were going to use that word, I would probably be 
talking about government-sponsored program of investment in human 
capital.  So --<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Any last minute questions?  Shirley 
Peterson.  And then Education Feulner.<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER PETERSON</b>:  Congressman, thank you for 
being here today. <p> 
 
		I find many aspects of your proposal; very attractive.  
There's one aspect of it, however, that worries me.  As a former 
tax administrator, I have a concern about compliance.  <p> 
 
		And I am concerned that compliance would drop 
precipitously if we did not have withholding.  And I would like 
to hear your views on that subject.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Well, this is a -- it's probably 
the most controversial and <p> 
 
high-risk part of my proposal, and you'll find it probably in 
nobody's proposal.  <p> 
 
		The flat tax is, in a general sense, a Tax Code that 
bets on the goodness of the American people and not the guile of 
the federal government.  <p> 
 
		And it's a Tax Code, as I've envisioned it, that says 
to America, "We're going to give you a simple, direct, and honest 
bill for the size of big government and let you see as clearly as 
possible what it's costing you, because we bet that if you know 
how much it's costing you, you will vote for less big 
government."<p> 
 
		Now, in my scheme, I say to America, "We're not going 
to have a system of withholding.  We're going to ask you to sit 
down at your kitchen table the first of every month, and as you 
write your bills to here, there, and everywhere and you look at 
your Penney's bill and wonder, 'Did I get money's worth,' when 
you look at your rent bill or your mortgage payment and say to 
them, 'Am I getting my money's worth,' then you will write a 
check to Washington, D.C."  <p> 
 
		And you'll realize that "This is more than I paid for 
food, shelter, and clothing combined, and I wonder if I'm getting 
my money's worth?"	<p> 
 
		I think that's a healthy question for the American.<p> 
 
		Now, people say, "Well, Americans won't pay."  <p> 
 
		With all the enforcement power of the federal 
government, why would the same person who doesn't dare not pay 
their Penney's bill turn around and say, "But I'm not going to 
pay my IRS bill"?<p> 
 
		And I'll remind you what I had said earlier, there are 
many, many people in the world with whom I would pick a fight.  
The <p> 
 
IRS is not one of them. <p> 
 
		(Laughter)<p> 
 
		So, I honestly don't.  <p> 
 
		On the other hand, I think if a people say, "I got a 
fair, direct, honest bill that treated me the same as everybody 
else.  I know what my share of the cost is, and I can quickly 
compute what my neighbor's share is.  I know he's got to pay it," 
I think the goodness of the American people would come out, and 
compliance becomes less of a problem.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  But before we give <p> 
 
Ed Feulner the last question, I'd like for the press to know and 
our television audience to hear that we're taking this on the 
road.  	Bill Archer suggested that we do that in order to 
maximize the impact of the tax reform movement on the American 
people.  <p> 
 
		And we're going to be holding hearings in Boston; 
Omaha, Nebraska; Charlotte, <p> 
 
North Carolina; and Silicon Valley, California <p> 
 
-- among other things.		<p> 
 
		I told Charlie Rangel that I would like to see us maybe 
go into East Harlem or "Bed Sty" and talk about the particular 
problems of minority entrepreneurial-minded men and women. <p> 
 
		Matt Fong and I have talked about going into Watts and 
East L.A. to talk about minority entrepreneurship, but that is 
subject to the decisions to be made.  	<p> 
 
		But, Dick, we want to thank you so much for --<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  May I make a point?<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  -- your pedagogy. <p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  One point, Herman Cain, apparently 
I did not understand your question properly and went off on one 
of my tirades.  <p> 
 
		One of the things that I think will happen in a flat 
tax world is charitable contributions will go up.  We saw this in 
the '80s.  We reduced the tax value of a charitable contribution 
enormously in the '80s and, frankly, I might add, confounded it, 
so that you can't make a charitable contribution without a tax 
lawyer these days.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Mm-hmm.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  50 percent of the American people 
do not -- or 50 percent of the charitable contributions are never 
taken on taxes, and yet charitable contributions more than 
doubled in the '80s.  And I think that that's where you get 
investments in human capital that really pay off.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Yes.<p> 
 
		?? Southern sounding:  I just might add that I do not 
propose or support government-sponsored human capital programs.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		And finally, I --<p> 
 
		<b>COMMISSIONER</b>:  So, I want to point that out for the 
record.  That was not the intent of my question or the point that 
I was alluding to.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  Oh, I appreciate that.  I knew 
that all along.  <p> 
 
		If I may miss Jack -- and final out to Shirley 
Peterson, when you go on the road and you ask people, "How about 
withholding?  Should --or should we or should we not have it?" -- 
one of the things you're going to find people express in a rather 
assertive fashion:  "It's my money in the first place.  Why 
should the government take some part of my money before I even 
get a chance to see it?"<p> 
 
		There's a certain assertiveness about that.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Bill.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARCHER</b>:  This would be a good way to end 
it.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Yes.  That is a great ending.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Thank you again.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  Dick, thanks.  Well done.<p> 
 
		<b>CONGRESSMAN ARMEY</b>:  Thank you.<p> 
 
		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP</b>:  World class. <p> 
 
		Thank you all for coming.  <p> 
 
		The Commission will close our public hearings and get a 
bite to eat and discuss our next meeting.<p> 
 
		Staff is welcome to join us as well.<p> 
 (Whereupon, the public hearing of the National 
Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform was adjourned.)<p> 
