<a name="Renner"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY JEFF RENNER<br>
PRINCIPAL OFFICER, THE FREEMAN CO., INC.</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


		MR. RENNER:  Thank you, Chairman Kemp and
members of the Commission.<p>

		I'm a small businessman, also, primarily
engaged in banking and real estate.  However, I've also
had 15 years of experience in government.<p>

		You've heard an awful lot of reasons today why
there should be a major overhaul of the Nation's Tax
Code.  <p>

		But the single over-riding reason is this, that
the current Tax Code is an enormous waste of
everybody's time.<p>

		A Heritage Foundation study estimated that
Americans spend 5.4 billion manhours annually complying
with the Tax Code and with tax planning and record-keeping and tax return preparation.<p>

		And I saw a recent article in the Wall Street
Journal that estimated that the current Tax Code costs
our economy 6 billion hours annually.<p>

		So, I did some quick calculations.  That's the
equivalent of 10,000 lifetimes wasted every year.<p>

		According to the Tax Foundation, the compliance
costs for the federal income tax last year cost
American business alone $127 billion.  And it cost all
Americans $200 billion.  That's an amount equal to the
output of our automobile, truck, and aircraft
industries combined. <p>

		That time and effort and money did not educate
a single child, it didn't feed a single family, and it
didn't produce a single tangible product to improve the
life of anyone.<p>

		The main reason for this waste of time and
money is the sheer complexity of the Tax Code.  In its
present form, it's impossible for many Americans to
even comply with the tax laws simply because they can't
understand it.<p>

		I had the personal experience at one time of
being told by the government to handle a transaction in
a certain manner, only to be audited and later told
that it should have been done differently.  <p>

		Unfortunately, ignorance of the law is no
excuse for we American citizens.  But equally as
unfortunate, the ignorance of the law seems to be the
only excuse required of our employees.<p>

		Another focus of the Commission's work is the
basic principles and objectives that the reform plan
must embody.  And I would suggest that these are three: 
Simplicity, stability, and fairness.<p>

		A recent Andersen Consulting survey revealed
that simpler forms and filing instructions were among
individuals' top tax concerns.  And I saw another
survey that showed that over 70 percent of the college
graduates in this country can't compute their own
taxes.<p>

		Now, our Tax Code should be simple enough so
that an individual is able to prepare and file his or
her own tax return.<p>

		I'm one of those college graduates who can't
file his own tax return.  And last year it cost me over
$5,000 just to file my own personal tax return.  And
that's ridiculous.<p>

		The current complexity of the Tax Code leads, I
think, to this instability.  In an eight-year period,
we've seen six major tax bills pass the Congress.  <p>

		And these constant attempts to correct or fine
tune the Tax Code lead to more change and more
uncertainty, making it impossible for individual
Americans to meaningfully plan for their own future.<p>

		Americans need to be able to understand what
the Tax Code is and know that it's going to remain
reasonably stable.<p>

		Finally, the Tax Code must be fair, and this is
the most difficult term to define.  But we do know that
the current Tax Code pits organized special interest
groups with money and lobbyists against families with
children and limited resources.  They can't compete in
that arena.<p>

		The current tax compliance system costs small
businesses proportionately 10 times more than large
corporations, as Mr. Henry pointed out.<p>

		A fair Tax Code, I suppose, would be one that's
more uniform, that would tax all income without special
exceptions and loopholes, hopefully at a lower rate;
that it would tax all income the same way, regardless
of the source, and would tax it only once. <p>

		By eliminating the complexity and introducing
stability and fairness through uniformity, I think that
we, as a nation, can redirect our time and energy and
resources toward production and economic growth.<p>

		Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Great.  Thank you.<p>

		Thank all of you.  Very eloquent.<p>

		Herman Cain -- Mr. Cain.<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Thank you, Chairman Kemp. <p>

		I want to direct my question.  I would like to
ask all of you the question, but time only allows me to
direct the question to just two of you.  <p>

		So, Mr. Renner and Mr. Hayes -- Frank -- I'll
direct it.<p>

		When I was asked to participate on this
Commission by Jack Kemp and Newt Gingrich, one of the
reasons I said yes, that I would participate, was
because the charge was not to come up with incremental
changes to a system that is as screwed up as all of you
have indicated, but to replace the current system.<p>

		And, Jerry, when you were talking about the
mind-set that we've got to break with the American
public in order to replace, which is a revolutionary
jump from where we are today, it's going to take a
couple of things:<p>

		One, there has to be a groundswell with respect
to the American public that will put the pressure on
the politicians to be able to make that leap.<p>

		My question is:  What, in your opinion, are
some of the things we can do to create the proper
groundswell that will give it the necessary momentum
that will cause the lawmakers to make the necessary
leap that we have to make if we all collectively are
going to be successful at replacing the current Tax
Code?<p>

		Yes.  Start with you, Jerry.  And then Frank.<p>

		<b>MR. RENNER:</b>  Well, we could spend a long time
or a short period of time.  I think I'll go short.<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Okay.<p>

		<b>MR. RENNER</b>:  It is clear to me that when the
American public is given good information, they almost
always make good decisions.  <p>

		And I wrote a letter to Mr. Gingrich as soon as
the Congress changed this last time -- which I will
forward a copy to you -- and warned him that if we
balance the budget without the public's understanding
of tax policy and so forth, that we, the Republicans --
excuse me for doing that, but that's what I am -- would
end up suffering, because people would be critical of
stuff that was done properly because they wouldn't
understand it.<p>

		I believe what you are doing will do more than
any other single thing, but you have to not just go to
Omaha, Nebraska, you have to go to Cozad, Nebraska --
not necessarily you, but you could have subcommittees. 
But if people really understand things, I think we're
okay.<p>

		One example, look at all the people that
believe that they themselves have paid for their Social
Security benefits and their Medicare.  They actually
believe it.  And until they understand the facts,
they're not going to change it.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Frank Hayes.<p>

		<b>MR. HAYES:</b>  Yes.  Herman, I think, just to echo
what Mr. Renner said, it has to be understandable.  <p>

		And that's why I like the flat tax, because if
the average individual does not understand it -- and
right now nobody, pretty much, understands the Tax Code
unless you work with it every single day -- if you
don't get that understanding on the part of the average
individual, if you do not reach that as part of your
recommendations, then you won't, in my estimation, have
the groundswell of support, because people won't know
what they're for.  <p>

		So, it has to be something that is simple
enough that it's understandable to the average person.  <p>

		And if you don't get that, I doubt very
seriously if you're going to get the groundswell of
support, because nobody is going to understand it.  <p>

		And I guess that's what Mr. renner said, and I would just echo that.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Thanks.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Commissioner Kleckner.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  Thank you, Jack.<p>

		Incidentally, we're in Omaha, Nebraska, but
right across the river is Council Bluffs, Iowa, my home
state.  	<p>

		So, Herman, do I have your permission to
welcome everybody --<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Yes, Dean.	<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  -- all over Iowa?  <p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  Yes.  Yes, you have my
permission.<p>

		(Laughter)  <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- Iowa.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  It's been a --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Is there something going on in
Iowa that we ought to know about?<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  The corn is growing
good, and I sell -- I'm a corn and soybean hog raiser
and sell hogs.  And Herman buys some of them to put in
the topping of Godfather's Pizza that we're going to
eat this noon.<p>

		<b>COMMISSIONER CAIN:</b>  That's right.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  You're going to be
eating my pork this noon from my farm in northern Iowa,
Jack.<p>

		This has been a great panel.  And small
business and farmers come next, and that's also small
business.  And that's the backbone of this country.<p>

		We're hearing about the mega, the Disney and
the ABC merger now.  But you know, the real jobs are
being created by the Herman Cains and all of you and
the small business.<p>

		Just a comment.  My farm -- I made -- Mr.
Hayes, I made tax decisions, as farmers still do,
rather than economic decisions.  The years we had the
investment tax credit by buying or not buying at the
end of the year.  <p>

		Now that we've lost income-averaging, farmers
and, I think, probably some small business, too, I'll
bet you Mr. Thom and his irrigation business, it goes
up and down some years.  But at least farmers have
tremendous shifts in income.  We've lost income-averaging.  We try to do it ourselves. <p>

		I do it by not selling hogs at the end of the
year, delaying till the next year, A lousy economic
decision, but a tax decision, and either buying or not
buying inputs in the first of the year to try to level
out my own income tax.<p>

		What, as a CPA -- and I presume you may do some
farmers' -- ranchers' returns, what do you -- how do
you assess this?  What do you do?  What do you think
should be done, for example, with the extremes of
income that farmers have?  How would you attempt to
level that out?  One or two things that you'd like to
see done to do that.<p>

		 <b>MR. HAYES:</b>  Well, it is a difficult question,
because whenever somebody asks me a question about a
particular tax issue, I always say, "It depends on the
circumstances."<p>

		And the reason that I say it, again, goes back
to the way the Code is structured, and that not
everyone fits the same idea or the same solution.<p>

		Not having income-averaging -- that went away
several years ago -- not having any kind of way to
balance your income out, I think it -- your question
really answers itself and that that's why you need a
simplification process.<p>

		I don't know if I can answer that question
specifically and say you need to do this or you need to
do that.  <p>

		But I think what you need to look at is say the
way the system is now.  There's almost nothing you can
do other than, like you said, delay the reporting of
the income until next year; spend as much money this
year as you can, even though you might not really want
to, it might not be the best thing to do.  But I think
simplification goes back to the answer.<p>

		If you know every single year -- when we do tax
planning, we sort of plan two years at a time.  And we
say, "Okay.  Let's look at a two-year span instead of a
one-year span.  And let's try to make as many good
decisions as we can within that two-year span to reduce
your tax burden."<p>

		What I would suggest is that if we go to a
simplified system, then that takes that decision out.  <p>

		I think one of the gentlemen said the amount of
money and effort and time that we spend in this, it
could be spent helping you make other types of
decisions that are going to be beneficial in the long
term, because I really think short-term -- tax
decisions are really short-term decisions.  And as a
businessperson <p>

-- and if you really want to be successful in business,
you have to make long-term decisions. <p>

		So, I think it's more or less tax
simplification is the answer.  I don't have any
specific recommendations that I can give you at this
point.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		(End tape 1, side 1)<p>

		MR. FARIS:  -- amounts to an inheritance tax
bill change, to change the death tax, make it a $4.2
million exclusion, and all taxes above that will be cut
in half from the current rates, which we are supporting
and applauding.  It's one of NFIB's targets for this
year.<p>

		How important is it to you, in our tax reform
look, to deal with estate taxes and to tax that day --
the capital gains tax the day you sell your business? 
How critical is that to you in terms of priorities for
us, in this Commission?<p>

		And I'd ask any of you who feel motivated to
answer that.<p>

		MR. <b>MR. THOM:</b>  Well, we spend a lot of time, since
my years is 70 years of age, trying to figure out how
we're going to be able to pass the business down.  And
many of our decisions are now made on that basis,
rather than on a good business judgment.  <p>

		And it's -- you know, I think estate tax is
more regressive than any tax that there is, because it
kills the goose that laid the golden egg.<p>

		And government -- it should be look at that. 
If you kill the goose, you get a big chunk right then,
but you don't get any from then on.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Jerald, do you want to make a
comment? <p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Yes, a quick comment. <p>

		Professionals, by and large, do not build much
equity.  It's a service business, and there's not a lot
that you can convert.  <p>

		But you asked me how important it is.  Nebraska
is a small business state.  I like the state.  And we
have farmers and ranchers and small business, and it's
critical to me and my family that people like Mr. Thom
have relief.<p>

		There's an article in today's Wall Street
Journal, concerning the Dole bill, about estate tax
relief.  I just thought I would quote one thing, which
I did in my written testimony.  It's about the attitude
of federal bureaucrats on taxes.<p>

		A Treasury official praises the idea of estate
tax relief for small family businesses, but says the
Dole bill -- and I quote -- "gives away too much money
to the very rich."<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes. <p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  It's as if it's their money to
give back. <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  That's the problem.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well said.  <p>

		Now, Allan Reynolds, chief research economist
for the Commission, reminded me that the estate tax
only raises $12 billion or so for the federal
government.  And it isn't a question of raising money
as much as it is punitive in nature.  <p>

		And each and every one of you -- I agree with
Jack Faris -- has been passionate about the subject of
how to grow this economy. And you can't do it by
confiscating the estate and the farm or the business of
the individual.<p>

		Loretta -- Commissioner Adams.  <p>

		COMMISSIONER ADAMS:  Thank you, Chairman.<p>

		Listening to all of you is very inspirational,
because I, too, am a small business owner.  <p>

		And I would like to see the outcome of this
Commission, as the title says, focus on economic growth
as well as tax reform, and want to be able to devote
much more of my energy to growing my company, rather
than see what I do with my taxes. <p>

		And one person just said -- and I remember
sitting with the accountant at the end of every fiscal
year -- "No, I'm not going to close those projects till
next year.  I don't care if the company looks larger on
paper.  I don't want to pay those taxes this year."<p>

		One of the things I've heard throughout here,
through the testimony, has to do with fairness.  And
some of you alluded to what you meant by "fairness."  <p>

		But you, in particular, Mr. Hayes, said
"fairness" at the very beginning.  And what do you mean
by "fairness" in the Tax Code as you envision it?<p>

		<b>MR. HAYES:</b>  Well, my perspective on fairness is
that if a person is doing things to grow their
business, to enhance their wealth, positive efforts
that the tax system be fair to that individual.  <p>

		It wasn't so much relative to one group of
people versus another, or a certain income level versus
another.  It was I need to feel, like, if I'm doing --
if I'm playing the game, if I'm doing it right, if I'm
playing fair as a business person, then the government
is fair with me and not taking away my incentive to do
so.  And I think that's what I meant by "fairness."  <p>

		It wasn't so much relative to different people,
but relative to my own particular situation.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well said.<p>

		Ted.	<p>

		COMMISSIONER FORSTMANN:  Yes, I was very taken
by what all of you said.  <p>

		And I have a question which maybe we could just
have everybody answer yes or no.  <p>

		And the basic question is going to be:  	
	If we could construct something that really didn't
have the government involved in citizens' decision-making at all, would you be in favor of it?<p>

		And I want to take two examples of things that
-- one that Mr.  Abramson said and one that Mr. Hayes
said.<p>

		Who is not in favor of charities, for example? 
Who is not?<p>

		(No response)<p>

