<a name="Bettger"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY BOB BETTGER<br>
FAIRMOUNT, IOWA</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>MR. BETTGER:</b>  Thank you, Mr. Chairman.<p>

		Mr. Chairman and members of the Commission, my
name is Bob Bettger.  I farm at Fairmount, Nebraska.  <p>

		You have a copy of my text, and I will deviate
off that, because that does specifically state Farm
Bureau policy and agriculture's concerns in this area.<p>

		So, I will get right into our specific
situation that my family and I have and how it relates
to our operation and taxes.<p>

		I farm with my father, who is basically retired
now, and two brothers.  And we have an irrigated corn
and soybean farm approximately two hours west of here.<p>

		Over the years, we have accumulated
approximately 3800 acres.  And the last few years, the
biggest thing we've had to plan for is estate taxes and
Social Security taxes and basically just income taxes.	<p>

		And what we've done, we set up three individual
corporations, my brothers and myself, and a general
partnership.  And what that has allowed us to do,
instead of incorporating all the income into one entity
and dividing it out, we have created three separate
entities.  <p>

		We take rents.  It greatly reduces our payments
on Social Security and Medicaid by doing it that way,
trying to also keep the corporations into a lower tax
bracket.<p>

		And as Mr. Kleckner stated, one of the things
we also have to do, because we were hit somewhat in '93
with the excessive rains -- and, as Mr. Cain can
remember, the central part of the state had a very
devastating windstorm go through, and we virtually had
a half a corn crop in '93 -- and without income-averaging, we are forced to adjust our sales
accordingly, hold back some grain from one year
possibly to sell in the next, and things like that just
to help even our tax load if we can from year to year.<p>

		So, I don't know -- there'll probably be some
questions later, but another thing is the health issue. 
That's another primary reason why we've gone to this
method.  We can deduct 100 percent of -- for our
families -- our health premiums and health costs by
doing it that way, also. <p>

		And it's kind of sad, because most of our
fathers and the older generation were brought up, as
you know, agriculture is just a way of life.  And
they've never had to really treat it as a business, the
way we have to today.  <p>

		You know, they were almost out of the old shoe-box method.  You know, they'd fill the bins up and sell
corn whenever they needed to.  But unfortunately now it
is strictly a business and for a lot of reasons,
because of taxes, and this is the way we have to
operate our farms.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  Thank you, Bob.	<p>

		In the absence of the Chairman, who said if he
wasn't back -- we want to thank you for being concise,
and there will be questions, I'm sure, for the panel or
comments.<p>

		We'll move now to Gary and Jackie, whichever
one of you wants to start.  <p>

		I've known you for some time.  And welcome to
this Commission hearing, and we're interested in your
comments.<p>

<a name="Muller"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY GARY AND JACKIE MULLER<br>
GRISWOLD, IOWA</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


		MR. MILLER:  Thank you, Dean.<p>

		Herman, the first thing I would like to say, if
I was going to create a grassroots groundswell
movement, I'd have you for my spokesman.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>COMMISSION CAIN:</b>  No, but thanks, Gary.<p>

		<b>MR. MULLER:</b>  This is Jackie, with a J.<p>

		Jackie and I would like to thank you, as a
board of Commissioners, for your effort and for your
thought put into this tax reform.<p>

		It's an honor to be here today to represent the
American farmers.  We've helped feed the world, and
we're proud to be part of that.  <p>

		For a country to remain strong, it needs a
safe, dependable, and an abundant food supply.  And we
have provided that.<p>

		But our ag sector is currently being weakened
by a system that is forcing us to make decisions based
on taxation, rather than sound economic principles.<p>

		We're going to speak to three issues today:  <p>

			Capital gains tax.<p>

			Estate tax.<p>

			And payroll taxes.<p>

		In 1869, my great-great-grandfather left
Germany because of political and economic oppression. 
He came to the United States to find greater
opportunity.  When he arrived in Iowa, he bought
farmland.  <p>

		In 1968, 99 years later, Jackie and I purchased
that land.  This land now will have a property tax
higher than the purchase price by several times.  And
this property tax must be paid whether or not we
produce anything on our farm.<p>

		One of the advantages of being a farmer is that
each farm family independently decides what plan best
suits their situation.  <p>

		For our personal situation, what makes the most
economic sense is to intensify our livestock
production. <p>

		 I have developed skills that have put me in a
position to build a world-class hog operation, a 3600-sow unit.  A unit like this will carry a price tag of
about $4 million, but it will still give us a very
favorable return on our investment.<p>

		The farmland that I would have to sell in a
quest for the capital could open up land for three
beginning farmers.  And an added benefit that this
project would give, it would be a ready market for the
grain that they would produce on this land.<p>

		However, the capital gains tax that we would
have to pay would deplete our holdings to the point
that it would be a foolish move.  So, instead of
creating a new economic opportunity for myself and
about 20 new employees, we've put the plans on hold.<p>

		Further, let me point out, if we should elect
to proceed with this project, the dollar amount will be
$2 to $3 million, too large to pass on to our children
because of estate tax.<p>

With the current exemption limit, they simply couldn't
afford to inherit it intact, thus making it difficult
for them to continue the projects that we've started.<p>

		We're not merely interested in surviving out on
the farm; we want to thrive.  But we are unable to make
our decisions based solely on our profit-and-loss
statement.  The tax ramifications have to be high on
our list of considerations.<p>

		Once again, the tentacles of taxation are
reaching through the economic lifeline of my farm and
are killing many projects before they're ever started.<p>

		We have the resources here in the Midwest to be
an effective competitor in a global economy, but the
tax system that inhibits our ability to compete needs
to be rethought.<p>

		Farming is unique from other businesses in our
inability to pass on the cost of taxation.  Farmers
don't set their own prices, and we're at the mercy of
the market because we're unable to hold our products
off the market.  <p>

		Our products are perishable, and we're unable
to hold them off the market to receive higher prices. 
It's not as simple as including higher taxes in the
selling price.  <p>

		Unnecessary taxes are stifling economic growth. 
What's needed is encouragement for myself and other
people like me who are willing to take risks and create
new jobs.  We certainly don't need any new hurdles to
jump over to do these things.  <p>

		Although not like my great-great-grandfather, I
don't plan to flee to another country, but I am turning
down opportunity based on the current tax structure
that my government is imposing on me.<p>

		I appreciate the opportunity to visit with you
this morning and make some brief points.  <p>

		I'd now like to have my better half talk about
payroll taxes.<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  At least you got that part right.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Good morning.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Good morning, Jackie.<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  Payroll taxes are filled with
complexities.  It must be remembered that unlike the
folks who make the regulations that we live by, farmers
do not have at their disposal a legion of accountants
and lawyers to comply with the payroll and employment
record-keeping.  This is a real burden on the small
businessmen who try to comply and are penalized if they
make a mistake.<p>

		Every payroll check is accompanied by a variety
of computations, partially determined by the marital
status of the recipient, amount of dependents, and
frequency of payment, all requiring different charts.<p>

		Each payroll check has a minimum of six
entries, including federal tax, state tax, unemployment
tax, Social Security and Medicare withholding and the
employer matching amount.<p>

		To untangle the complexities of making out the
payroll, I use a farm accounting computer program and
subscribe to a support service for trouble-shooting.  <p>

		Of course, when I have serious problems, I can
always depend on my concise, east-to-understand --<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		-- Circular A, Agricultural Employees' Tax
Guide to clear things up.<p>

		For example -- I've highlighted a paragraph
here -- in this paragraph, one is referred to five
other publications and requested to complete 11 other
forms, such as the 943, 1099, 1099 Miscellaneous, W-2,
W-3, 940, 940-EZ, just to name a few.<p>

		That's just one paragraph from just one of the
cumbersome publications requesting information that is
almost all redundant in the previous year's monthly
reports.    <p>

		I keep wondering how many forms they had before
the Paperwork Reduction Act.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Young folks are often scared off completely
when they see the record-keeping requirements involved
in farming.  And often seasoned farmers are simply
hiring additional help in order to save the recurring
problems connected with payroll.  They are refusing to
grow because of that extra burden.    <p>

		Others are a little more creative.  Some hire
workers but call them contract labor, leaving the
details of reporting up to the workers' discretion.  Or
there are those who simply pay with cash or goods, such
as grain and livestock, and forget the deductions and
reporting altogether.<p>

		Once again, Gary and I applied your efforts to
make our tax system flatter, fairer, and simpler and, I
might add, hopefully filled with some common sense.<p>

		Not only will it help to ease the burden on the
small businessperson, but in so doing, will stimulate
economic growth.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Here, here.<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.  Thank you.<p>

		(Applause)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Sitting ovation.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		Thank you, both Jackie and Gary.<p>

		Keith Olsen -- Mr. Olsen.<p>

<a name="Olsen"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY KEITH OLSEN<br>
GRANT, NEBRASKA</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>


		<b>MR. OLSEN:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		I am happy to have the opportunity to come
before you today and give you a farmer's perspective on
concerns that I have about our federal tax system.  <p>

		I have a dry-land farm in southwest Nebraska,
about 350 miles straight west of here.  I raise about
1300 acres of wheat and about 300 acres of corn
annually.<p>

		Also, I prepare tax returns -- have a business
in the wintertime -- and provide tax services for many
farmers, ranchers, and businesses.<p>

		I'm also a member of the Nebraska Farm Bureau
Board of Directors.<p>

		As this Commission presents recommendations, I
hope they take into concern this uniqueness that
farmers and ranchers have that may not be as important
to other types of taxpayers.<p>

		And I want to just take a couple of minutes to
talk about some of the concerns I have and try not to
duplicate some of the concerns that have already been
presented.<p>

		Farm income is very volatile.  It can go up and
down, and depending mainly upon the weather.  The only
thing consistent about weather in our part of the
state, and for most farmers in the United States, is
that weather is inconsistent.<p>

		A couple of tiny rains in June or a severe
hailstorm in July on my 1300 acres of wheat can put my
income in high tax bracket or at zero.<p>

		And to illustrate that, as we were harvesting
last -- about two weeks ago, a cloud came up and the
combines were in the field.  And about 15 minutes later
some combines didn't need to go back to the field,
because the wheat crop was destroyed by hail.  A
beautiful wheat crop <p>

-- we'd be making $200, $300 per acre gross --was
reduced to zero.  And that had a tremendous effect on
tax planning.<p>

		In 1992, in our area, most of our wheat was
destroyed by a late freeze.  Here again, how do you
plan taxwise when you have such variable income?<p>

		Another area I'd like to touch on is farmers
getting reading to retire.  I've had a friend who
retired this -- at the end of '94.  He planted his last
wheat crop in '94, which he harvested here in '95.  <p>

		He had an equipment sale and sold his
machinery.  He had no expenses in '95; he just had his
income.  So, he's going to be in a big tax bracket.  <p>

		And he found out, when he sold his equipment,
that he had a partner in his farm business.  <p>

		He bought his equipment with his own money.  He
maintained that equipment.  He made the payments on it
if he bought it on time.  He paid personal property tax
on part of it, which we have in Nebraska.  He paid the
sales tax on part of it.  He paid the insurance on it.  <p>

		But when he sold it last spring, he had a
partner, and that partner took one-third of his
machinery, just like a thief in the night coming out
and taking part of the equipment away.<p>

		And this is money that my friend was going to
use to retire on.  And one-third of it, approximately,
went to the government, both federal and state.<p>

		We did have -- prior years, we did have income
tax averaging.  That would have helped my friend,
because he would have got some of that income into a
lower tax bracket.  But we no longer have that.<p>

		Another real problem that has been touched on a
little bit -- we cannot emphasize it enough -- is the
capital gains tax due when a farmer wants to sell his
land.  <p>

		And here again, a lot of farmers have a small
tax base, bought the land years and years ago.  And we,
since then, have had much inflation in the price of
land.  And the government has just, you know, taken an
awful lot of income off of that land as tax.  <p>

		And that's going to affect me.  I'm not quite
ready to retire, but I'm getting to the age where I
need to start thinking about retirement and making my
plans.  <p>

		I had three boys.  Is one of my boys going to
come back to farm?  If he does, how do I transfer the
farm to him?<p>

		And a big concern is the tax issue.  You know,
it isn't a question of is the farm economical, can we
make a living off the farm.  It's a question of how can
you transfer that farm and not pay the government.  And
this is a real, real concern that farmers have to
address.<p>

		And farmers are not just selling assets, mainly
the land and the equipment, because of the taxes.  Some
of them are hanging in farming longer than they want
to.  They're not taking that income -- or that money
they've got invested in land.  <p>

		And to many farmers that's their retirement
plan.  They don't have a 401(k) or a Keogh Plan or
whatnot.  They put their money back into the land and
equipment, and that's what they wanted to retire on. 
And now the government takes so much of it.<p>

		Finally, I'd like to mention one other area of
concern.  As I prepare tax returns -- and a lot of my
farmers are in the $30- to $50,000 income range on a
normal year.  Abnormal years, they're below zero to
maybe $75- or $80,000. <p>

		But for many farmers, my average client in that
$30- to $50,000 range, they will pay more in Social
Security tax than they do in income tax.  And when they
get their tax bill, they don't separate the two.  They
say, "What's my tax bill?"<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		<b>MR. OLSEN:</b>  And then you point out, "Well, this
much is Social Security.  This little bit over here is
the income tax."  <p>

		And, you know, it's a fantastic amount that
goes off -- at a doable farm that has to go to the
government.  And a lot of it is Social Security tax,
the self-employment tax.  		 <p>

		I thank you for giving me an opportunity to
offer some thoughts and viewpoints.  <p>

		And a copy of my testimony was presented to the
Commission.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Great.  Great.  Thanks, Keith.<p>

		Robert Soloth.  Thanks for being here.<p>

		(Pause)<p>

		Can you move?<p>

		That's pretty cumbersome.  We apologize to our
panel.  We should have another microphone.<p>

		(Pause)<p>

		Thank you for being here, sir.<p>

<a name="Soloth"></a><center>PRESENTATION BY ROBERT SOLOTH<br>
McCLELLAND, IOWA</center>
<p>
<center>
<Font size="-1"><a href="#contents">Contents</a></Font>
</center><p>

		<b>MR. SOLOTH:</b>  I appreciate the opportunity to be
able to pass some of my thoughts on to somebody who
maybe will be able to get something done with them.<p>

		My name is Robert Soloth.  My wife, Rosalie,
and my family live near McClelland, Iowa, which is less
than 20 miles east of where we are right now.<p>

		We have four children.  Greg is a December 1944
graduate of Iowa State University and farming with us. 
Dawn is a senior at Simpson College in Indianola,
majoring in elementary education.  Lee Ann is a senior
at Trainor High, and Sarah an eighth grader.  <p>

		We farm 1750 acres in Pottawatomie County, with
1600 acres split between corn and beans and the balance
in set-aside hay and pasture.  We also have a small cow
herd.<p>

		When I was asked to speak before this
Commission, it was suggested I make my comments
primarily on capital gains.  I feel that capital gains
is one of the most unfair taxes we have.  And in my
opinion, in many instances it is a tax on a loss,
rather than a gain.<p>

		In 1966, after I returned from the Army, I
bought a new 1967 Chevy Impala.  It cost me $2500.  The
next summer, a realtor came to me wanting to sell an
80-acre farm in the next section to settle an estate.  <p>

		The price was $450 per acre.  That farm today
would bring about $1400 an acre.  To the IRS, this
would be a $950-per-acre gain, to be taxed at probably
31 percent, or $295 per acre.		<p>

		We just bought a new car last month.  It has a
fancier radio and lots of bells and whistles, but
probably weighs a third less than the '67 Chevy Impala. 
It cost $19,000.  It would have taken 5.5 acres of that
farm in <p>

1967 --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  That's a perfect way of
explaining that.<p>

		<b>MR. SOLOTH:</b>  -- to buy the new car.<p>

		It would take 13.6 acres to buy our new car
today, a 60 percent reduction in buying power.<p>

		But it would also take another <p>

3.6 acres to pay the capital gains tax on the land
sale, making a total loss of buying power of 68
percent.<p>

		In 1968, I bought a new 85 horsepower tractor
for $8500, equal to 18 acres of land.  Today, a
similarly equipped tractor would cost $45,000, or 32
acres of the same land.  This would be a 42 percent
loss in purchasing power.  And after taxing the alleged
gain or inflation, it would take 40 acres, or a 54
percent reduction in actual value.<p>

		To give you one more example, in 1968, my
sister was attending Iowa State University.  Tuition,
room, and board had the phenomenal sum of $800 per
year, or 1.7 acres of that same farm.  <p>

		Last year, when our son graduated from Iowa
State University, the annual cost was $6,000, or 4.3
acres of land, a 61 percent reduction in buying power. 
Or with the capital gains imposed, it would now take
5.4 acres, or a 69 percent reduction in what that acre
would purchase.<p>

		There are situations where it would be best to
sell a farm, but capital gains prevents that from being
economically feasible. <p>

		In 1966, my uncle retired and I rented his
farm.  Things went well until about eight years ago,
when his wife had to be placed in a nursing home.  They
had saved some money and, along with the income of the
farm, were able to pay their bills.<p>

		Two years later, however, my uncle also had to
go to the nursing home.  They were both there together
for about two and a half years, at a cost of nearly
$42,000 per year.<p>

		After my aunt passed away, their money was
gone, along with the operating capital for the farm. 
The farm income, along with his Social Security, will
not cover the nursing home costs for my uncle.  So, the
farm has been mortgaged to make ends meet.  <p>

		As there are no heirs interested in operating
the farm, it would be best of the farm were sold, since
there is no money for repairs or soil conservation
work.  <p>

		However, because my uncle acquired the farm in
the 1930s, his basis in the farm was only $110 per
acre.  The capital gains would take nearly one-third of
the sale price.  In this situation, indexing of capital
gains would certainly not be a tax break for the rich,
as some in the media and Congress would have us
believe.  <p>

		Indexing of capital gains for inflation would
be beneficial for the farm economy, because it would
make more farmland available to young farmers.  It
would put cash into the marketplace or into lending
institutions where it could be loaned for expansion and
capital improvements.  <p>

		There would be more willingness to invest in
agriculture if people knew their investment would not
be punished with a regressive capital gains tax.   <p>

		Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.  <p>

		Let me say, on behalf of the Commission, we've
had testimony for several weeks, and all of it has been
good.  All of it has been essential to the work of this
Commission.<p>

		And I would not be disrespectful to the
wonderful contribution that Keith Olsen and Jackie and
Gary and Bob have made.<p>

		But, Robert, may I say, as the son of a small
businessman -- my daddy was a truck driver and turned
it into a trucking company -- but whether it's trucks
or farming or widget-making or producing bread or wine
or a service, no one has yet testified to this
Commission in such an eloquent fashion on the basic
ingredient of a free market or free enterprise economy,
that you must judge the value of an enterprise not by
some abstraction.  		<p>

		You have brought it down from the abstract to
the empirical, the objective, the historical, the
personal, the family, the real.  		And on behalf of
all of us, and myself in particular, I really want to
thank all of you -- but you particularly -- talking
about acreage and what it would take today to send a
child to college, buy a car, do the things that we, as
Americans, call the American Dream.  <p>

		But it is not American; it is universal.  It is
the universal dream of people everywhere, from South
Africa to the South Bronx, and from East Europe to East
L.A.<p>

		So, that was very, very powerful.  And we're
going to circulate all of your testimony.<p>

		But, Robert, again, it was again, that was a
tremendous contribution to our work.  I really want to
thank you.<p>

		Excuse me for making such a lengthy editorial
comment, but you moved us all.  All of you have, but
that was great.<p>

		The president of the American Farm Bureau,
Commissioner Dean Kleckner.<p>

		COMMISSIONER KLECKNER:  Okay.  Thank you, Jack.<p>

		I would echo what Jack Kemp just said.  And all
of you gave outstanding testimony.  I want to read it
all.<p>

		I can just say amen, or ditto, or whatever, to
all of what you said.  It's what we deal with
constantly in agriculture -- and small business, too,
Herman.  And all of you, it's the same issue.<p>

		Jackie, you particularly -- you talked about
Social Security and Medicare, that tax.  And someone
said that, for farmers, it's often more than the income
tax.  <p>

		I mean -- I guess, Keith, it was you, wasn't
it, as you prepare tax returns? <p>

		How is it affecting all of you?  <p>

		And, you know, Social Security is kind of off
limits politically now.  It's such a touchy issue with
the elderly.  <p>

		And I'm approaching it a lot faster than I
really want to admit, thinking that my mother is 86
years old now, living in Osage, Iowa, on Social
Security and some minor other investments that she
made.  She was a nurse.  <p>

		And our senior citizens worry about Social
Security.  <p>

		And with the media constantly drumming into our
politicians, it almost is off limits to even talk
about.  But heck, I don't care.  I'm going to talk
about it.  I'm going to ask about it.<p>

		What's your view on that?  Is it untouchable? 
Where are we going with it?  What do you think we ought
to do?<p>

		Bob, you're --  <p>

		<b>MR. BETTGER:</b>  Well, one thing that I would like
to talk about on Social Security -- and in 1991, we
were more or less forced to incorporate out business to
avoid some of these taxes.  And I'm sure these other
gentlemen have, too.<p>

		One thing that happens to a farmer as an
individual, when he buys land and he works all of his
life to pay for it, and unless he does something to
incorporate his business otherwise, that land is paid
for, and even though it's an investment -- and the
return from that investment, when he sells grain, it
goes on his 1040-F.  And he pays Social Security on the
return from the investment in that farm, because it's
all included in his 1040-F.<p>

		And it has forced anybody with any acreage or
who owns any land to incorporate or to some way get
around that.  <p>

		But as far as Social Security, I'm <p>

50 years old, and if I could opt out of it now, I sure
would.  <p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  I would like to speak to that,
because whenever I write out a payroll check, about
one-third of the -- well, okay, to give an example, if
a man earns $1,000 approximately, he receives about
$800, but I send to the government the extra $200.  <p>

		So, to me, that man costs me $1200, but he's
only making $800 -- taking home $800, I mean.  I don't
think that sounds fair to either one of us.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  And the biggest comment that I
hear from virtually everyone is "We're sending this in,
but it won't be there when we get there anyway."<p>

		That is just a universal comment, I believe.<p>

		And like Mr. Soloth, I believe we'd all just be
glad to get rid of it.  Like many of our other
government programs, I think it probably started out as
a very good idea, to help people with catastrophic
problems that hadn't, for some reason, been able to
save for their retirement.<p>

		One thing, it has just simply gone awry.  We're
giving people -- not only are they getting a living,
but cost-of-living increases?  		Pardon me, but as
a farmer, I don't get a cost-of-living increase.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		I could probably -- <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  No, that's --<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  -- take the entire forum to talk
about Social Security taxes, so I'll just pass.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well, no.  You made a powerful
case for the explanation of the wedge <p>

-- that is, the gap between what a worker gets to take
home in his or her paycheck and what the employer must
pay to get his or her work done --i.e., labor.  <p>

		And the wider the wedge, the more frustration,
the employer vis-a-vis the worker.  And that's what
this whole issue is about.  Reducing the wage lowers
the cost of labor and brings more employment, brings a
broader tax base.  <p>

		So, that -- hearing it from you, I think --
everybody says, "Oh, economics is so difficult."  <p>

		Nonsense.  It is common sense.  <p>

		I think Keith Olsen said, "I hope you approach
this with common sense."  That is just a commonsense
approach to taxation.<p>

		Loretta.  And then Herman Cain.<p>

		COMMISSIONER ADAMS:  You mentioned, Jackie,
there were six deductions on your payroll check.  If
