the others, you're the ones who have to see it every
day in making out these six entries.  How do you feel
about that whole issue vis-a-vis what we're going?   <p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, in your earlier panel, they
were talking about how to communicate to the general
public about the change in the tax law.  <p>

		And I think if they would totally eliminate tax
withholding and the IRS can open an office in the post
office -- but if everybody had to go write a check
every week or every month for their taxes, there would
be a whole lot more awareness in this country of how
much it takes.  And it would also take a big load off
small business.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, I'd also like to point out
that one of the problems that we have with our
government is the amount of spending that we have.  And
part of that is because of the huge bureaucracy that we
have created.<p>

		I think government could take a lesson from
agriculture.  If they could have improved their
productivity at the rate farmers have improved their
productivity, three out of four of them wouldn't have a
job.<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  I'd like to speak to the concern
about getting the message across -- and I bet I'll get
a nod of every head up there when I say that the media
does not portray what is happening and what needs to be
done accurately.  It just doesn't come to us with a
slant, but it really should.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Well, let me <p>

encourage --<p>

		<b>MRS. MULLER:</b>  I think that's a big problem that
you have.  I don't see how you can sell this if you
have to go through the media to do it.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  That's a great point.<p>

		And I'll tell you, when we listen to panels and
listen to the eloquence of -- the crispness of your
testimony, it's penetrating.  As Herman said, it
excites us and encourages us.<p>

		Let me please urge and recommend that you write
letters to the editors, to cut through some reporting
that's done or not done, and encourage you to be
willing to come testify, to be willing to speak up and
speak out more, because, quite frankly, as a
Commission, we can just say and do so much and it will
be pictured and framed a certain way.  <p>

		But what you're doing every day, from your
farm, ranch, and business, to communicate is extremely
important.<p>

		I just want to encourage you, for your
testimony, not only to us today, but don't lose your
voice.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Great.<p>

		John - Commissioner Wieland.  Question?<p>

		COMMISSIONER WIELAND:  Mr. Bettger said that he
had created several corporations to, you know, deal
with the issues that are out there.  And I wonder if
the rest of you -- is that what you have done, and is
that what other farmers have done generally?<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  We have not incorporated our
farm, because whenever we start getting into these
types of organizational changes, you've got to take
into considerations what it's going to do with your tax
bases of your land, how are you going to be able to
take your land back out.  		We visited with a
bunch of lawyers.  You can visit with a bunch of
accountants.  And it's very difficult to figure out
what needs to be done.  And after you're looking at
both issues, I'm not sure which way is the right way. 
And I get tired of paying the accountants and attorneys
trying to advise me.<p>

		<b>MR. BETTGER:</b>  As I mentioned, we did
incorporate our business in 1991, and I felt we were
forced into it.  We were looking at having two kids in
college for three years, and that amounts to more than
I, at one time, would have ever thought I could make.<p>

		When we were looking at trying to raise our
income, we were already at the point -- between
federal, Social Security, and state income taxes, we
were already paying at a rate of about 56 percent.  So,
any new dollar that we took in, we were only going to
be able to keep 44 percent.  <p>

		By incorporating and keeping land out of the
corporation, the corporation rents the land back.  And
we've eliminated the Social Security tax on the
investment that I mentioned earlier, and we are able to
deduct our health care.  <p>

		And there are a few things that it helps, but
it also creates double bookkeeping, it creates legal
fees, and there are also a lot of drawbacks.  <p>

		But like I said, I felt that we were forced
into it, not because we really wanted to do it.  <p>

		PARTICIPANT:  All right.  I incorporated in
1979.  The main reason was for tax management and debt
management. <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Ted.<p>

		COMMISSIONER FORSTMANN:  I'm kind of with
Herman.  I think that people like yourselves are what
America is really all about.<p>

		I just would like to say that I've got
everybody's written testimony here, except Gary and
Jackie Muller.  <p>

		And if you could get it written up --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		COMMISSIONER FORSTMANN:  -- it would be great
for me, because I think there are places we can put
this and incorporate it.  <p>

		And I was particularly taken by something Gary
said.<p>

		About your great-grandfather (sic), <p>

I guess.  He left Germany for a reason.  And I don't
believe that what we're talking about here is really
economics.  There is nothing -- there is no economics
in favor of the kind of looney things that you people
are forced to do.  There's no such thing as it.  <p>

		We're really talking about civics.  We're
talking about essentially two ways of looking at how
life should be lived.  One is where the state is kind
of preeminent.  And the other is where the person is
kind of preeminent.<p>

		And to make a long story short, your
grandfather (sic) left Germany because at that time the
state was very preeminent.  There <p>

was a -- <p>

		And if we don't get things right here, that's
really what you're talking about.  You're all forced to
do this crazy stuff, thinking about incorporating, not
incorporating -- this, that and the other -- for what
reason?  <p>

		Nobody on this side of the fence and nobody on
this side of the fence has been able to come up with
any reason at all except that the state interferes in
your lives.<p>

		And so we really ought to try.  I'm with
Herman.  We all are donating time and a lot.  And I'm
glad we are, because without people like you, there
isn't going to be anything worth doing here.<p>

		Thank you.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  That is a very important point
to anybody who is listening.<p>

		All of these men and women are busy.  They're
