		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Our next is going to
address this whole issue.  <p>

		We've got Patrick Hendershott from <p>

Ohio State University, and Robert Genetski, <p>

Bob Genetski; George Zodrow; and John Anderson <p>

-- all of whom are economists and experts on tax
policy.<p>

		And I know they'll remind us of something that
came from a simple, yet profound, farming career and
life, which is that you either have a Tax Code that
redistributes wealth, or you have a Tax Code that
allows wealth to be created.<p>

		And Forstmann asked the question rhetorically
about how this happened.  It grew.  		But it grew
because, in my opinion, having been in the Congress for
so long, 18 years from Buffalo, New York, there are two
kinds of politics.  <p>

		There is the politics of envy and the politics
of egalitarian -- not egalitarian reward, but
egalitarian opportunity.  I think that's what democracy
really is.<p>

		And envy and fear that someone is going to get
rich is what has added to the complexity of the Tax
Code in my opinion.<p>

 		There would be no estate tax.  There is no
earthly reason to tax someone's income, tax it again in
a dividend, tax it again on a capital gain or risk, tax
it again at death.<p>

		I hope their panel can come up with a simple,
single source of tax.  Not judging the outcome, but all
of us are passionate in our belief.<p>

		I would make one other point about the press. 
Reagan proved, I think, once and for all that good
economics is good politics, without suggesting that
everything was perfect.  <p>

		I think it was clear that he got attacked --
left and probably right -- for trying to reduce tax
rates and regulations and to strengthen the currency
back in the early '80s.  <p>

		And it overcame the hostility of the press.  It
drove the press crazy that Ronald Reagan could win the
presidency of the United States on a program of getting
America moving again.  <p>

		And incidentally, that's what John F. Kennedy
did in the early '60s, and that's how a lot of people
really approach this issue.  <p>

		How can we make America grow by allowing
farmers to farm, businessmen and women to produce
widgets, and people to save?<p>

		I am -- well, I think all of us very much
