<HEAD>

<TITLE>RANGE OF CITIZENS
TO TESTIFY ABOUT NEED FOR TAX REFORM IN INNER CITIES -- TRC
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center>
<i>September 19, 1995</i>
<P>
<h3>FROM WALL STREET TO 135th STREET, RANGE OF CITIZENS
TO TESTIFY ABOUT NEED FOR TAX REFORM IN INNER CITIES</h3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>
<CENTER>
<B>Chairman Jack Kemp and Tax Reform Commission members
to hear from inner city entrepreneurs and financial experts</B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<B>WASHINGTON, D.C. -</B> Access
to capital, credit and job opportunities in our nation's inner
cities will be the focus of a public hearing in Harlem on Wednesday
that will feature minority entrepreneurs, academics, and financial
experts, according to Jack Kemp, chairman of the National Commission
Economic Growth and Tax Reform.
<P>
&quot;Citizens from several important  sectors of
New York City will emphasize the importance of tax reform to economic
growth, jobs and ownership in our nation's urban areas,&quot;
said Kemp, former secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
<P>
Among those on the diverse witness list for the Harlem
hearing are U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel (D-NY);  Lee Bowes, President
of America Works;  Robert Wallace, President of the BiTH Group,
and author of <I>Black Wealth through Black Leadership</I>;  Van
Woods, President and Founder, Sylvia's Soul Foods;  Morton Davis,
Chairman of the Board, D.H. Blair Investment Banking Corp.; and
Bob McKnew, Chairman of the Public Securities Association.
<P>
The hearing is scheduled for Wednesday, September
20, beginning at 9:00 a.m. at Aaron Davis Hall (at City College
of New York), 135th &amp; Convent Street, Theatre B, in New York
City.  It is free and open to the public. 
<P>
By the end of September, the Tax Reform Commission
will have held 12 public meetings in the three months since it
was formed.  The commission is determined to &quot;listen first.&quot;
It is holding this series of public hearings to learn from the
American people their frustrations, fears, and concerns with the
federal income tax system.  Almost 100 witnesses, from a cross-section
of American life, have already testified before the Tax Reform
Commission, during hearings in Washington, D.C.; Boston, Massachusetts;
Omaha, Nebraska; Charlotte, North Carolina; Palo Alto, California
(Silicon Valley); and, South-central Los Angeles.
<P>
&quot;We are searching for real ideas, from real
people, for real reform&quot;, said Kemp.  &quot;We have already
found overwhelming dismay and frustration with the current system.
 The federal tax code, with its high marginal rates, and mindboggling
rules and regulations, is choking economic growth in all sectors
of American life.  It is burdensome to minority men and women
who want the seed corn and venture capital necessary to achieve
their part of the American dream.&quot;
<P>
Kemp said that as currently written, the tax code:
<UL>
<LI>Punishes the most dynamic forces for growth in
our economy -- the small business owners and entrepreneurs who
turn bold ideas into new businesses, new jobs, and new products.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Discourages working Americans who are trying
to save for the future and to build a better life for themselves
and their families.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Is endlessly complex and confusing, costing literally
billions of dollars in lost time and effort.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Senate Leader Bob Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich
have charged the 14-member commission with making recommendations
for a tax code that is &quot;flatter, fairer, and simpler&quot;
-- a system that will encourage economic growth and greater opportunity
for all Americans.  
<P>
The commission hopes to present recommendations that
will make the tax code more family friendly and create incentives
for saving and investment. Its aim is to help guide the tax reform
debate toward changes that will reinvigorate entrepreneurship,
risk taking, saving, investment, and work effort. It hopes to
contribute to changes that will make America more competitive
and expand the nation's worldwide leadership in the 21st century
economy. 
<P>
Among the issues it is studying:  What are the implications
to the economy of a steeply progressive tax system? What is the
impact on economic growth of higher marginal tax rates? What do
people mean whey they say they want a &quot;fairer&quot; tax system?
 What do we mean by &quot;flatter&quot; tax rates?  &quot;There
are a lot of different views, and we want to know what the American
people think and what are the ramifications,&quot; Kemp said.
<P>
&quot;We are setting the stage for American tax policy
for the new century.  We hope that this series of hearings will
help all of us to learn more about the changes that are needed
to make better informed decisions about the hard choices that
lie ahead,&quot; Kemp said. &quot;If we can find the core, central
principles of a new vision for tax reform that includes everyone's
views, we can get this done. The American people -- and our children
and grandchildren-- will be the winners.&quot;
<P>
Other Tax Reform Commission hearings will be held
this month at Howard University in Washington, D.C., on Tuesday,
September 26; and in Cleveland, Ohio, September 27.  The commission
expects to issue its recommendations and report by the end of
the year.
</blockquote>
