<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Charlotte, NC Meeting Announced -- TRC
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>


<CENTER>
<i>August 1, 1995</i><P>
<h3>TAX REFORM FIELD HEARING TO BE HELD IN CHARLOTTE,
SPONSORED BY THE NATIONAL COMMISSION 
ON ECONOMIC GROWTH AND TAX REFORM</h3>
</CENTER>

<P>
<P>
<blockquote><B>WASHINGTON, D.C. -</B> &quot;Designing a flatter, fairer and
simpler tax system that will encourage economic growth and greater
opportunity for all our people,&quot; is how Jack Kemp described
his goal as Chairman of the recently formed National Commission
on Economic Growth and Tax Reform, commonly referred to as the
Tax Reform Commission (TRC).  
<P>
Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-GA) and Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole
(R-KS) have appointed Jack Kemp, co-Director of Empower America,
to chair the 14 member Commission consisting of leaders in both
the public and private sectors.  Kemp states the purpose of the
TRC is &quot;to study how major restructuring of our tax code
can help unleash the entrepreneurial spirit of Americans, grow
the economy without inflation and create greater opportunity for
people to escape poverty.&quot;  
<P>
In its first field hearing on July 19, Commission members gathered
in Boston to begin discussions on tax reform.  Over one hundred
business leaders, government representatives, and citizens attended
the hearing to share their views. On August 2nd the Commission
travelled to Omaha, Nebraska for its second public hearing to
hear from business owners, farmers, and tax analysts.
<P>
The TRC will hold its third field hearing concerning tax reform
in Charlotte, North Carolina on <B>Wednesday, August 16, 1995
beginning at 9:00 a.m.</B> <B>at the Marriott City Center</B>.
 The hearing is free and open to the public.  The central purpose
of the hearing is to examine the impact of the tax system on economic
growth and tax receipts.  The hearing will feature local citizens
and tax experts.  
<P>
&quot;The Commission will gather the views of American citizens
from all walks of life and collect and analyze the best available
analysis and evidence from the experts who study tax policy. 
The Commission is expected to issue its recommendation and its
report in December.  The Commission's report will provide recommendations
that will contribute to reinvigorating entrepreneurship, risk-taking,
savings, investment, and work efforts.  Our goal is to offer ideas
for a major overhaul of the tax system to make America more competitive,
expand the nation's worldwide leadership in the 21st century global
economy, and help eliminate, where they exist, any conditions
of despair and poverty,&quot; Kemp said.  
<P>
<a href="/taxcom/commlst.html">Commission members</a> include Loretta H. Adams, President, Market
Development, Inc.; J. Kenneth Blackwell, Ohio State Treasurer;
Herman Cain, Chairman and CEO, Godfather's Pizza, Inc.; Carroll
Campbell, former Governor of South Carolina; Pete du Pont, former
Governor of Delaware; Jack Faris, President, National Federation
of Independent Business; Edwin J. Feulner, Jr., President, The
Heritage Foundation; Matt Fong, California State Treasurer; Theodore
J. Forstmann, Partner, Forstmann Little &amp; Co.; Dean R. Kleckner,
President, American Farm Bureau Federation; Shirley Peterson,
President, Hood College; John Snow, Chairman, President and CEO,
CSX Corporation; and John Wieland, President, John Wieland Homes,
Inc.
</blockquote>
