<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Tax Reform Commission Continues Public Hearings -- TRC</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<center><i>
July 26, 1995</i>
<P>
<h3>Tax Reform Commission Continues Public Hearings</h3>
</CENTER>

<P>
<blocquote>
The National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform continues
to hold weekly hearings to explore the problems with the current
tax code and principles for reform.  The commission's next public
hearing is being held Wednesday, July 26, in the Lehrman Auditorium
at The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Ave., N.E.  It will
begin at 9:30 a.m. and is open to the public.
<P>
 &quot;We know far too much about what doesn't work, and we know
that those who are hurt most by bad public policies, especially
tax policy, are those at the bottom of the economic ladder,&quot;
said Commission Chairman Jack Kemp. 
<P>
&quot;While there is overwhelming anger and frustration with the
current system, we need to explore more about citizens' experiences
with problems and solutions before we can go forward with radical
change,&quot; he said.
<P>
For example, what are the implications to the economy of a steeply
progressive tax system? What is the impact on economic growth
of higher marginal tax rates? What do people mean whey they say
they want a &quot;fairer&quot; tax system?  What do we mean by
&quot;flatter&quot; tax rates?  &quot;There are many different
views, and we want to know what the American people think and
what are the ramifications of various options for change,&quot;
Kemp said.
<P>
The commission will develop recommendations designed to make the
tax code more family friendly and create incentives for saving
and investment. Members will focus on proposals to reinvigorate
entrepreneurship, risk taking, saving, investment, and work effort.
Their charge is to develop recommendations for changes that will
make America more competitive and expand the nation's worldwide
leadership in the 21st century economy. 
<P>
Senator Dole and Speaker Gingrich, who created the Tax Reform
Commission,  asked commissioners to study ways in which the current
tax code -- with its &quot;high marginal tax rates and thousands
of pages of rules, regulations, and red tape -- poses a barrier
to economic growth.&quot; As they said:
<UL>
<LI>It punishes the most dynamic forces for growth in our economy
-- the small business owners and entrepreneurs who turn bold ideas
into new businesses, new jobs, and new products.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>It discourages working Americans who are trying to save for
the future and to build a better life for themselves and their
families.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>It is endlessly complex and confusing, costing literally billions
of dollars in lost time and effort.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
&quot;One of the most important aspects of our work is to talk
with Americans from all walks of life -- small business people,
farmers, factory workers, inventors, and entrepreneurs -- who
make America work. We will be holding hearings across the country
over the next several months to talk with taxpayers and to hear
from experts who study tax policy,&quot; said Commission Vice
Chairman Ed Feulner, President of the Heritage Foundation.
<P>
&quot;I am proud to serve with the distinguished men and women
on this commission who have offered to give of their time and
energy and talents so that all Americans can have a better chance
at the American dream,&quot; Kemp said.  &quot;Individually and
collectively, my colleagues on the commission have a huge font
of knowledge, experience, and courage that can help guide our
work.
<P>
&quot;We are setting the stage for a 21st century tax policy for
America,&quot; said Kemp.  &quot;It is imperative that everyone
work together to advance this monumental task.  What we are undertaking
may feel at times like moving a mountain. Making the tax code
simpler will be a very complicated process.
<P>
&quot;We hope that this series of hearings -- in which both citizens
and experts present views -- will help all of us to learn more
and to make better informed decisions about the hard choices that
lie ahead. If we can find the core, central principles of a new
vision for tax reform that includes everyone's views, we can get
this done. The American people -- and our children and grandchildren--
will be the winners,&quot; Kemp said.
<P>
Other <a href="/taxcom/commlst.html">members</a> of the Tax Reform Commission include: Loretta H.
Adams, President, Market Development, Inc.; J. Kenneth Blackwell,
Ohio State Treasurer; Herman Cain, Chairman and CEO, Godfather's
Pizza, Inc.; Carroll A. Campbell, Jr., former Governor of South
Carolina; Pete du Pont, former Governor of Delaware; Jack Faris,
President and CEO, National Federation of Independent Business;
Matt Fong, California State Treasurer; Ted Forstmann, Partner,
Forstmann Little &amp; Co.; Dean R. Kleckner, President, American
Farm Bureau Federation; Shirley D. Peterson, former IRS Commissioner;
John Snow, Chairman, President and CEO, CSX Corporation; and John
Wieland, President, John Wieland Homes, Inc.
</blockquote>
<P>

<P><P><font size="-1"><a href="/taxcom/prindex.html">PR Index</a> | <a href="/taxcom/">TRC Home</a> | <a href="/taxcom/reptoc.html">The Report</a></font></center><P></body>

