<html>
<head>
<title>The Washington Times Article</title>
</head>
<body>
<b>The Washington Times</b><br>
June 15, 1995
<p>
<center><h2>Kemp vows fairness with tax reform ideas</h2>
<p>
GOP commission takes up alternatives</center>
<p>
(AP) -- Former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp opened the first meeting of a Republican tax reform commission yesterday by promising to give fair consideration to the full range of proposals for overhauling the tax code.
<p>
Mr Kemp is a fan of a flat-rate income tax, but he said the 14 member commission, appointed by Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas and House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia, would evaluate a wide variety of ideas.
<p>
In addition to a flat tax proposed by House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, he mentioned proposals for a consumption tax from Rep. Bill Archer of Texas chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee; a national sales tax from Sen. Richard G. Lugar of Indiana; and plans offered by House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, Missouri Democrat and Sen. Bill Bradley, New Jersey Democrat.
<p>
"It looks partisan. We're all men and women of the center-right of the spectrum," Mr. Kemp said of the
commission of business executives and former government officials. "I've taken stands, probably every one of us . . . has taken a stand on one sort of tax code or another We're going to approach it as open-minded as we humanly possibly, politically can."
<p>
Mr. Dole and Mr Gingrich asked Mr. Kemp to head the National Commission on Economic Growth and
Tax Reform two months ago; it is expected to issue its findings late this year in time for the presidential
primary elections.
<p>
"In no small way, this is the first day of the 21st century, at least in terms of taxes," Mr. Kemp said "This
.. . will be at the center of attention in '96 for the American people."
<p>
Republicans, who seized control of Congress last year for the first time in four decades, are hoping to make tax reform as powerful an issue in 1996 as tax reduction was in 1994.
<p>
"If Congress just stops at reducing taxes, then it will not have finished its job," Mr. Dole said at a news
conference at the start of the commission meeting "Americans . . . gave us control of Congress for the first time because they were fed up with the status quo. Now if there's one status quo that needs changing it's the federal tax code."
<p>
Mr. Gingrich said he is "really astonished by the intensity of resentment and irritation with the IRS."
<p>
<center>[ <a href="/taxcom/">TRC Home</a> ]</center>
</body>
