<center><h2><a name="close"></a>Up Close</h2></center>
<B>Comedy and Tragedy, 1996<BR>
<I>Actual Course Descriptions</I><BR>
(Emphasis Added)</B>
<P>
<B>BROWN UNIVERSITY:
<P><I>Women's Studies 196b</B></I> <B><U>Christianity, 
Violence, and Victimization</B></U>  This seminar will 
examine historical and contemporary Christian 
theological perspectives on suffering and violence. 
While Christianity may be said to provide a remedy 
for evil, sin and suffering, contemporary critics, 
including feminist ones, argue the opposite: that 
<I>Christianity has helped to create and perpetuate 
a culture of violence, especially against women and 
other dispossessed persons</I>....  Attention will also be 
given to contemporary proposals for reconstructing Christian theology and ethics and transforming 
a culture of violence and abuse.
<P>
<P><B>CORNELL UNIVERSITY:
<P><I>Psychology 277 </I><U>The Social Construction 
of Gender</B></U>  This course addresses the very 
broad question of how an individual's gender and 
sexuality are constructed. Although some attention 
is given to biological perspectives, <I>the course 
emphasizes the social-psychological processes by which the 
culture transforms male and female newborns into 
&quot;masculine&quot; and &quot;feminine&quot; 
adults.</I> In addition to being quite interdisciplinary, the course is also 
oriented to <I>questioning the &quot;naturalness&quot; of not only 
masculinity and femininity, but exclusive heterosexuality 
as well.</I> Among some of the specialized topics 
discussed are psychological androgyny, egalitarian relationships, gender-liberated child rearing, 
the male centeredness of the work world, female 
sexuality, sexual harassment and homophobia. 
<P>
<P><B>AMHERST COLLEGE:
<P><I>Black Studies 53</B></I> <B><U>Black 
English</B></U>  An examination of the language of African-Americans. 
Topics will include the historical development of 
black English; a comparison of black English and 
standard American English features; a review of major theories of research on the language 
abilities of African-Americans; linguistic issues 
underlying the black English language/dialect controversy; 
the role of black English in creative expression; 
and the impact of black English on the social 
economic and education opportunities of African-Americans.
<P>
<P><B>GEORGETOWN UNIVERSITY:
<P><I>English 134</B></I> <B><U>Prison 
Literature</B></U>  The United States has the highest per capita imprisonment 
rate in the world. Over four million people are on 
probation, parole, in jail or prison. In this context 
we will read a selection of literature by and about 
the imprisoned....  This course directly promotes 
service learning through community involvement with youth offender programs, ex-inmate 
organizations, criminal justice internships and 
prison tutoring programs. <I>Students will be asked to 
create an outreach that will join the incarcerated 
community with the community at large in order to help 
halt the &quot;prison mill.&quot; </I>
<P>
<P><B>UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN:
<P><I>Psychology 211</B></I> <B><U>Social 
Justice</B></U>  <I>Learn about racism, homophobia, sexism, rape, incest, domestic 
violence, eating disorders, substance abuse, the AIDS 
crisis, and teen pregnancy. </I>Develop supportive 
and helping relationships with people as they 
encounter special challenges throughout the life-span 
of teens through elderly, or <I>join with local 
agencies working to bring about change in the lives of people 
of color, women, gay men, and lesbians.</I>
<P>
<P><B>CHAPMAN UNIVERSITY:
<P><I>Peace Studies 341</B></I> <B><U>Reversing the Arms 
Race</B></U> Why did the U.S. and U.S.S.R. pursue a 
costly and ecocidal arms race in the wake of World 
War II? What are nuclear weapons and what threat 
do they pose to the planet? As the Cold War wanes, what dangers lie ahead due to the spread of 
weaponry? How might we all benefit from conversion from a military to a peacetime economy? How 
do we ensure national security while doing so? 
This course is a primer for citizenship in the 21st century.
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Bizarre Leftist Themes Dominate College Classrooms</H2>

<B>Frivolous `Multicultural' Courses Demean the Value of a College Degree </B><BR>
An annual survey conducted by Young 
     America's Foundation reveals that, 
     students are being offered heavy doses 
     of Leftist indoctrination in their college courses.  The survey, which examines the 
curricula of the nation's top colleges and 
universities, found that the &quot;victim studies&quot; triad of 
race, gender, and class dominated the course 
offerings on all campuses, showing up in courses 
including &quot;Inequality:  Class, Race, and Gender,&quot; 
at Princeton; &quot;Race, Class, Gender, and Ethnicity 
in the City,&quot; at NYU; &quot;Race, Gender, and 
the Politics of Rock `n' Roll,&quot; at Columbia; and 
even &quot;Issues of Gender in Sport,&quot; at Brown.
<P>Young America's Foundation uncovers the farce of modern college curricula in its 
annual study, <I>Comedy and Tragedy:  College 
Course Descriptions and What They Tell Us About 
Higher Education Today</I>.  Now in its second edition, 
<I>Comedy and Tragedy</I> is an in-depth documentation of the efforts 
of radical Leftists to implement their ideology on 
the nation's top college campuses.
<P>With recent surveys showing over fifty percent of employers seeking 
highly-skilled college graduates, the curricula offered by 
the nation's leading universities is now more 
important than ever before.  With a job market 
stifled by government regulations, employers need 
to choose the next generation of the work-force with much care and attention.      
<P>An examination of what students are learning quickly reveals that 
many of today's colleges are not meeting the needs of the work-force or the 
students, because they do not provide the learning skills integral to life 
after graduation.  Today's curricula neglects our nation's founding 
principles in favor of pushing politically charged courses such as &quot;The History 
of Socialist Thought,&quot; and &quot;Feminist Reading, Lesbian Writing.&quot;  
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="cornel.gif" ALT="Cornell West"  ><BR>
<B>Cornel West</B> of Harvard University is a self-avowed socialist who teaches courses such
as "The Thought of W.E.B. DuBois" in the school's Afro-American Studies Department</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>When traditional fields of learning are covered, they are often 
covered from a Leftist perspective.  Such is the case with religion, as seen in 
Carleton College's &quot;Witches, Saints, and Seers;&quot; Fordham's &quot;Religion 
and Feminism;&quot; and Smith College's &quot;New Age America:  The Role 
of Mysticism in Secular Culture.&quot;  Christianity and other Western religions 
are almost always cast as being &quot;oppressive&quot; to minorities.  Observe Cornell's 
&quot;Gender and Sexuality in Early Christianity;&quot; or 
UPenn's &quot;The Historical Origins of Racism:  Views 
of Blacks in Early Judaism, Christianity, and 
Islam;&quot; and &quot;A Feminist Critique of Christianity.&quot;  
There are no reports of a course dealing with the &quot;Christian Critique of Feminism,&quot; however.  
<P>Even hard sciences, such as physics and biology, must yield to the forces of 
Political Correctness.  Princeton students can learn 
about &quot;Gender and Science,&quot; which offers a 
&quot;feminist critique of scientific knowledge.&quot;  
Dartmouth College explores &quot;the wider implications of 
the contemporary critique of rational, binary, hierarchical, and patriarchal thinking&quot; in a 
course called &quot;Ways of Knowing:  Physics, 
Literature, Feminism.&quot;  Science also seems to be affected 
by the racial politics of multiculturalism, 
warranting an examination of &quot;Afrocentric Health 
Care Systems&quot; at Emory University.  
<P>These frivolous courses have now spread to all types of schools, 
from large State-run universities to small liberal arts colleges.  
Amherst College offers &quot;Taking Marx Seriously,&quot; 
for example.  The University of Georgia hopes to 
educate its students in the &quot;History and Analysis of 
Rock Music.&quot;  &quot;Freud, Fairy Tales, and Feminism&quot; is an 
official course at UCLA, and Fordham University offers a course 
simply entitled:  &quot;Victimology.&quot; 
<table align=left width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="cartoon.gif" ALT="Cartoon" ><BR>
<B>Students <I>and </I>employers</B> are beginning to realize that college 
diplomas aren't worth much when students are taking &quot;victim studies&quot; courses 
such as Notre Dame's &quot;Economics of Gender and Ethnic Discrimination.&quot;<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
Classes that often offend a student's morals, upbringing, or religion are common fare 
in today's colleges, such as &quot;The History of 
Witchcraft and Magic,&quot; at Rutgers University, and 
a course drawing parallels between 
&quot;Christianity, Violence, and Victimization&quot; at Brown.
<P>
<I>Comedy and Tragedy </I>allows those outside 
of the Ivory Tower walls to see inside for themselves.  This study is especially helpful for 
concerned alumni, as they cannot rely upon the sterilized alumni publications of their alma 
mater to expose the proliferation of these bizarre classes.   
<P>
<BR>
