<center><b>Volume 17, Number 2<br>March and April 1996</b>
<h3><a name="contents">Contents</a></h3></center>

<br>
<UL>
<LI><a href="#close">Up Close: </a>Conservatives speakers set to buoy students against leftist barrage.
<LI> Vice-President <a href="#quayle"><B>Dan Quayle </B></a> was received at Northwestern University 
and Southeast Missouri State University by large student audiences eager to hear 
his message.
<LI><a href="#cong">Congressional leaders,</a> such as Speaker of the House 
<B>Newt Gingrich</B>, play an integral part in the Foundation's 
mission to bring a conservative, free market message to America's college students.<br>
<LI>Young America's Foundation activists scored a major victory for student 
rights when Congress passed, and the President signed into law, a bill that bars 
schools from accepting Defense Department money if they discriminate against 
<a href="#rotc">ROTC cadets. </a><br> 
<LI><a href="#will">Armstrong Williams</a> Inspires Large Student Audience<BR>
<LI><a href="#about">About <i>Libertas</i></a><br>
</ul>

<p><p><hr><p><p>

<center><h2><a name="close"></a>Up Close</h2></center>

The radicals of the 1960s have taken over the universities as the 
professors and administrators of the 1990s.  They are eager to offer their campuses 
as soapboxes to Leftists such as <B>Joycelyn 
Elders</B>, <B>Louis Farrakhan</B>, <B>Donna 
Shalala</B>, and <B>Bill</B> and <B>Hillary 
Clinton</B>.  In four short years, lessons that 
parents have spent a lifetime instilling in their children can be undone by this 
liberal monopoly.  
<P>Young America's Foundation has assembled an extensive program to help 
students defend themselves against this Leftist barrage.  Through our four special 
lecture series programs (named after prominent American philanthropists), the 
Foundation is able to sponsor some of the most 
exciting speakers on the lecture circuit several 
times a year on campuses across the country.  
<I>These named lecture programs are our most 
effective way of reaching besieged students on the 
campuses, and would not be possible without the financial support of the Foundation's most 
generous supporters.    </I>
<P><B>Walter Williams</B>, the 1995-1996 <B>Henry 
Salvatori Distinguished Lecturer</B>, is an author, 
columnist, and a guest-host for <I>The Rush Limbaugh 
Radio Show</I>.  He is an authority on economic and 
governmental issues and his lectures highlight the ideals of freedom and liberty that 
motivated our Founding Fathers.  Dr. Williams also serves as the chair of the Economics 
Department at George Mason University.  
<P> <B>Robert Novak</B>, the <B>William Howard 
Flowers, Jr. Lecturer</B>, is one of the most insightful 
political analysts today.  He is co-host of the 
<I>Evans and Novak </I>interview program and executive director 
of CNN's <I>Crossfire</I>.  His column is published four times a week and 
appears in more than 150 newspapers across the country.  Mr. Novak is the author of 
several books, including <B><I>The Reagan Revolution 
</B></I>and <B><I>Nixon in the White House</B></I>.
<P><B>Michael Medved</B>, co-host of <I>Sneak Previews 
</I>and chief film critic for <I>The New York 
Post</I>, is the <B>Grover Hermann Freedom 
Lecturer</B>.  Mr. Medved is an authority on cultural values and 
Holly-wood's role in influencing them.  He regularly appears as a guest 
host on <I>The Rush Limbaugh Radio Show</I>. 
<P><B>Peter Schweizer</B>, the inaugural speaker for the 
<B>William Casey Lecture Series</B>, is the author of 
<B><I>Victory</B></I>.  Mr. Schweizer explains to 
students how the Reagan administration developed a secret strategy that led 
to the collapse of the Soviet Union.  <BR>
<p><p><HR><p><p><center>
<h3><a name="quayle"></a>Quayle Addresses Thousands of Students at Foundation Lectures</h3><p>
<b>Vice-President Draws 1100 at Southeast Missouri State and 900 at Northwestern</b><p>
[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
In a matter of hours, all 900 tickets made                available to students at Northwestern      
          University were taken by young people      
          eager to hear former Vice-President 
<B>Dan Quayle</B>.
<P>&quot;The demand was much greater than we anticipated,&quot; remarked 
<B>Kevin Frost</B>, the Northwestern student who coordinated the 
event with Young America's Foundation.  &quot;This 
was truly a great speech,&quot; he added.  &quot;There 
aren't many events on campus when tickets are all taken within hours and the crowd is as 
enthusiastic as this one was tonight.&quot;
<P>This spring, Mr. Quayle has addressed standing-room-only crowds at 
Northwestern University and Southeast Missouri State 
University, speaking on the values and principles upon which our country is built, and 
the qualities and characteristics our national 
leaders need to possess.
<P>&quot;Character <I>does </I>matter,&quot; the former 
Vice-President assured students.  &quot;The 
American people today simply want to have a 
president who will tell the truth.  It's that simple.&quot;
<P>The Quayle speech was greatly anticipated by students at both campuses.  
Young America's Foundation has found that students are eager to hear conservative and free 
market ideas and will turn out enthusiastically 
when given the opportunity.  Many students are now beginning to protest when their professors 
and administrators exclusively promote Leftist 
ideas on campus.  Prior to Mr. Quayle's Northwestern University speech, many students 
expressed these very sentiments:
<P>Northwestern student <B>Jason Goch </B>was one of many students who was anxious to hear 
an alternative message, saying that he hoped that Mr. Quayle would &quot;provide a bit of balance 
to the overwhelming number of liberal speakers who are brought here.&quot;
<P>Student <B>Danny Rashburn</B>, who serves as the head of Northwestern's student 
Senate, commented that even though he considered 
himself a liberal, he was anxious to hear Mr. Quayle speak. 
 &quot;I'm pretty involved with politics and I 
don't really know much of what he stands for because 
the media has developed an image of him that preceded 
all of his politics,&quot; he admitted.  &quot;I'm 
interested in seeing not only what he stands for but whether or not 
that image is correct.  It will definitely be one of 
the most memorable events for me.&quot;
<P>In his speech before 1100 students at Southeast Missouri State, Mr. Quayle 
stressed the need for a less burdensome tax system, 
and the need for our country to dismantle the welfare system.
<P>
&quot;I'm not talking about just reforming [the welfare system],&quot; Mr. Quayle declared.  
&quot;Some people say that all we need is to tinker with 
it on the edges, just a little reform.  Well, 
forget it.  It doesn't work.  It doesn't help the 
homeless, doesn't help the poor, and doesn't help 
the disadvantaged.  The system is a destroyer of families.  It penalizes marriages, it 
discourages work and it subsidizes illegitimacy.  What 
kind of system is that?  We have unfortunately created a culture of dependency, where we need a culture of opportunity.&quot; 
<P>Vice-President Quayle is just one of the highlights of the Foundation's spring 
lecture program which features such prominent 
figures as Supreme Court Justice <B>Clarence 
Thomas</B> at Southeast Missouri State on April 30, 
<B>William F. Buckley</B> at Weber State University on 
April 18, <B>Jack Kemp</B> at Loyola 
University-Chicago on April 24, <B>Edwin Meese</B> at the University 
of Dayton School of Law on May 18, <B>Dinesh 
D'Souza</B> at Iowa State University on April 17 and also at Brown University on April 23. 

<p><p><HR><p><p><center>
<h3><a name="cong"></a>Congressional Leaders Play an Integral Part in Foundation Programs</h3><p>
<BR>
<B>Foundation Vice-President, Ron Pearson, Provides Valuable Link to Capitol Hill</B><p>
[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
Since its inception 27 years ago, 
     Young America's Foundation has 
     sought to bring a conservative, free 
     market message to America's college students.  An essential part of this 
outreach mission is allowing students to hear, 
firsthand, the thoughts and principles espoused by 
our country's greatest leaders and thinkers.  Over the years, Young America's Foundation 
has been fortunate to develop close working relationships with many of America's most 
distinguished congressional leaders, and has been able to bring their valuable messages to 
students, who represent the next generation of national leaders.
<P>Each summer, at the Foundation's National Conservative Student Conference, 
attending students are treated to a Congressional 
Briefing featuring conservative legislators from both 
the House and Senate.  In past years, students 
have been able to meet and hear from figures such as Speaker <B>Newt Gingrich</B>, Senate 
Majority Leader <B>Robert Dole</B>, Senator <B>Phil 
Gramm</B>, House Majority Leader <B>Dick Armey</B>, 
Senate Majority Whip <B>Trent Lott</B>, 
Conservative Democratic Forum founder 
Representative <B>Charles Stenholm</B>, and Senator 
<B>Jesse Helms</B>, to name just a few.  The Foundation's 
Congressional Briefing is often carried on C-SPAN, 
and last summer, a special Foundation luncheon with Speaker Gingrich was covered by 
NBC, ABC, and CBS.  
<P>This briefing is organized each year by the Foundation's vice-president, 
<B>Ron Pearson</B>, who served as chief of staff to 
Representative <B>John Ashbrook </B>and Representative 
<B>Bill Dannemeyer</B> before opening his own 
political management and government relations 
consulting firm on Capitol Hill.  Mr. Pearson notes that he tries 
to find congressmen who might have a wider appeal 
to students than simply just as a &quot;politician.&quot;  
<P>&quot;I try to identify congressmen who would have 
an interesting message for college students.  That's one of the 
first things I look at,&quot; says Mr. Pearson.  &quot;I 
try to look at freshman members and newer members who 
might be of interest, and that's how I first started 
inviting Congressman Gingrich almost seven years ago.  
Although he was known as a `backbencher' back then, he really wasn't.  He was a leader 
in the House as far as having some strong ideas on how to take control of 
the Congress.  He was also very active on issues in Congress.  So I started 
inviting him because I thought he would be of special interest to the students, and 
also because he was a college professor before he became a congressman.&quot;
<P>Many of the most popular speakers at the Foundation's Congressional 
Briefing share an academic background.  In addition to Speaker Gingrich, who 
was once a history professor at West Georgia College, other former professors 
include Senator Gramm, Representative Armey, and Representative 
<B>Phil Crane</B>, who has spoken before Foundation audiences 
for more than 15 years.  Congressman Armey notes that his experiences as 
a college professor give him a great understanding of the unique service that 
Young <BR>

<HR>
<blockquote>
<B>&quot;I have worked closely with Young America's Foundation over the years 
and have found their commitment to promoting balance, academic 
integrity, and free market values on campuses is unsurpassed.  If students are 
serious about effectively challenging the liberal monopoly on campus, they must 
contact Young America's Foundation.&quot;
<P> Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich</B><BR>
</blockquote>
<HR>
America's Foundation conferences provide.  &quot;As a former professor myself, I know 
the challenge that these students face on college campuses,&quot; he acknowledges.  &quot;The work 
of Young America's Foundation is a useful antidote to the usual liberal litany on the 
college campus.&quot;
<P>Above all, Mr. Pearson looks for speakers that are activist leaders and who have 
bold ideas and a strong message.  When asked what sets these leaders apart from the rest, he 
replied that he seeks legislators who &quot;want to come 
to Congress to <I>do things</I>, rather than just come 
to Congress.  They have some idea in mind of 
<I>why</I> they were elected to Congress and what 
they want to accomplish.  They have some specific ideas, not just, `Well, I want to make 
things better.'  You can usually tell when members 
get to Congress, in their first couple years, if they're going to be active or inactive.&quot;
<P>Mr. Pearson also recruits speakers whose lives can serve as an inspiration to students. 
 One such speaker, Representative <B>Chris Cox</B> 
of California, is an excellent role model for students.  &quot;When Chris was in law school,&quot; 
Mr. Pearson explains, &quot;he was working on his 
MBA at the same time he was working on his Law degree, and he was also one of the editors 
of the <I>Harvard Law Review</I>.&quot;  Mr. Pearson 
points out that congressmen such as Chris Cox, 
<B>Dana Rohrabacher</B>, and <B>Mark Souder</B> were 
conservative activists as students and &quot;have 
remained conservative activists in Congress.&quot;
<P>Mr. Pearson also has advice for students wishing to pursue careers on Capitol Hill: 
 &quot;The important thing is to get involved 
early, as a student, get involved on a 
philosophical basis.  Be well educated and well read.  So 
you not only have a knowledge of the issues, but also 
the philosophy behind them.  It gives you a much wider 
background and better grasp of the process and lets you 
handle issues much easier; particularly if you want to work in 
a congressional office.
<P>&quot;As a student, it is also important to be involved, 
by bringing speakers to campus, by sponsoring the 
programs that the Foundation encourages, because that helps to 
develop the skills that are necessary to succeed in any field.&quot;


<p><p><HR><p><p><center>
<B><a name="rotc"></a>New Law Prohibits Defense Department Funding of Schools that Discriminate Against ROTC </b><BR>
<h3>Foundation, ROTC Students Defeat Campus Leftists</h3>
[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
Young America's Foundation activists scored a major victory  on February 10, when the ROTC Campus Access Act was signed into law by the President.  The legislation, which cuts off Department of Defense funding to colleges and 
universities that ban the Reserve Officer Training Corps was part of this year's 
Defense Authorization Act.  It was introduced following a public information 
campaign, conducted by Young America's Foundation, designed to expose 
unfair discrimination against ROTC cadets and bolsters the right of students to 
participate in ROTC on their campuses.
<P>The law marks a huge defeat for campus radicals intent on 
denying students the right to participate in military programs on campus.  
Historically, the ROTC program has assisted economically disadvantaged 
students, providing scholarships for those willing to make a commitment to serve 
their country.  By limiting access to ROTC, many academics who purport to 
promote diversity and educational opportunity have in reality undermined these ideals. 
 Many poor and middle class students are able to afford the costly price of higher 
education solely because of the financial assistance 
ROTC provides. <B> Colin Powell</B>, Secretary of 
Education <B>Richard Reilly</B>, Senator <B>Strom 
Thurmond</B>, and former senator and current University of Oklahoma President 
<B>David Boren</B> are a few of the many 
distinguished Americans who benefited from the 
ROTC program.
<P>The first massive wave of expulsions of ROTC programs dates back to the 
Vietnam War, when radical activists forced the 
military off campus through protests, violent 
demonstrations, and even bombings.  Today, many of those same 1960s protesters now call the 
shots on campus as faculty and administrators, 
using the armed forces' &quot;don't ask, don't tell&quot; 
policy on homosexuals as a pretense to prevent students from participating in ROTC. 
<P>Many Young America's Foundation supporters will remember the story of 
<B>Flagg Youngblood </B>and the persecution that he 
and his fellow ROTC cadets at Yale University faced.  Banned from meeting on their 
own campus by leftist faculty and administrators, Yale's cadets are forced to travel 65 miles to 
the nearest ROTC unit if they wish to participate 
in the program.  Not only does this policy cut off educational opportunities for students and 
deny the armed forces the quality officers it 
deserves, it also endangers the lives of students 
who choose to defend our country.  Three times in the past two years cadets making the trip to 
the distant campus have been involved in serious car accidents.  These accidents were 
attributed to slick New England winter roads and 
exhausted cadets falling asleep at the wheel.  
This is all happening while Yale's faculty and 
administrators solicit and accept Department of Defense research grants and contracts. 
<P>Sadly, Yale's hypocritical stance of banning ROTC while accepting defense funds is 
followed by a number of other schools including Harvard, Stanford, Columbia, and Brown 
to name a few.  
<P>After Young America's Foundation disseminated these disturbing facts to the 
general public, members of Congress began taking action against academia's 
pervasive anti-military policies.  This educational campaign included 
appearances on over 20 talk shows, including National Empowerment Television's 
<I>Capitol Watch</I>, where Foundation staffers described the discrimination members 
of the armed forces face on campus.  A petition drive succeeded in alerting 
tens of thousands of Americans to the problems patriotic students serving 
their country encounter as a result of leftist faculty and administrators.  
<P>An education campaign by Young America's Foundation activists both 
on Capitol Hill and through the mail resulted in Congressman 
<B>Richard Pombo</B> introducing the ROTC Campus Access Act.  Revealing op/ed 
articles written by Foundation Program Officer <B>Dan Flynn 
</B>for <I>The Washington Times</I> and <I>Human 
Events</I>  the latter of which was read from on the floor of the 
House of Representatives by Congressman <B>Jack 
Kingston</B>  provided much of the information used in debate against 
anti-military colleges and universities.
<P>With the passage of the ROTC Campus Access Act, ROTC supporters look to 
the future with much optimism, citing the example of a 1993 law which cut off Defense funds 
for schools that banned military recruiters from meeting with students on campus. 
Following the passage of that legislation, all but one of 
the 140 colleges and universities which had previously banned military recruiters opened 
their doors rather than risk a loss of funding.  It 
is uncertain whether any school will continue to ban ROTC 
and risk losing millions of dollars in grants and 
contracts.
<P>Commenting on the success of this type of strategy, 
Young America's Foundation President <B>Ron 
Robinson </B>explained, &quot;While left-wing 
academics may not listen to reason, they often listen 
when the flow of money, the lifeline of many colleges 
and universities, is jeopardized.&quot;<BR>

<p><p><HR><p><p><center>
<h3><a name="will"></a>Armstrong Williams Inspires Large Student Audience</h3>
<BR>
<B>Conservative Political Action Conference Luncheon Features Radio, T.V. Host Armstrong Williams</B><P>
[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>

&quot;Personal responsibility.  Economic independence.  Thrift.  The work ethic.  Optimism.  Hope.  Ambition.  Enthusiasm.  Perseverance.  Pride... These are some of the many values my parents taught their children...&quot;  And they are some of the many ideals <B>Armstrong 
Williams</B> imparted to his <B>student audience of 300</B> at a recent Young America's Foundation's luncheon. Armstrong Williams is the host of two nationally syndicated radio programs, 
<I>The Right Side</I> and <I>The Armstrong Williams  Show</I>, and a weekly program which airs on 
National Empowerment Television.  His columns frequently appear in <I>Reader's Digest </I>and <I>USA Today</I>, and run nationally on the  <I>L.A. Times</I> Syndicate.  He is the author of 
<I>Beyond Blame:  How We Can Succeed by Breaking the Dependency Barrier</I>, and also serves as the CEO of a Washington D.C. based public relations firm.
<P>Mr. Williams' message of personal responsibility and the importance of family 
resonated with the students and was met with fervent applause as he stated, &quot;Families are the 
first, best departments of Health, Education, and Welfare.  Our policies must assist families, rather than punish marriage and reward promiscuity.  Our policies should encourage industry, rather than reward indolence.  Our laws should be equally and fairly applied to all Americans, offering opportunity to all, and special treatment to no one, be they wealthy or poor, man or woman, black, white or brown.&quot;
<P>Held annually in Washington, D.C., the Foundation's CPAC luncheon attracts 
student leaders from across the nation.  <B>Tina 
Tran</B>, a student from UCLA, thought Armstrong Williams' speech &quot;was absolutely fantastic!&quot;  Loyola College student <B>Sergio Vitale</B> was 
so inspired by Mr. Williams' message that he is already making plans to sponsor him on 
campus next fall.  &quot;Armstrong Williams' speech 
was by far the best event in the whole CPAC line-up!&quot; raved Sergio.
<P>Deeply proud of the liberties we cherish in America, Armstrong Williams impressed 
upon the students that, &quot;Freedom is not free.  
It requires as much exertion to maintain it as to establish it.  Especially in a free nation, 
every citizen has certain duties:  to him-self, his family, and to his 
fellow countrymen.  Freedom requires risks, but 
its rewards are great.&quot;<BR>

<hr><center><p><p><a name="about">[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</a></center><P>
<b>Publisher: Ron Robinson<br>Editor: Matthew Schenk<br>Design Photos: Twin Lens Photo</b>
<p><i>Libertas</i> is published 
by Young America's Foundation, 110 Elden Street, Herndon, Virginia 22070 (703) 318-9608.
<p>Young America's Foundation was formed in order to provide essential conferences seminars educational materials scholarships and speakers to the young people of America. As an educational organization, the Foundation strives to acquaint American youth with the principles of American government and the genius of the American political system in order that they may have a fuller understanding of contemporary public policy questions. Contributions are tax deductible. The Foundation gratefully accepts contributions from individuals, corporations, and other foundations.<p><p>[ <a href="home.html">YAF Home</a> ]</body></html>

