<H3>Terry Eastland to Deliver 1996-97 Hermann Lectures</H3><BR>
<B>Terry Eastland</B>, author of 
<I>     Ending Affirmative Action: 
     The Case for Colorblind Justice</I>, will be the featured 
speaker of the Foundation's <B>Grover Hermann Freedom Lecture 
Series</B> for the 1996-1997 academic year. 
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="eastland.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=206><BR>
<B><I>Terry Eastland</B>, 1996-97 Grover Hermann Lecturer.
</td></tr>
</table>  
Mr. Eastland offers a 
compelling criticism of race-based quotas and rigged admissions 
policies.  He argues that the true test of a democracy is its adherence 
to colorblindness. 
<P>Mr. Eastland is editor of <I>Forbes 
MediaCritic</I> and a fellow at the <BR>
Ethics and Public Policy Center in Washington, D.C.  He is a 
leading authority on Supreme Court decisions concerning not only race 
but also religious freedom.  His research and experience give him 
a unique perspective on the impact of affirmative action.  
<P>The Grover Hermann Freedom Lecture Series was named 
in memory of the entrepreneur, <B>Grover 
Hermann</B>.  As founder of American Asphalt Company 
and chairman of the board of Martin Marietta Corporation until 
his death in 1979, Mr. Hermann was remembered as a man who 
generously contributed both his time and fortune to many 
philanthropies.
<P>To bring Mr. Eastland to speak on your campus, call 
<B>Stephen Slivinski</B> at 1-800-292-9231.
<P>
