<BR>
<H3>Are There &quot;Screwballs, Devil Dames, and 
Closet Cases&quot; in Your College's Curriculum?</H3>
Young America's Founda
          tion has just completed the 
          second edition of <I>Comedy and Tragedy:  College Course 
Descriptions and What They Tell Us About Higher Education 
Today</I>.
<P>This edition examines courses from fifty national 
universities and liberal arts colleges and concludes that bizarre 
and trendy courses have infiltrated every facet of higher 
education.
<P>To many, courses such as Harvard's &quot;A Thousand 
Feminisms,&quot; De Paul's &quot;Sociology of Rock Music,&quot; 
and Amherst's &quot;Black English&quot; are 
merely amusing, but college students understand that the 
product of this kind of frivolous, &quot;multicultural&quot; curriculum is 
an inferior education and poor preparation for the job market.
<P>Parents, taxpayers, concerned educators, and prospective employers should also be troubled 
by this tragedy in American higher education.  Due to this 
obsession with multiculturalism and &quot;victim studies,&quot; an entire generation 
of students is being ill-prepared for life in the real world.
<P><I>Comedy and Tragedy </I>reveals that courses such as 
&quot;Sorcery and Magic,&quot; and &quot;Sex and Gender on Film: 
Screwballs, Devil Dames, and Closet Cases,&quot; are just the tip of 
the iceberg.  
<P>
<BR>
To order this in-depth study of the modern 
college curriculum, contact <B>Dede Hamilton </B>at 1-800-292-9231. <HR>
