<p><hr>
<center><a name="medved"><h3>Film Critic Michael Medved<BR> Selected as 1995-96<BR>
Grover Hermann Freedom Lecturer</h3>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
Film critic <b>Michael Medved</b> will be featured as this year's <B>Grover Hermann Freedom Lecturer</b>. As the co-host of Sneak Previews and the chief film critic for The New York Post, Mr. Medved is an authority in the debate over cultural values and the role that Hollywood plays in influencing them. Most recently, he has appeared as a guest host on the Rush Limbaugh Radio Show.
<p>
As a best-selling author and nationally recognized television personality, Mr. Medved has been featured in numerous televised debates concerning the negative impact of the entertainment industry. His most indelible contribution to this subject, however, is his book Hollywood vs. America. Speaking at the Foundation' s 1995 Summer Conference, Mr. Medved noted that Senator Robert Dole, in making his highly publicized speech denouncing the film, television, and music industries, drew much of his theme from <B><I>Hollywood vs. America</B></I>. "Senator Dole had a copy of my book on the podium, somewhat visible," Mr. Medved noted, "and I do know that he quoted four sentences from my book more or less verbatim. . . and he even acknowledged one of them. . . which I was very pleased to see."
<p>
Michael Medved is also the author of several other books, including <b><I>The Shadow Presidents, Hospital: The Hidden Lives of a Medical Center Staff</B></I?, and <B><I>What Really Happened to the Class of '65?</b></I>, which served as the basis for an NBC television series. He is also a member of the Writer' s Guild of America and has worked as a screenwriter on several major studio film projects.
<p>
The Grover Hermann Freedom Lecture Series was named in memory of philanthropist and entrepreneur, Grover Hermann. Mr. Hermann's career has been described as an "old-fashioned, free enterprise success story." In 1913, at age 23, he used a $5,000 investment to start the American Asphalt Company, which he expanded over the years into a large, diversified nationwide corporation.
<p>
Mr. Hermann's business, renamed American Marietta Company in the early 1930's, ultimately merged with the Martin Company in 1961 to form Martin Marietta Corporation for which he served as chairman of the board. At the time of his death in 1979, Mr. Hermann was remembered not only as a great entrepreneur and businessman, but also as a man who generously contributed both time and fortune to many philanthropies.
<p>
To find out how you may submit a proposal to bring Mr. Medved to speak at your campus, please call <b>Michelle Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.


<p><p><hr><center><a name="document"><h3>Document Leftist Bias on Your Campus!</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center>
<p>
When was the last time you heard a conservative lecturer speak on your campus? If you can't remember, chances are your college is like most others, in that an endless stream of liberals are paraded onto campus, all warmly embraced by college faculty and administrators, while no effort is made to bring in traditional or free market ideas.
<p>
What can you do to turn this tide and hold your college accountable for providing educational balance? One way is to document just how one-sided the campus debate is by researching the speakers your college has sponsored recently.
<p>
Students at Swarthmore College combed through the archives of the campus newspaper, and discovered that in the past four years not one conservative had been featured as a guest lecturer. During that same period, dozens of radical liberals were sponsored by the college, including a former leader of the Black Panthers, politicians such as Lenora Fulani and Michael Dukakis, and no less than 15 "experts" on multiculturalism and homosexual issues. With this information, these students were able to convince the college to help bring in Young America's Foundation speakers <b>William Buckley, Star Parker, Michael Medved, Walter Williams, </b>and<b> Dinesh D'Souza</b>.
<p>
Students at Appalachian State University went even farther, going back eight years and totaling exactly how much money was spent to bring in speakers such as Abbie Hoffman, Molly Yard, Maya Angelou, and Ralph Nader. After they were finished with their research, the front-page headline in the next issue of their student paper read: "Liberal Speakers - $242,000; Conservative Speakers - $0."
<p>
Ask your campus' speaker selection committee for a list of past guest lecturers, or look back through past issues of the school newspaper to find out who your campus has been sponsoring. Once you have your results, publicize them by notifying local newspapers and radio talk shows. Send a letter to sympathetic alumni, letting them know what speakers your college has been endorsing.
<p>
The next step is to use the information as a leveraging point to get the college administration and speakers committee to help you bring in alternative speakers. Every college that has done this kind of research in the past has achieved great success in sponsoring conservative lecturers.
<p>
After you have documented the bias and made the case for balancing your college's lecture program, contact Young America's Foundation and we can help you sponsor a speaker on your campus.
 


<p><p><hr><center><a name="clc">
<h3>Conservative Leadership Conference<BR> to be Held in Atlanta:<BR> November 10-11</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center>
<p>
Need a break from your liberal professors? Come spend a weekend hearing from top conservative leaders Robert Novak and Oliver North! Leave sensitivity training behind and join fellow right-minded students at the <B>1995 Conservative Leadership Conference!
</b><p>
Young America' s Foundation is proud to host our fall regional Conservative Leadership Conference in <b>Atlanta, Georgia on November 10-11, 1995</b>. Campus leaders from across the South are invited to meet in Atlanta for this two-day conference focusing on current public policy issues, free market economics, and the future of the conservative movement.
<p>
Confirmed speakers include CNN commentator <b>Robert Novak</b>, author <b>Peter Schweizer</b>, economist <b>Thomas DiLorenzo</b>, and radio show host <b>Lt. Colonel Oliver North</b>. In addition, Young America's Foundation President <b>Ron Robinson</b> will brief students on how to become more effective campus activists.
<p>
The Conservative Leadership Conference will begin at 5:00 p.m., Friday, November 10 and conclude by 4:00 p.m. on Saturday, November 11. The conference, cosponsored by Freedom Alliance, will be held at the Stouffer Renaissance Waverly Hotel and Cobb Galleria Conference Center in Atlanta.
<p>
The registration fee is $100, although <b>this fee is waived for full-time college students.</b> Please contact <b>Kristen Kingsley</b> at 1-800-292-9231 for more information or to receive a registration form. (All registration is subject to written confirmation.)


<p><p><hr><center><a 
name="courses"><h3>Witches, Werewolves, and Ouija Boards?<br>
What College Course Descriptions Tell Us<br>
About Higher Education</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><p>
<b>Comedy and Tragedy: College Course Descriptions and What They Tell Us About Higher Education Today</b> is a survey published by Young America's Foundation documenting the decay of academic standards in the classes offered at our nation's top colleges and universities. Young America's Foundation found that a disturbingly high number of classes propagate ideology (including feminism, anti-Americanism, and Marxism), and not education.
<p>
Such classes as Yale's "Drag Queens, Transsexuals, and Queers:  Anthropological Approaches," Harvard's "Perceptions of the Supernatural: Witches, Werewolves, and Ouija Boards," and Columbia's "Race, Gender, and the Politics of Rock 'n' Roll" are among the hundreds of bizarre courses listed.
<p>
While <i>Comedy and Tragedy</I> is not for sale, students can obtain copies of the report by sending Young America's Foundation at least five politically correct courses offered by your school. Though not every school offers titles as bizarre as the University of Michigan's "Lesbian Literature" or SUNY-Albany's "Society's Nightmare: Images of Gender, Race, and Class in Horror Film," we are confident that you can add to the list of questionable courses.
<p>
If you wish to receive <i>Comedy and Tragedy</I>, send the aforementioned information to <b>Dan Flynn</b> at Young America's Foundation, 110 Elden Street, Herndon, VA 22070. Make sure to note the department in which the courses you list are offered and the full description that appears in your school's course catalogue.


<p><p><hr><center><a name="williams"><h3>Walter Williams to Deliver
<BR>1995-96 Salvatori Lectures</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center>
<p>
Young America's Foundation is pleased to announce that <B>Walter Williams</b> is the <b>1995-96 Henry Salvatori Lecturer</b>. Dr. Williams, the John M. Olin Distinguished Professor of Economics at George Mason University, is a nationally syndicated columnist and appears regularly as a guest host on the <I>Rush Limbaugh Radio Show</i>.
<p>
Currently an adjunct scholar at the Heritage Foundation and the CATO Institute, Dr. Williams received his B.A. in economics from California State University, and his M.A. and Ph.D. degrees in economics from UCLA.
<p>
Dr. Williams is the author of several books, including <I><B>The State Against Blacks, America: A Minority Viewpoint</B></I>, and <i><b>All It Takes Is Guts</b></i>.
<p>
<B>Henry Salvatori</B> is the founder of Western Geophysical Company, one of the largest oil-exploration contracting organizations with worldwide operations. He founded Western Geophysical in 1933 and, after a merger with Litton Industries in 1960, he continued as Western' s chief executive officer and director of Litton Industries until his retirement in 1967. Mr. Salvatori is a graduate of the University of Pennsylvania, and received his masters degree in physics from Columbia University. He is a trustee of the University of Southern California and <a href="http://www.mckenna.edu">Claremont McKenna College</a>.
<p>
If you would like to have Dr. Williams speak on your campus, please call <b>Michele Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.

<p><p><hr><center><a name="contact"><h3>Contact Information</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center><p>Campus Leader is published by Young America's Foundation.<p>Address all editorial matter, free subscription inquiries, and changes ot address to Campus Leader, 110 Elden Street, Herndon, Virginia 22070.<p>Young America's Foundation was formed in order to provide essential conferences, seminars, educational materials, scholarships and speakers to the young people ot America. As an educational organization, the Foundation strives to acquaint American youth with the principles of American government and the genius of the American political system in order that they may have a fuller understanding of contemporary public policy questions.<p><p><p>[ <a href="home.html"> YAF Home</a> ]</body></html>
