<p><hr>
<center><a name="speakers"><h3>95 Speakers Booklet Includes<br> Buckley, Reed, D'Souza, and Quayle</h3>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
It is time to begin planning which speakers you will bring to your campus this fall. Young America's Foundation's 1995-96 speakers program booklet features not only prominent leaders of the conservative movement who are available to speak on your campus, but also includes crucial information on how to host a successful event.<P>

Last year the Foundation sponsored speakers such as <b>Margaret Thatcher, Walter Williams</b>, and <b>Dan Quayle</b> on campuses across the country. New additions to the speakers booklet this year include <b>G. Gordon Liddy, Ralph Reed, P.J. O'Rourke, Marilyn Quayle</b>, and <i>USA Today's</i> <b>Tony Snow</b>. To order your free copy of the speakers booklet, or to sponsor a Foundation speaker, please call <b>Michelle Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.


<p><p><hr><center><a name="gov"><h3>Is the Government Crushing Your Job Prospects?</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center>
<p>
Concerned about finding a job when you graduate? It's tough out there for a couple of reasons, and they might surprise you. Big government and political correctness are a graduate's main adversaries. Over-regulation of every type of industry combined with the diminishing regard corporate leaders have for today's college degrees are dramatically impacting recent college graduates' ability to find employment.
<P>Through the Foundation program, <i>Job Prospects for College Graduates: What's the Problem?</i>, free market economists and corporate leaders will speak to students on these critical issues, giving students the insights they need for maximizing their educational opportunities and avoiding the pitfalls of a useless degree. <p>
Students who participate in our program will gain a unique understanding of the job market and of the qualities employers are seeking in new recruits.
<P>Young America's 
Foundation will work with you in developing a program which will meet the needs of your campus. We will provide literature, including <b><i>Job Prospects for College Graduates: The Role of Government</i></b> and <b><i>The Responsibilities of the University</i></b>, a monograph written by economics professor <b>Thomas J. DiLorenzo</b> and published by Young America's Foundation. We will also assist you in bringing a corporate leader and free market scholar to your school. If you are interested in participating in this Foundation program, please call <b>Kate Griffin</b> at 1-800-292-9231.


<p><p><hr><center><a name="novak">
<h3>Political Commentator Robert Novak<BR> to Deliver 1995-96 William Howard Flowers, Jr. Lecture Series</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center>
<p>
Young America's Foundation is pleased to announce <b>Robert Novak</b> as the featured speaker for the <b>1995 William H. Flowers Lecture Series</b>.<P>
<b>William Flowers</b> is the former chairman of Flowers Industries, a Fortune 500 company with distribution throughout the United States. A graduate of Washington and Lee University at the age of 19, William Flowers has a lifelong commitment to traditional values and the free market. As a former Georgia state senator, he authored the "Georgia Plan," which called for a constitutional amendment to balance the budget.
<P>This year's Flowers lecturer, Robert Novak, is one of the country's most respected journalists and political commentators. A nationally syndicated political columnist, he is also a commentator on CNN, where he is co-host of the Evans and Novak interview program. He frequently co-hosts CNN's <I>Crossfire</i>, and often appears as an interviewer on NBC's <i>Meet the Press</i>.<P> If you are interested in balancing the debate on your campus by having Robert Novak or other Foundation lecturers speak at your school this year, please call the Foundation and discuss details with <b>Michelle Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.



<p><p><hr><center><a 
name="history"><h3>History Scholars Discredit Renewed Attempt to Politicize National History Standard</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><p>
Just like Jason from "Friday the 
13th" or "A Nightmare on Elm Street's" Freddy Kreuger, the <b>National Standards for History</b> is a monstrosity that refuses to die.
<P>A product of the Goals 2000 
project, strongly endorsed by President Clinton, the Standard s met with widespread criticism when they were first released last year. Blasted for their politically correct revisionism and strong anti-Western bias, it appeared that the Standards had been completely defeated, especially after the U.S. Senate voted 99-1 to condemn them.<P>
In February, however, the National Center for History in the Schools, the group based out of UCLA that created the Standards, redoubled its efforts to inject the flawed curriculum into grade schools and high schools across the country. The Center produced a slick brochure showcasing the National Standards, attempting to market them directly to school districts. The debate is clearly far from being over.<P>
In response to this attempt, Continuity, the history journal published by Young America's Foundation, asked eleven of the country's most respected history scholars to assess the Standards based on their historical merit.<P>
The result is the most in-depth, fact-based criticism of the Standards to date. This special issue of <I>Continuity</i> will give you all the ammunition you need to discuss or debate the National Standards with your professors or classmates.<P>
If you would like to receive a free copy of <I>Continuity</I>, please call 1800-292-9231.



<p><p><hr><center><a name="last word"><h3>Don't Let the Liberals Have the Last Word!</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center>
<p>Have you ever been in a class and had your professor or a classmate go on and on expounding some liberal position? Perhaps you wanted to challenge their arguments but were reluctant because you didn't have all the facts on hand. Young America's Foundation would like to help.
<P>We understand that 
conservatives are overwhelmingly outnumbered on campuses, and that conservative ideas are rarely mentioned in the classroom unless they are being distorted by a professor. It is easy for students to come across the liberal arguments in their classes, in casual discussions, or in the campus paper. In order to learn about conservative ideas, however, students need to go out of their way, doing their own research and taking the initiative. Achieving philosophical balance in higher education can be a very time consuming project.
<P>To help students learn about the other side of the argument, Young America's Foundation is compiling and will distribute "issue briefs" on the most controversial and hotly debated issues on campus. The Foundation's issue briefs will assist you in learning the conservative side of the argument. With the information provided by them, you will be able to challenge liberal professors, misguided classmates, and slanted editorials.<P>
The first issue brief will deal with the liberal policy of affirmative action and will be available within the first weeks of the school year. If you would like to be put on the mailing list to receive these briefs, or if you would like to suggest a topic for a future issue brief, please contact <B>Matthew Schenk</b> at Young America's Foundation at 1-800-292-9231.



<p><p><hr><center><a name="schweizer"><h3>Schweizer to Inaugurate William Casey Lecture Series</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center><p>
Young America's Foundation is 
proud to announce its newest lecture program: the <b>William Casey Lecture Series</b>. Named in honor of the late <b>William Casey</b>, who served under Ronald Reagan as the director of the C.I.A. from 1981-86, the Casey Lecture Series will feature author <b>Peter Schweizer</b> as its inaugural speaker.
<P>Mr. Schweizer is the author of several books, including Friendly Spies, and Victory: The Reagan Administration's Secret Strategy that Hastened the Collapse of the Soviet Union. In Victory, Mr. Schweizer uncovered previously unpublished information revealing that the United States' victory in the Cold War was a direct result of actions taken by the Reagan Administration. The main architect of this strategy, Schweizer's research revealed, was C.I.A. Director Casey. Mr. Schweizer has been active with Young America' s Foundation since a student in high school, and served as its academic director from 1991 to 1994.
<P>A true American hero, William Casey not only headed the C.I.A. and directly helped to bring about the collapse of communism, but he also served as the manager of Ronald Reagan's 1980 presidential campaign.
<P>To have Mr. Schweizer speak at your campus, please contact <b>Michelle Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.



<p><p><hr><center><a name="rush"><h3>Foundation Offers 'Rush Limbaugh Show' Tickets</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center><p>
Young America's Foundation is offering college students the once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to attend live tapings of "<b>The Rush Limbaugh Show</b>."
<P>The tapings will take place in November, with tickets being distributed only to students organized in blocks of ten who attend the same school.
<P>Serious dittoheads interested 
in being a part of Rush's live television audience should contact Dan Flynn at Young America's Foundation at 1-800-292-9231.




<p><p><hr><center><a name="tapes"><h3>Gingrich, Lott, Bono, North Tapes Available!</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]</center><p>

<b>Newt Gingrich, Jack Kemp, Robert Novak, Fred Barnes, Walter Williams, Dinesh D'Souza, Ralph Reed, Michael Medved, Trent Lott, Sonny Bono</b>, and <b>Oliver North</b> have a lot in common. Not just their conservative ideals. Not simply the fact that they are top national leaders. These individuals, among others, recently addressed the 17th annual National Conservative Student Conference.
<P>Four hundred activists from campuses nationwide convened from July 23 to 29 in Washington D C. for the most comprehensive conservative conference available to students. The Summer Conference taught student leaders from hundreds of colleges and universities how to become more effective campus activists and exposed them to lectures by leaders of national prominence. Each summer, Young America's Foundation hosts the National Conservative Student Conference to help balance students' increasingly liberal education.
<P>If you missed out on 
attending this once-in-a-lifetime event, you still have an opportunity to benefit from the lectures and advice given by the nation's most influential leaders. Audio tapes of all lectures are available for $10 apiece. You may also purchase a set of six for $58, or the entire set of 33 lectures for only $310. To purchase cassettes, please contact <b>Wells Walker Company</b> at 1-800-645-6907.


