<html>
<title>Department of Lectures and Educational Programs -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></center>
<H3>DEPARTMENT  OF  LECTURES  AND  EDUCATIONAL  PROGRAMS 
</H3>
<HR>
<p>

<h3>1995</h3>
<p>
	The department of lectures and seminars hosted 32 lectures in the last three months of 1995, 
bringing over 1500 people into the Heritage Building.  There were four standing room only events: a 
conference entitled "The New Great Game: Pipeline Politics in the Caucasus and Central Asia," a 
panel discussion on "Communism's Post-Mortem:  Six Years After the Fall of the Berlin Wall," a 
lecture <a href="/heritage/library/categories/forpol/lect544.html">"Rebirth, Return, Reunion: 
Hungary's Euro-Atlantic Agenda"</a> with The Honorable Arpad Goncz, President of Hungary,  and 
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/lect545.html">"Homer, Shakespeare and Tolstoy: What 
Literature Teaches About the Collapse and Recovery of the Family"</a> with David Patterson, 
Associate Professor of European Literature, Oklahoma State University.  Other successful events with 
large attendance included "Debt Ceiling Politics:  A Wall Street Perspective," "Why We Should 
Defund Political Advocacy Groups, and "Can Congress Promote Civil Society?"
<P>
	The Russell Kirk  Memorial Lecture series continued through 1995 with parts two through four  
of a four-part series. The second lecture was given by David Patterson, Associate Professor of 
European Literature, Oklahoma State University, on <a href=" 
/heritage/library/categories/family/lect545.html">"Homer, Shakespeare and Tolstoy: What 
Literature Teaches About the Collapse and Recovery of the Family."</a>  The third lecture featured 
Annette Kirk, President, The Russell Kirk Center for Cultural Renewal, on <a href=" 
/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect547.html">"The Conservative Heart: Life With Russell 
Kirk."</a>  The fourth lecture, <a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/lect550.html">"The Mystic Chords of Memory: Reclaiming America's History"</a> was 
given by Wilfred McClay, Associate Professor of History, Tulane University.
<p>
	The <a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/3gener.html">Third Generation Project</a> held two 
Wednesday evening meetings, as well as the Christmas Party.  The highlight was a lecture on "What 
Comes Next: The End of Big Government -- and the New Paradigm Ahead" featuring Jim Pinkerton, 
Newsday Columnist and former Domestic Policy Advisor to President Bush.
<p>
<p>
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG 
SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>

</HTML>  
	

	

	
