<HEAD>

<TITLE>What is the Resource Bank? -- Heritage</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><IMG SRC="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a></center>
<P>
<H2>What is the Resource Bank?</H2>
<HR>
<P>
Building the conservative movement is the main function of the Heritage Foundation's nineteen-year old <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/rtoc.html">Resource Bank</a>.  Part of
Heritage's <a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/extrel.html">External Relations</a> Department, the Resource Bank is
a communications link and information clearinghouse for some 400
conservative policy groups and 2,000 conservative experts and
scholars around the world.
<P>
Its main activities include publishing the monthly <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/rtoc.html#insid"><I>Insider</I></a>
Newsletter and biennial <I>Guide To Public Policy Experts</I>,
hosting several regular policy working groups; building directories
of policy organizations, experts, and activists; organizing conferences
and meetings of conservative scholars and policy group directors;
and handling referrals concerning conservative groups and experts.
<P>
Placing special emphasis on the growing network of grassroots
and state policy organizations, The Heritage Foundation Resource
Bank advances the conservative cause by highlighting the work
of other conservative groups, promoting strong intra-movement
communications, and organizing timely leadership strategy forums.
 
<P>
For more information about the Resource Bank please contact <a href="mailto:meadt@heritage.org">Tom Mead</a>, Program Manager, Resource Bank, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C.  20002,  202/546-4400,
Fax 202/544-0961.
<P>
Go to the <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/rtoc.html">Resource Bank</a>. 
<p>

