<title>Ed Facts</title>

<body background="/townhall/FRC/images/bckgnd7.jpg" text="#ff0000" 
vlink="#000000">

<center><h1>ED FACTS - JANUARY 3</h1>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/edfacts/pencil.gif">
</center>
<p>

<font size=+1>

<center><h3>BANISHING THE BARD, AND OTHER ENGLISH TRAGEDIES</h3></center>

<p>

William Shakespeare and other great authors
of English literature are no longer required reading at most of
the nation's top colleges and universities, according to a study
released last week by the National Alumni Forum.  &quot;The Shakespeare
File:  What English Majors Are Really Studying&quot; surveys English
major requirements at 70 leading institutions of higher learning.

<p>

The National Alumni Forum (NAF), a non-profit
organization &quot;dedicated to academic freedom and excellence&quot;
and chaired by Lynne Cheney, launched its study when Georgetown
University announced in early 1996 the elimination of its great
authors requirement for English majors.  Georgetown had been among
the many colleges which, until recently, required majors to study
the work of at least one (in Georgetown's case, two) of the three
writers hailed as &quot;the pre-eminent representatives of English
language and literature -- Geoffrey Chaucer, William Shakespeare,
and John Milton.&quot;

<p>

Of the 70 schools surveyed, only 23 now require
English majors to take a Shakespeare course, which NAF loosely
defined as any course in which students read two of the three
great English authors.  &quot;The National Alumni Forum conducted
this study to see if the decline in standards at Georgetown was
an isolated incident or part of a national trend,&quot; NAF president
Jerry L. Martin explained.  &quot;The survey confirmed our worst
fears.  Dropping Shakespeare is not just a trend; it is the norm.&quot;

<p>

Shakespeare gets the boot for courses in pop
culture and sex.  The NAF study reports a litany of new fads (in
terms taken directly from course descriptions):  advertising imagery,
AIDS activism, attitudes to marriage, capture of the state, electronic
frontier, feminism, futurism, global factory, homophobia, living
arrangements, Madonna, music videos, oppression and marginalization,
politics of representation, rock and rap music, socialist struggle,
transnationalism, work and play habits, world wide web, etc.

<p>

&quot;Individuals will be exposed to popular
culture their whole lives; college is the time for studying something
deeper and more enduring,&quot; the NAF report aptly remarks.
C.S. Lewis also warned of &quot;the dangers of an exclusive contemporary
diet.  A new book is still on its trial and the amateur is not
in a position to judge it&quot;  (&quot;On the Reading of Old
Books&quot;; <I>God in the Dock</I>).  How will students be able
to critique any of these topics in modern culture without a mooring
in the literature of the past?

<p><blockquote>

<i>&quot;Universities without Shakespeare?
Unthinkable. Language without Shakespeare?  Unspeakable.  I'm
heartened by the National Alumni Forum's effort to stop the erosion
of the greatest artist in the history of the world....  Thank
God he's already translated, and constantly performed, in just
about every language on earth.  Keep him there.&quot;</i>

<p>

<center>-- Charlton Heston</center>

</blockquote><p>

<b>ACTION:</b> For a copy of the NAF study, &quot;The Shakespeare File: 
What English Majors Are Really Studying,&quot; contact the National
Alumni Forum at 1625 K St., N.W., Suite 310, Washington, D.C.
20006-1604; telephone (202) 467-6787.

<p>

<center><h3>HIGHER ON DRUGS</h3></center>

<p>

One in five 10th graders used marijuana within
the past month, according to the National Institute on Drug Abuse's
&quot;Monitoring the Future Survey&quot; released December 19.
The survey found a <I><B>190 percent</B></I> <I><B>increase</B></I>
over the past five years in adolescent use of illicit drugs.

<p>

The survey also indicates a move from dabbling
to dependence.  Among high school seniors who use marijuana, one
in nine smoke it daily.  The perception of risk associated with
marijuana has declined -- by 25 percent since 1991 -- a trend
that won't be reversed without a strong, certain message from
national leaders.

<p>

&quot;President Clinton has been outspoken
about snuffing-out Joe Camel and Mr. Kool but has been virtually
silent on illicit drugs.  School-age children know the president's
MTV 'I didn't inhale' confession and use it to trivialize drug
use,&quot; notes FRC Senior Policy Analyst Lt. Col. Robert Maginnis.
&quot;It's about time the president, who has forced states to
increase their level of enforcement on tobacco, put a similar
emphasis on fighting the drug scourge -- especially the legalization
campaign that has already overwhelmed California and Arizona and
threatens to engulf the rest of the country.&quot;

<p>

In response to California and Arizona drug
legalization propositions which passed in November, a Clinton
Administration team presented last Monday its campaign against
further drug legalization.  &quot;The only problem was that the
team was missing its quarterback.  President Clinton needs to
personally tackle this national crisis,&quot;  Col. Maginnis said.

<p>

The Goals 2000 legislation ostensibly aims
for drug-free schools by the Year 2000.  Two and a half years
after its passage, the problem continues to get worse, in part
because the president who gave us Goals 2000 hasn't given us a
clear message on drugs.

<p>

<b>ACTION:</b>  Talk to your kids about the dangers of drugs.  Watch 
for resources from Family Research Council in the weeks to come.

<p><hr width=50%><p>

<font size=-1>
<i><b>Ed Facts</b> is a weekly facsimile publication of Family
Research Council, 801 G St., N.W., Washington, D.C.
20001. Phone:  202-393-2100; FAX:  202-393-2134; Legislative
Hotline: 202-783-HOME; Order line:  800-225-4008; Internet Site:
http://www.frc.org.  Suggested annual donation for <b>Ed
Facts</b>: $25.</i>
</font><p>
